<FIRST>r a AM-NightStalker     09-28 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Night Stalker,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Ends Day Without Verdict on Sentence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The jury that convicted ``Night Stalker''
Richard Ramirez of 13 murders and 30 felonies spent a full day
deliberating on his punishment Thursday without reaching a decision.
   The panel must decide whether to recommend the death penalty or
life imprisonment without possibility of parole for Ramirez, 29, of
El Paso, Tex.
   The jurors, who have spent over a year on the ``Night Stalker''
case, were urged by a prosecutor to give Ramirez death as
punishment for his crimes.
   But a defense attorney asked for life, saying that even if
Ramirez was possessed by the devil, as some claim, he deserves
mercy.
   ``Richard Ramirez ... has no claim to your kindness,'' attorney
Ray Clark Clark said in his closing argument Wednesday. ``But if
you give him kindness, then that's what mercy is.''
   The prosecutor, Deputy District Attorney P. Philip Halpin, urged
that jurors recommend death in the gas chamber for Ramirez, a man
he described as ``a miserable human being'' who killed for self
gratification.
   The jury's decision is a recommendation. Superior Court Judge
Michael Tynan has the final say on sentencing. He has the option of
reducing a death penalty recommendation to life, but cannot
increase a life without parole verdict to death.
   The serial murderer still faces trial in San Francisco for a
``Night Stalker'' murder and in Santa Ana for the attempted murder
of a Mission Viejo couple.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
