<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Gorbachev     09-28 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Gorbachev,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet President To Visit Japan in 1991</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev will visit Japan in 1991,
becoming the first Soviet leader ever to visit this country, a
Foreign Ministry official said today.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Soviet
Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze informed his Japanese
counterpart Taro Nakayama of Gorbachev's intention in a meeting at
the Soviet mission to the United Nations in New York on Wednesday.
   Shevardnadze also told Nakayama that he hopes to visit Tokyo in
mid-March and invited Nakayama to visit Moscow afterwards, the
official said.
   To date, four Japanese prime ministers have visited Moscow, but
no Soviet leaders has ever visited Tokyo.
   Japan has repeatedly requested the Soviet Union to send its top
leader to Japan to improve relations.
   The Tokyo government hopes a visit by a Soviet leader would help
resolve the territorial dispute over the ``Northern Territories,''
a group of small islands off northern Japan claimed by Japan but
occupied by the Soviet Union.
   The two countries began long-stalled talks on a peace treaty
earlier this year, but the territorial issue remains the largest
stumbling block.
</TEXT>
