<FIRST>r i PM-Duarte     09-28 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Duarte,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Talks with Ailing Duarte</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President George Bush has
telephoned ex-president Jose Napoleon Duarte to inquire about the
health of the former leader, who is dying of liver cancer, Duarte's
son said.
   ``They talked for about 10 minutes, as old friends,'' Alejandro
Duarte said by telephone of Wednesday's conversation. ``President
Bush asked him about his health, how he was feeling.''
   Alejandro said his father, who nearly died last week from
pneumonia, was out of bed, lucid and feeling well during the
morning, when Bush called.
   ``But this afternoon he has been in acute pain, in the area of
his liver, from the cancer,'' he said.
   Doctors sedated the former president, who was in bed late
Wednesday receiving both oxygen and intravenous feeding, said
Alejandro.
   ``He is still not completely recovered from the pneumonia,'' he
said.
   Duarte's doctors have said that, as soon as the former president
is well enough to travel, he will fly to Washington for analysis
and treatment at Walter Reed Army Medical Center, where his cancer
was diagnosed in June 1988.
   Alejandro said Bush expressed the desire to visit with Duarte
when the ailing leader travels to Washington.
