<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 0208EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-LebanonRefugees     09-28 0713</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon Refugees,0735</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cease-Fire Does Not Persuade Many Lebanese to Return Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN MARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cease-fire in Lebanon has sent
thousands of refugees streaming back home, but Tony Raphael and
many others are turning their backs on their ravaged homeland and
planning new lives elsewhere.
   ``I don't believe in it,'' the 26-year old Maronite Catholic
said as he waited for a Canadian visa in Cyprus. ``It's always like
this, one cease-fire after another. It's been going on for 14
years. I don't want another 14 years.''
   Tens of thousands of Lebanese, most of them Christians, have
made the hazardous 100-mile trip to Cyprus since fighting broke out
in March between Syrian and Christian forces in Lebanon. Some came
seeking visas to other countries, others to sit out the fighting.
   About 1 million refugees have returned to Beirut since a
cease-fire Sept. 22. Raphael's parents are among those who plan to
go back home.
   ``I told them, `You want to go back? You're crazy!''' said
Raphael, who lived in Beirut. ``I swore last time I got off the
boat, I'm not going back.''
   Cyprus government spokesman Akis Fantis said Wednesday there
were 11,000 Lebanese in Cyprus, which often has been a sanctuary
during periods of intense fighting in Lebanon.
   But relief officials said the number just before the cease-fire
was at least 30,000.
   In the latest exodus, most of the Christian refugees made the
risky three-hour journey on a 330-seat hydrofoil, the Santa Maria,
from Jounieh north of Beirut to Larnaca on the southern Cyprus
coast.
   For much of the last six months, the hydrofoil, often shelled by
the Syrians, was the Christians' only link to the outside world
from their enclave north of Beirut.
   Ghada Nasser, 26, was one who fled on the Santa Maria. The last
straw for her was the fear that an artillery barrage would mar her
wedding reception, as happened during a friend's wedding.
   ``Shells started falling when they were having the reception.
Boom! Boom!'' she said. ``That was it, and the bride was crying.''
   Mrs. Nasser came to Cyprus, was married in Nicosia in a civil
ceremony and prepared to start a new life with her Jordanian
husband in Kuwait.
   Bassel Abou Jaoudeh, 19, ran an electronics repair shop part
time while studying at a college in Christian east Beirut. The
Syrian barrages ended that.
   ``My house was destroyed. My shop was destroyed. The college
closed and there was no way to continue my studies,'' said Jaoudeh,
a Maronite who has just received a Canadian visa after a four-month
wait.
   On the eve of his departure for Canada and a new life, he spoke
in the dining room of a 15th-century monastery nestled in the heart
of the bustling southeastern tourist resort of Ayia Napa.
   The monastery, run by the Middle East Council of Churches as a
conference center, has become a haven for Lebanese who arrive in
Cyprus penniless or have difficulty finding shelter.
   The Rev. Riad Jarjour, who runs the center, helps dozens of
Lebanese who turn up on his doorstep seeking assistance with money,
lodging or food.
   The exodus from Lebanon to Cyprus over the last six months was
``unlike any time before,'' said Jarjour. Hotels and furnished
apartments were crammed with refugees.
   Jarjour stressed that his center does not encourage people to
emigrate. ``We want them to stay, to live in unity in their own
country.''
   But many Lebanese are not convinced.
   Every weekday, dozens line up at the U.S. Embassy in Nicosia,
staying up all night for visa interviews the next morning.
   An embassy spokesman said consular officers interview 30 to 40
applicants a day. Only a few dozen are allowed to wait in line.
Security guards turn away as many as 100 others, asking them to
come back the next day.
   Canada had to open an immigration office in Nicosia to cope with
the flood of applicants. The emigration process for the United
States, Canada and other countries takes months. But for the
war-weary Lebanese, it's worth the wait.
   ``Anything's better than sitting in Lebanon, even if it's just
sitting here and not doing anything. Here there are no shells
falling on you,'' said 24-year-old Zena Touma.
</TEXT>
