<FIRST>u a AM-ChemicalFire 1stLd-Writethru a0416 09-28 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chemical Fire, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0416,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chemical Plant Fire Forces Evacuations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to UPDATE with fire under control.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The threat of toxic fumes from a fire raging
out of control at a chemical plant Wednesday night forced the
evacuation of more than 600 homes and shut down Amtrak's Northeast
Corridor.
   A fire dispatcher said the first alarm in North Philadelphia was
reported at 8:23 p.m. By midnight, the fire was under control. No
injuries were reported.
   ``We're very worried about it because of the volatility of the
chemicals,'' Fire Commissioner Roger Ulshafer said.
   He said the chemicals included benzene, styrene, hydrochloric
acid, benzyl-peroxide, sulfuric acid, caustic soda, bromine,
propylene dichloride and di-vinyl benzine.
   ``They are very flammable, explosive and also several of those
are very toxic,'' the commissioner said.
   Witnesses said the 500-foot building was almost completely
engulfed in flames minutes after the fire broke out, and it
appeared to be destroyed as the fire raged. Some of the 200
firefighters on the scene said they were worried about the walls
collapsing.
   The evacuees were taken to three nearby churches.
   ``We're fortunate that most of the products of combustion went
straight up into the air. However, every once in a while there's a
wind change and they blow to the south. That's the reason for the
evacuation,'' Ulshafer said.
   Four Amtrak tracks on the Northeast Corridor near the factory
were shut down from 8:45 p.m. until 10:05 p.m., when two tracks
were re-opened, according to railroad spokesman John Jacobsen.
   ``We had six northbound trains and three southbound trains
holding in different parts of Philadelphia,'' Jacobsen said soon
after partial service was restored. ``Two tracks is all we need,
and we should be back to normal.''
   Local trains that also use the Amtrak line were stopped. The
Southeastern Pennsylvania Transportation Authority arranged for
shuttle bus service for two inbound trains and delayed several
outbound ones.
   The burning building was owned by the Purolite Chemical Co., a
water-purification business, but employees said the second floor
was rented to Sterling Hobbies, a company that makes balsa model
airplanes.
   The Purolite employees said they smelled an odor like gasoline
and looked up to see flames.
</TEXT>
