<FIRST>r p AM-Mason-Mayoral     09-28 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mason-Mayoral,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Comic Pulls Out of Giuliani Campaign After Dinkins Remark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comic Jackie Mason will no longer campaign for
Republican mayoral candidate Rudolph Giuliani after commenting that
Democratic candidate David Dinkins looks like ``a black model
without a job.''
   ``Mason is withdrawing from the campaign because he didn't want
this matter to deflect from the importance of the campaign,'' said
Charles Perkins, a Giuliani spokesman.
   Mason told reporters he meant nothing by the remark, published
Wednesday in The Village Voice.
   ``I care more for the black people than any other person in the
country,'' Mason said. ``I hate bigots.''
   Dinkins said he was ``not particularly'' offended by the remark.
``I can say that that kind of comment is not helpful to our city,''
he said.
   Giuliani was ``troubled'' by Mason's comment, Perkins said.
   The Voice, a weekly newspaper in New York, also quoted Mason as
saying: ``There is a sick Jewish problem of voting for a black man
no matter how unfit he is for the job. ... Jews are sick with
complexes.''
   Mason later called that comment ``stupid,'' but not before Mayor
Edward I. Koch and several Jewish groups denounced the remark as
offensive. Dinkins defeated Koch in the Democratic primary.
   Mason's attorney, Raoul Felder, said the comic's remarks were
taken out of context by the Voice and the interview was off the
record. Mason said he would file a $25 million libel lawsuit
against the Voice on Thursday ``for a vicious attack on the
goodness of my name.''
   Jonathan Larsen, editor-in-chief of the Voice, said the paper
would ``reserve comment until we actually see the suit. But we
stand behind the story.'' He denied Mason's comments were taken out
of context and made off the record.
</TEXT>
