<FIRST>r i PM-Ecuador     09-28 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ecuador,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Of Emergency Declared To End Oil Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Rodrigo Borja imposed a national
state of emergency and put petroleum installations under military
control after oil workers went on strike.
   Workers at the U.S.-owned Texaco Inc. walked off the job early
Wednesday demanding severance pay. The action came just days before
the company is to turn its operations over to the government.
   ``A state of emergency is declared and constitutional guarantees
are suspended,'' Borja said in a decree signed late Wednesday.
   Troops were sent to petroleum installations controlled by Texaco
and the state-owned oil company, PetroEcuador. Together, the
companies produce 90 percent of the country's daily oil output of
300,000 barrels.
   Luis Roman, president of PetroEcuador, said the move was to
prevent sabotage and to ``protect national interests.''
   Besides being involved in oil exploration and drilling
operations, Texaco runs the 300 mile-long Trans-Ecuador pipeline,
which transports oil from Ecuador's jungle fields to the coast.
   Texaco spokesman Guillermo Cevallos said the strike shut down
the oil fields, the pipeline, ship-loading facilities and company
offices. Oil exports _60 percent of Ecuador's export earnings _
were paralyzed, he said.
   Government spokesman Gonzalo Ortiz said oil reserves would cover
Ecuador's need of 120,000 barrels daily for the time being.
   The 170 striking Texaco workers want severance pay from the
company, which has agreed to turn over its operations to the state
on Oct. 1. It was not immediately clear how much compensation the
workers were demanding.
   The contract between the government and Texaco expired in March
1986, and the government decided in September last year to take
over the company's operations.
</TEXT>
