<HEAD>PM-PA-Brokers Fined,280</HEAD>
<HEAD>Philly Brokerage Suspended Over Penny Stock Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Philadelphia brokerage has been fined
$50,000 and suspended from the National Association of Securities
Dealers following accusations of manipulating the price of a
publicly traded stock.
   The NASD said Wednesday the action was part of a crackdown on
fraud and abusive sales practices in the penny-stock market.
   Bailey, Martin &amp; Appel Inc. was accused of violating the NASD's
anti-fraud provisions by artificially increasing the price of stock
for Northgate Industries Inc., a shell corporation with no assets.
   The firm neither admitted nor denied the allegations. It settled
the case by paying the fine and agreeing to the suspension.
   Two of the firm's owners, who also were suspended from the
association, denied any wrongdoing. They said they had agreed to
settle the case to prevent a long, costly legal fight.
   ``We feel they've made an enormous mountain out of a molehill,''
said Donald Bailey, chairman of BMA Group Ltd., the holding company
that owns Bailey Martin.
   Howard M. Appel, a co-owner of the firm, said the sales involved
only 30 clients and none had complained to the association, which
regulates over-the-counter stocks.
   The association's market-surveillance committee filed a
complaint in July stating that Bailey Martin had acquired 70
percent of Northgate's stock at 20 cents per share shortly before
it merged with Starcom Entertainment International Inc., a company
with no operating history or revenues.
   After the merger, the brokerage increased the price of the stock
to $3 per share _ an increase of 1,400 percent _ by purchasing and
selling shares at higher prices despite ``limited wholesale and
retail demand for the stock,'' the complaint said.
</TEXT>
