<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     09-28 0880</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,870</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ag Committee Chairman Vows Farm Bill By Spring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House Agriculture
Committee says he expects to see a 1990 farm bill on President
Bush's desk next spring, with or without an administration
blueprint.
   Rep. Kika de la Garza, D-Texas, said Wednesday the 1990 farm
bill will not be held up so trade negotiations can proceed ``in
Geneva or any other place.''
   De la Garza reacted to recent comments by Agriculture Secretary
Clayton Yeutter who has indicated that only minor work might be
necessary on current farm law until substantive progress is made in
the Uruguay Round of talks under the General Agreement on Tariffs
and Trade.
   The current Food Security Act of 1985 will expire at the end of
next year, and Congress is just getting started on a 1990 bill.
   Much of the nuts and bolts of the legislation will bear directly
or indirectly on GATT trade policies and whether the United States
will be successful in its bid to scale back _ and eventually
eliminate _ trade barriers and subsidies that distort agricultural
trade.
   Yeutter said earlier this week in Minneapolis, Minn., that he
expected only minor changes in the commodity portions of the 1985
farm law and that major modification could come in 1991 after GATT
negotiations are completed.
   De la Garza said it is up to Congress to legislate and decide
how long a farm law will be in effect.
   ``The Congress will decide whether or not to accept or reject
any agreement made by the administration in Geneva or any other
place,'' he said in a statement.
   ``We will cooperate to the extent possible with the
administration, but it is my firm intention to continue with our
stated goal of concluding the most extensive set of farm bill
hearings in history by the end of this calendar year,'' de la Garza
added.
   Further, he said, ``it is my intention to begin the markup of a
farm bill early in 1990,'' with or without a proposal by the Bush
administration.
   Yeutter has said he expects the administration to send its 1990
farm bill to Congress by the end of this year.
   De la Garza said he wants to have a five-year farm bill
completed and on the president's desk by the end of May.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A National Farmers Union official says
President Bush's proposal to reduce the capital gains tax rate
would attract many non-farmers into agricultural investment.
   Mike Dunn, NFU legislative director, said Wednesday that his
organization's policy is ``opposed to rescinding capital gains''
although there are some inequities in the current law.
   Dunn said the current law puts an unfair load on some farmers,
primarily those who have had to restructure loans as provided by
the 1987 Farm Credit Act. In some cases, he said, high capital
gains taxes offset any write-off benefit that might be extended by
lenders.
   When that happens, the borrower can be pushed into bankruptcy or
liquidation to settle the debt.
   The Bush proposal, however, includes some worrisome provisions
that could be attractive to outside investors _ a common practice
before Congress overhauled the tax structure three years ago, Dunn
said.
   ``We would see (the capital gains proposal) as an excuse for
absentee landlords to get back into agriculture,'' he said.
   The American Farm Bureau Federation, on the other hand, has
applauded the recent House Ways and Means Committee approval of
reduced capital gains taxes. It would help ``mom-and-pop type''
farmers, not just rich people, said federation president Dean
Kleckner.
   But analyst Chuck Hassebrook of the Center For Rural Affairs,
Walthill, Neb., noted the USDA's own economists had reported the
1986 Tax Reform Act tightened up the investment loopholes and that
``tax breaks became more progressive'' in agriculture.
   In other words, he said in a telephone interview, the
higher-income farmers paid a larger proportion of the tax load as a
result of the 1986 reform.
   With a reduction in capital gains, he said, the impact would be
to shift tax burdens off the highest-income farmers.
   ``If we raise the capital gains exemption, we'll again turn
farmland and breeding stock into tax shelter investments,''
Hassebrook said.
   By doing that, livestock herds could increase, thus boosting the
supply of meat and milk and depressing prices that farmers are
paid, he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says preliminary
payments totaling $248 million are going out to states as their
share of national forest sales receipts are collected this fiscal
year.
   F. Dale Robertson, chief of the Forest Service, said Wednesday
total state shares for the fiscal year than ends Sept. 30 are
expected to be more than $331 million, up from $318 million last
year.
   By law, 25 percent of the revenues collected by the USDA agency
for the sale of timber and other use of national forest resources
must be returned to the states where the forests are located. The
states are required to use the money for schools and roads.
   The 10 largest preliminary payments will go to Oregon, $118
million; California, $39 million; Washington, $33 million; Idaho,
$7 million; Arkansas, $6.2 million; Montana, $5.4 million; Arizona,
$5.3 million; Alaska, $3.2 million; Pennsylvania, $2.8 million; and
Mississippi, $2.6 million.
</TEXT>
