<DOCNO> AP890928-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 0357EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-TVOlympics     09-28 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-TV Olympics,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authors Say U.S. Paying Unfair Share for Olympic Coverage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two researchers say the financial setup of the
Olympic Games is a ``travesty'' that demands enormous sums from the
American networks while giving sports coverage to other nations at
cut rates.
   Those other countries can turn their savings into big subsidies
for their athletes, the authors contend in their study, ``Fool's
Gold: How America Pays to Lose in the Olympics.''
   NBC paid $300 million for the rights to the 1988 Summer Olympics
in Seoul and needed 5,000 commercials in 179 hours of air time to
recover its costs, Robert Z. Lawrence and Jeffrey D. Pellegrom note
in the study for the Brookings Institution.
   Even then, the network later returned $70 million to advertisers
because of low ratings, they say in the fall issue of The Brookings
Review.
   ABC paid $309 million bid for the U.S. rights to the 1988 Winter
Olympics in Calgary and lost some $65 million when expenses
exceeded advertising revenue.
   Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union, meanwhile, paid only $3
million combined to get rights to the Seoul Games. Western Europe,
negotiating through a single body, paid just $5.7 million total for
the Calgary rights.
   The study says that after each competing nation receives a share
of the TV monies from Olympics organizers, the Soviet Union and
East Germany may be getting more back than they spend on TV rights.
   The East Bloc nations may then lavish funds on their athletes.
   ``The funding setup for the Olympics is a travesty,'' the
authors say.
   ``We pay more than our fair share for the games, we have to put
up with an excessive number of commercials to see them, and our
athletes receive little of the money we do pay,'' they say.
   The IOC divides the money between the host city, judges and
officials, media centers, the national Olympic committees and the
IOC itself.
   The U.S. Olympic Committee got 2.5 percent of the $609 million
ABC and NBC paid for the summer and winter games in 1988, the study
says. USOC's share for the 1992 games, for which CBS and NBC are
paying $644 million, will be 10 percent.
   Lawrence and Pellegrom suggest the U.S. government and the U.S.
Olympic Committee form a joint entity that would auction the U.S.
television rights. That group then would negotiate for U.S. TV
rights with the IOC, as other nations do.
   Presuming the auction amount is higher than what is finally paid
to the IOC, the excess money could be used to support athletes, the
authors say.
   Congress might have to grant the networks an antitrust exemption
for them to bid together.
   CBS on Wednesday refused comment on the article, and NBC
officials did not return a call seeking reaction.
   Dennis Swanson, president of ABC Sports, said ``We have no
response on any proposals at this time.''
   One network official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
he did not see how a government-USOC body could make substantial
changes. Also, the official said, ``We don't think it is the burden
of the networks to finance the training of the athletes.''
   He denied the networks were overbidding.
   ``When a network bids on a rights package ... they take a look
at what its value is. Obviously, networks aren't going to be
spending money that they can't justify.''
   Lawrence and Pellegrom acknowledge most foreign TV networks are
non-commercial and public owned and can't afford huge fees, but say
there are an increasing number of commercial networks and the
American networks no longer should have to foot the Olympics bill.
   Lawrence is a senior fellow in economic studies at the Brookings
Institution, a Washington think tank. Pellegrom is a research
assistant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890928-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 0402EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-NuclearPlants     09-28 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Plants,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Watkins, in Reversal, Orders Fuller Testing of Nuclear Reactors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Additional safety tests ordered on the three
Savannah River reactors that produce a gas needed for nuclear
warheads could lead to further delays in restarting the idled
reactors.
   The order announced Wednesday by Energy Secretary James D.
Watkins marked a switch from his earlier position that the tests
need not be completed before restarting the reactors, which have
been plagued by various mechanical problems.
   In a related development, Watkins confirmed the department was
considering a possible two-year delay in underground testing at
Yucca Mountain, a Nevada desert site being studied for use as the
first permanent dump for nuclear waste.
   The Savannah River complex, near Aiken, S.C., is the nation's
only source of tritium, a radioactive gas used to boost the
explosive power of nuclear warheads. All three reactors have been
shut down for more than a year for repairs.
   Watkins made no mention of a possible restart delay. His
spokeswoman, Christina Sankey, said later it was ``too early to
tell'' whether a delay was likely.
   Watkins announced Sept. 7 that the first of the three Savannah
River reactors would begin low-power testing late next summer and
would start production by the end of 1990. He ordered ultrasonic
testing of the reactor vessels to begin immediately, but he did not
require completion of the tests before restart.
   Ms. Sankey said Watkins changed his mind about the testing after
some of his own advisers said it should be completed in all three
reactors before any one is restarted.
   The timing of a Savannah River restart is viewed by the Bush
administration as critical because of dwindling supplies of the
gas. Tritium decays relatively rapidly and therefore must be
replenished to keep nuclear weapons fully operational.
   The Savannah River reactors have had a history of cracks and
leaks in the primary cooling system pipes as well as flaws in the
backup cooling systems. A leak from a crack in the vessel of
another Savannah River reactor, known as C reactor, was discovered
in 1984. That led to its permanent shutdown a year later.
   Watkins also announced that ultrasonic testing that began
recently on the P reactor vessel at Savannah River had discovered
``a potential indication'' of a crack ``in excess of nine inches''
in the area of a welded seam. He said the finding is still being
studied and that further tests are being performed on the P reactor.
   He said the significance of the problem had not yet been
determined, although Ms. Sankey said later, ``We're quite confident
there is no crack'' in the vessel.
   Ms. Sankey said there was ``no technical reason'' to condition a
K reactor restart on completion of the ultrasonic testing, but that
Watkins chose to impose the condition in order to ``instill greater
public confidence in the restart program.''
   In ultrasonic testing, sound waves are bounced off the reactor
vessel, and any abnormalities show up as breaks in the waves.
   Restarting the Savannah River reactors and completing a
suitability study of the Yucca Mountain, Nev., waste dump site are
two of Watkins' highest priorities.
   In a letter to Sen. Richard H. Bryan, D-Nev., on Tuesday,
Watkins said a senior department official had suggested a delay in
underground testing at Yucca Mountain in order to more intensely
study surface-level features that could disqualify the site.
   Watkins stressed ``no decisions have been made'' on the matter.
   The underground work had been scheduled to start earlier this
year but has been held up by Nevada's refusal to grant the needed
environmental permits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890928-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 0227EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ObsceneArt     09-28 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obscene Art,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators, Representatives Dicker Over Helms' Obscene Art Amendment</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Talks resume 10 a.m. EDT, lead planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional liberals and conservatives are
seeking middle ground on a measure barring federal grants for art
considered obscene, but the ban's author says he won't let them
``gut'' his proposal without a fight.
   House-Senate negotiators planned today to discuss Senate-passed
legislation by Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., barring federal assistance
for ``obscene or indecent'' art. It also forbids government backing
of materials that offend people because of their race, ethnic
background, religion, age or handicap.
   ``We're trying to work it out now,'' Rep. Sidney Yates, D-Ill.,
a liberal opposed to the Helms amendment, said after the two sides
debated the issue briefly Wednesday. ``I recognize this is a matter
that has provided controversy for decades and for centuries.''
   Helms said the art he opposes ``is the promotion of
homosexuality, and as long as I have breath in me, the American
taxpayer isn't going to be forced to subsidize this kind of
garbage.''
   The provision is part of a Senate measure providing $10.9
billion for federal land and cultural programs for the 1990 fiscal
year, which begins Sunday. The House's $11.5 billion version
includes no such language.
   Negotiators faced other issues, too. The Senate measure contains
new reporting requirements for lobbyists that the House bill lacks.
The Senate _ not the House _ also allows large tracts of federally
owned forest in the Northwest to be felled by timber companies and
bars environmentalists from using legal action to block some of the
cutting.
   The most intense public reaction has been to the Helms
amendment, which pits worries about government censorship against
concerns that tax dollars should not spent on offensive work.
   Helms, not among the bargainers, told a reporter the negotiators
are ``going to gut'' his proposal. He said he might force the
Senate to vote ``three or four times before we're through'' on
whether to reject a compromise and restore his original proposal.
   Sen. James McClure, R-Idaho, a conservative who defended Helms'
provision, said he has unsuccessfully sought an alternative. He
told reporters the Helms measure leaves unclear what should be
considered obscene or offensive.
   But he said, ``I still haven't found language which is an
adequate substitute.''
   McClure said a study is needed of the grant-making process used
by the National Endowment for the Arts. The endowment has come
under fire for spending $45,000 on two controversial exhibitions _
one including a photograph by Andres Serrano of a Christ figure in
a jar of urine, and the other including Robert Mapplethorpe
photographs depicting homosexual acts and erotic poses by children.
   Yates said he was considering offering guidelines, similar to
Supreme Court rulings, permitting federal aid to art that attains
certain artistic, scholarly or other standards.
   He also discussed the possibility of giving more responsibility
to top officials of the endowment. He said the endowment granted
money for the Serrano show before the artist produced his work, and
for the Mapplethorpe exhibition without seeing all of the
photographs in advance.
   The Senate adopted the Helms amendment with almost no debate on
a July 26 voice vote. On Sept. 13, the House rejected 264-153 an
attempt by conservatives to accept the Helms amendment.
   The House voted July 12 to cut a symbolic $45,000 from the
endowment's $171.4 million budget to protest the controversial
grants, but lawmakers rejected conservative efforts to eliminate or
severely slash the endowment's budget.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
