<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-Drugs     09-28 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Drugs,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Funds for Drug War, Testing of Transport Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposal to test millions of transportation
workers for drug and alcohol use is gaining in Congress along with
the Senate-approved $9.4 billion compromise to finance the war
against drugs.
   ``The war within our borders is a more terrifying and insidious
threat than any war on foreign shores _ so we must not be timid,''
Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., said Wednesday as the Senate approved
the drug plan 97-2.
   ``We're not going to whip this problem in one year, three years
or four years. Let's find out what works,'' added Senate Minority
Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan. ``We're going to save a generation if we
can. It may take a generation to do it.''
   The Senate added the drug plan to an $11.9 billion bill for
transportation programs in the fiscal year starting Oct. 1, and
included some other drug-related provisions, including testing for
transport workers.
   The measure also bans smoking on all domestic airline flights.
Current law bans smoking on flights of two hours or less, and the
total ban was added last week over the objections of tobacco-state
senators.
   The Senate approved the transportation bill 99-0 and sent it to
a House-Senate conference committee to resolve differences with a
House-passed version.
   The anti-drug compromise was worked out by the White House and
senators of both parties began after Democrats sought to add $2.2
billion to the $7.9 billion plan outlined by President Bush in a
nationally televised Sept. 5 speech.
   Democrats said Bush's funding for prevention and treatment was
inadequate.
   The final compromise includes the original $7.9 billion plus
$400 million for crime-fighting programs not directly related to
drugs, $200 million for juvenile justice, $800 million for
prevention and treatment and $100 million for law enforcement. The
additional money would come from a 0.43 cut in federal spending.
   The Senate approved the transportation drug and alcohol testing
plan, sponsored by Sen. John C. Danforth, D-Mo., on a voice vote
with no opposition.
   It would cover an estimated 125,000 airline and Federal Aviation
Administration workers, 172,000 railroad employees and 3 million
motor carrier workers, such as bus and truck drivers.
   Private industries would be required to pay for random,
pre-employment tests as well as tests ordered for cause or
following accidents. The Transportation Department could also order
periodic testing.
   ``The need for this legislation is obvious,'' Danforth said.
Since an Amtrak-Conrail collision at Chase, Md., three years ago
that killed 16, ``there has been an average of one train wreck
every 10 days in which testing has subsequently disclosed drug or
alcohol abuse,'' he said.
   A measure passed by the House in July covers only the rail
industry and would bar the firing of employees merely because they
tested positive. The Senate version would leave that decision to
the employer.
   The transportation bill includes $11.9 billion in new spending
plus $15.9 billion from previously collected taxes. It calls for
$12.2 billion for highway projects, $7.3 billion for aviation
programs and $3 billion for mass transit assistance.
   Another measure attached to the transportation bill on a voice
vote would earmark $50 million of the money in the drug package for
drug treatment and aid for pregnant women, new mothers and their
babies who have drug problems.
   Voting against the drug funding plan were Republicans Jake Garn
of Utah and Steve Symms of Idaho. Sen. James Sasser, D-Tenn., did
not vote.
   Garn issued a statement saying the ``problem with the drug bill
is that it essentially was the product of a bidding war between the
administration and Congress over who is going to spend the most on
drugs.''
   He said the cuts it envisions would hurt key programs, adding,
``We are not going to solve the drug problem by just throwing money
at it.''
</TEXT>
