<FIRST>r a PM-FDR'sSummit     09-28 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FDR's Summit,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Last Summit of Governors Was Ill-prepared Affair</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Education Summit Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTESVILLE, VA. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   However history judges the education
summit, one thing is certain: George Bush came better prepared than
Franklin Roosevelt did the last time a president convened the
nation's governors.
   That was in March 1933 when FDR summoned the governors to the
White House two days after his inauguration to discuss unemployment
benefits, taxes and other issues in the midst of the Depression.
   Roosevelt, the former governor of New York, tendered the
invitation to fellow governors a month before his March 4 swearing
in.
   But the tasks of getting his grips on the reins of government
while preparing emergency decrees to deal with a run on the
nation's banks left Roosevelt with little time for the governors.
   As FDR aide Rexford G. Tugwell later wrote, ``he was caught in
such a tangle of events that when he was wheeled into the East Room
... and faced the assembly of state executives, he had no prepared
address and was not ready to discuss the several matters mentioned
in his invitation.''
   The gathering took place the same morning the new Democratic
administration had promulgated a 1 a.m. decree closing the nation's
banks _ Roosevelt's famous bank ``holiday.''
   By Roosevelt's own account in his public papers, ``There simply
was not enough time in which to do all the things which had to be
done.''
   Speaking extemporaneously to the 25 governors and
representatives of a dozen others who had answered his call,
Roosevelt told of his plans to restore stability to the banking
system and ``prevent the withdrawal of any further gold and
currency.''
   The governors gave the distracted president a unanimous,
bipartisan show of support. They adopted a resolution expressing
their confidence in Roosevelt and urging both Congress and the
American people to back his efforts to restore ``banking and
economic stability.''
   Tugwell said the summit gave Roosevelt ``a chance to reassure
them concerning federal aid and to show them that a firm hand was
on the wheel. They responded.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
