<FIRST>r a PM-Bush-ChineseStudents     09-28 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Chinese Students,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Students Ask Bush to Get Tough With China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Education Summit Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese students are using the
education summit to prod President Bush to take a tougher line with
the government in Beijing.
   Organizers said Chinese students from more than 70 American
universities have endorsed a nine-page memorandum expressing
``disappointment'' with Bush's stance since the June 4 massacre in
Tiananmen Square.
   The appeal, spearheaded by the Chinese Student and Scholars
Society at the University of Virginia, said, ``The Chinese
democratic movement is now in a very difficult situation.''
   It urged Bush ``to take a firm stand on the side of the Chinese
people and to take appropriate measures to push the Chinese
government toward democratization.''
   ``Since the massive persecution in China is still going on, we
advise the United States not to eagerly seek improved elations with
the communist regime at this time,'' the memo says.
   The students support investments in China's private sector, but
urged the U.S. government ``to do nothing that would provide
financial and economic support for China's repressive ruling
clique.''
   Bush cut off military sales, withdrew U.S. support for loans to
China by international lending institutions and barred high-level
contacts after the Chinese government crushed the pro-democracy
demonstrations with tanks and troops.
   Quingsong Zhang, a spokesman for the University of Virginia
group, said the memo will be sent to Congress and the State
Department and will be given to the White House staff at the
education summit.
   The memo says the United States faces a ``crucial time of
decision. Will (it) repeat policies of the past by adhering to the
unpopular communist government and alienating the Chinese people,
or will it sacrifice short-term interests by standing with the
Chinese democratic movement and gaining a long-term friendship with
the people of China?''
   ``We firmly believe that the current regime will not last long.
We hope that by the end of the 20th century, a new, open and
democratic government will be established in China,'' it said.
</TEXT>
