<FIRST>r a PM-EducationSummit-Issues     09-28 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Education Summit-Issues,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governors Want Less Red Tape, More Accountability</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Education Summit, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Governors meeting with President
Bush to find cures for the nation's education ills are pressing the
case for less federal red tape, more accountability and a greater
commitment to help youngsters at the earliest age.
   ``If you want a slogan, it's exchange red tape for results,''
Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton told reporters Wednesday evening.
   Citing an example of federal rules that slow reform, Clinton
said current regulations forbid students in evening adult classes
from using computers bought for disabled children with federal
dollars.
   In urging Bush to give the states more flexibility, New Mexico
Gov. Garrey Carruthers said: ``Let us do it our own way. We will
demonstrate that we're doing it better.''
   Bush, for his part, responded to the call for deregulation with
a challenge for more specifics on how states will prove they are
getting results with less regulation.
   Governors met in three closed-door sessions Wednesday with Bush
and his Cabinet, discussing how to revitalize the teaching
profession, how to improve the learning environment, and who should
be in charge of governing schools.
   Clinton and other governors indicated that they hoped the summit
sessions will produce the raw material to develop concrete national
reform goals, possibly as early as the February meeting of the
National Governors' Association.
   Clinton said, ``The federal funding question is not the major
issue for this summit,'' although some governors have said they
want the federal government to boost its share of school spending.
   Federal drug czar William Bennett, who headed the education
department during the Reagan administration, said the exchanges
between governors and administration officials were sometimes
``feisty,'' especially when several questioned the lag in federal
education spending compared with defense.
   The discussion, Bennett said, was marked by ``standard
Democratic pap, Republican pap, with occasional outbursts of
candor.''
   On early childhood programs, the governors repeated their call
for full funding of federal programs such as Head Start. But
neither Bush nor anyone in his administration gave a clear signal
that they were ready to adopt full funding as a goal.
   ``It is a good program, it works, but it is not available except
to about 27 percent of the (eligible) students,'' complained
Colorado Gov. Roy Romer, a Democrat.
   Pennsylvania Gov. Robert P. Casey, a Democrat, said one of his
concerns is accountability in education, saying efforts to improve
schools need objective criteria to measure their success.
   Another session on how to revitalize the teaching profession
centered on, among other issues, how to recruit more minority
youngsters, but ``with a recognition that for a long time to come
minority students will be taught mainly by white teachers,'' said
Washington Gov. Booth Gardner, co-chair of that group.
   A two-page memo summarizing objectives for the summit by the NGA
outlined seven possible national performance goals, including:
   _All preschool-age children be ready for first grade by the year
2000.
   _Student achievement levels ``will rise to internationally
competitive levels,especially in math and science.''
   _``Disparities in achievement levels of students of different
races and economic backgrounds will be dramatically reduced.''
   _The number of students going on to college or other higher
education will be dramatically increased.
   _Adult illiteracy be ``virtually eliminated.''
   _Schools will have well-trained teachers and the technology to
be competitive.
   The memo proposed that once goals are set and ways are found to
achieve them, ``we should move to a report card issued every year
on the efforts of students, schools, the states, and the federal
government.''
   The memo suggested that governors urge Bush to get each member
of his cabinet to target federal resources to ten of the largest
and most troubled districts and ``50 to 100 poor rural districts''
to reduce racial and economic disparities in educational
opportunities.
   States, for their part, should agree to ``restructure the
education system in each state,'' work with the federal government
to reduce losses in the student loan program, and work toward
drug-free schools, the memo said.
</TEXT>
