<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     09-28 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dingell Unhappy with FDA Review</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A powerful congressmen who has been critical
of the Food and Drug Administration has asked the agency to add to
its generic drug review those drugs with a narrow margin of safety,
including ones used to treat epilepsy.
   Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the House Energy and
Commerce investigations subcommittee, based his request on the 1988
recall of a generic version of an epilepsy drug.
   Pharmaceutical Basics Inc. of Denver recalled 50 million tablets
of generic carbamazepine because the tablets didn't dissolve
correctly. FDA documents released by Dingell show problems with the
drug became apparent after the company switched suppliers for its
raw ingredient.
   Dingell blames the FDA process for failing to assure the safety
and effectiveness of drugs like carbamazepine that have a narrow
margin of safety.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Suburban Travel Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twice as many Americans live in suburbs and
commute to suburban jobs as commute from suburban homes to jobs in
the cities, according to a new study of traffic congestion.
   The study, done by the Urban Land Institute, noted that
``although the downtowns of our major cities are generally the most
important single destination, they no longer are the dominant
location for jobs.''
   Release of the study prompted a warning from Francis B.
Francois, executive director of the American Association of Street,
Highway and Transportation Officials.
   He predicted that Americans will drive about 4 trillion miles in
2007, which would be double the amount of miles driven two years
ago.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___ ^Consumer Advocates, Insurers Join Forces</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Auto insurance companies and advocates of
better cars are joining together to push for a variety of
auto-related legislation, including mandated safety features and a
return to the 55 mph speed limit.
   Insurers hope safety improvements will reduce rising auto
insurance costs, said Gerald L. Maatman, president of Kemper
National Property and Casualty Cos., one of several major insurance
firms joining the coalition.
   The insurance industry has been criticized by consumer advocate
groups over the cost of premiums.
   Consumer advocate Ralph Nader, in a telephone interview, said
the insurance industry had taken a first step toward fulfilling
``its neglected responsibility in loss prevention.''
</TEXT>
