<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     09-28 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Stocks Up In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against the Japanese yen for the
fourth consecutive day Thursday, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's
key index rose to another high.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, gained 319.41 points, or 0.90 percent, closing at
35,689.98. It had lost 74.25 points Wednesday. The previous record
close was Tuesday's 35,444.82.
   The market's main barometer rebounded in a favorable reaction to
the yen's continued appreciation against the dollar, traders said.
   The dollar closed at 140.85 yen, down 0.50 yen from Wednesday's
141.35-yen finish. It opened at 140.70 yen and moved between 140.65
yen and 141.00 yen. The dollar now has fallen 4.15 yen in four
trading days.
   The dollar's low opening followed its overnight decline in New
York and on other European markets, caused by the third consecutive
day of central bank intervention to push the American currency
lower.
</TEXT>
