<FIRST>r a PM-Bush-Drugs     09-28 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Drugs,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>Word `Bush' Found on Packages of Cocaine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The names ``Bush'' or ``Bush I'' were found on
several packages of cocaine seized in a raid. Four Colombian men
were arrested.
   Officials said it was unclear whether the labels found on 19 of
the 93 packages of cocaine worth about $17 million were a derisive
reference to President Bush, who is aiding the crackdown on
Colombian drug lords.
   But they speculated on the possibility.
   ``The president has brought the issue to an issue of national
priority unlike the issue has ever been brought to that point
before,'' said Robert Stutman, special agent in charge of the Drug
Enforcement Administration office in New York.
   ``So if you're a businessman down there selling dope you've
clearly got to say this guy is a pain in the neck to us.''
   Stutman said the word ``Bush'' had been found on cocaine
packages several other times in the city this year, and that
authorities are checking to see if it had been found in drug raids
elsewhere.
   Police trailed a car to the home in Great Neck, Long Island,
after watching a drug pickup in the New York City borough of Queens.
   Police seized 210 pounds of cocaine. The four men were charged
with conspiracy to distribute cocaine, authorities said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
