<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     09-28 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Stocks Up In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against the Japanese yen for the
fourth consecutive day today, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's key
index rebounded to another new high.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which fell
74.25 points on Wednesday, shot up 319.41 points _ 0.90 percent _
on Wednesday, closing at 35,689.98. The previous record high
closing was 35,444.82 on Tuesday.
   Stock dealers said market players, especially institutional
investors, were reassured by the yen's recovery against the dollar
after last weekend's agreement among seven major industrial nations
to cooperate in stopping the dollar's recent rise.
   Trading was active, with first section volume estimated at 1
billion shares, the same as on Wednesday. Among gainers were steel,
chemical and electrical issues.
   In currency dealings, the dollar closed at 140.85 yen, down 0.50
yen from Wednesday's 141.35-yen finish. It opened at 140.70 yen and
moved between 140.65 yen and 141.00 yen. The dollar has fallen 4.15
yen in four days.
   After opening lower following a downswing on overseas markets
overnight, the U.S. currency moved little during Tokyo trading,
said Yoshitsugu Hanada, a trader with Mitsui Bank.
   ``The dollar's uptrend was halted by the concerted central bank
interventions that became especially powerful after the G-7 (Group
of Seven) meeting last weekend,'' he said. ``But the market expects
the 140-yen level will probably be the lowest it can go for now.''
   The Bank of Japan sold dollars as soon as the U.S. currency
climbed above 140.80 yen early Thursday, and sold more when it
almost touched 141.00 yen, said Toru Kanai, foreign exchange
analyst with New Japan Securities Co.
   The amount of selling by the central bank was not known. The
bank does not comment on its exchange market activities.
</TEXT>
