<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-China     09-28 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-China,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>London To Facilitate Emigration of Some Hong Kong Residents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Secretary John Major of Britain
says London will make it easier for some Hong Kong residents to
resettle in Britain if their freedom is threatened by China as it
takes control of the colony in 1997.
   Major also promised a more representative government for Hong
Kong and an early bill of rights for the colony that sets forth
basic liberties such as freedom of expression and travel.
   These fall under a ``package of concrete measures to reassure
people in the territory about their future,'' Major said Wednesday
in a speech to the U.N. General Assembly.
   Many Hong Kong residents, anxious about their future under
communist China after its repression of the pro-democracy movement,
have appealed to Britain to let them emigrate.
   London has ruled out large-scale immigration from Hong Kong.
   But Major said it would give people considered ``essential to
Hong Kong's future stability and prosperity'' guarantees of
resettlement in Britain if they wish when the colony reverts to
Chinese rule.
   This was believed to cover citizens such as senior public
servants but it was not immediately clear how the ``essential''
citizens would be chosen and how many would be allowed to emigrate.
   Major said Britain would hasten the introduction of a
democratically elected government in Hong Kong, where the
legislature currently is appointed. The aim is for half the seats
to be chosen in popular balloting by 1995.
   He said the measures to be implemented and the resettlement
offer were to encourage citizens to stay in Hong Kong and push
China to uphold its promises under a 50-year agreement to maintain
the colony's freedoms and way of life.
   ``Practical reassurances are required from China to the people
of Hong Kong, so that they may feel secure in their future both up
to 1997 and beyond,'' Major said.
   Hong Kong is resilient and its economy is thriving, ``but it
will take time, steady nerves and, above all, an explicitly
supportive attitude on the part of China, to restore Hong Kong's
confidence in its future,'' Major said.
   ``Millions of us around the world were shocked to see Chinese
troops kill and wound their fellow citizens on the orders of their
own government,'' he said. ``No government can survive indefinitely
by the suppression of peaceful dissent.''
   Major said London's response to the June military crackdown in
China is not intended to isolate Beijing.
   ``We hope to see China return to genuine reform and repair the
damage done to her international relations,'' he said.
   In London on Wednesday, Chinese and British officials began
three days of talks on the issue. British officials pressed Beijing
authorities for pledges that China will respect human rights and
preserve Hong Kong's position as the major Asian financial center.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
