<FIRST>r a PM-AxSlayings     09-28 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ax Slayings,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor: Family's Murders Part of Teen-ager's Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager charged with murdering his
parents, sister and brother with an ax had talked to his friends
about killing his family as ``a kind of game,'' a prosecutor said.
   Jurors were presented with grisly evidence at the start of the
trial Wednesday, including photos of the carnage and a
blood-spattered ax the prosecution claims was used in the killings.
   Olmsted County District Judge Ancy Morse told jurors not to
discuss any trauma the trial may cause them, and said the county
would provide counseling to anyone seeking it after the trial ends.
   Seventeen-year-old David Brom is charged with first- and
second-degree murder in the Feb. 18, 1988 ax slayings of his
parents, Bernard and Paulette Brom, both 41; his sister, Diane, 13;
and brother, Ricky, 11.
   If he is found guilty, a second phase of the trial will be held
to determine if he was mentally ill at the time of the slayings and
therefore not responsible.
   Brom was dressed neatly and sat with his back to a half-filled
courtroom gallery, showing no emotion.
   County Attorney Ray Schmitz told jurors that Brom repeatedly
talked to friends about killing his family as part of ``a kind of
game.''
   The ``game,'' as the teen-agers referred to it, also called for
Brom and his friends to flee to the West or South after the
killings, Schmitz said, adding that some scenarios included talk of
the friends killing themselves.
   The prosecutor said a friend of Brom would testify that Brom
proposed different alternatives for killing his family and talked
on one occasion about practicing doing something against his mother.
   Schmitz said Brom admitted the killings in a conversation with a
friend. And he said Brom told a friend he had an altercation with
his father the night of the killings.
   ``Suddenly,'' Schmitz said, ``it moved from the game to
something far more serious.''
   Brom's palm print was found on a bloodstained ax found in the
family's home, the prosecutor said.
   A defense attorney said he does not plan to challenge evidence
linking the defendant with the slayings. Conceding that the jury
likely will reach ``a guilty verdict of some type,'' lawyer
Terrence Walters said he would argue that the slayings were not
planned and Brom should be convicted of the lesser charge of
second-degree murder.
</TEXT>
