<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Colombia     09-28 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Colombia,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Royal Navy Going to Colombia to Help Fight Drug War</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Colombia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Royal Navy warship was en route to Colombia
today as part of a British aid package requested by Colombia's
government to help it battle the country's powerful cocaine cartels.
   The ship will patrol Colombia's coast looking for drug
traffickers, but will not have the jurisdiction to arrest or detain
suspected drug traffickers, the Defense Ministry said.
   A ministry spokesman would not identify the ship involved, but
British news reports said the frigate HMS Alacrity was en route
from the Caribbean island of Montserrat where it had been helping
to clean up from Hurricane Hugo.
   Britain will also provide a secure communications network to
help protect government officials, judges and other senior
Colombian figures under death threats from the drug traffickers,
and protective clothing such as bulletproof vests for people at
risk.
   British military advisers will be sent to help train local
officials in bomb disposal and protection skills, and all-terrain
motorbikes will be sent to provide greater mobility for drug
enforcement teams working in remote areas.
   The package was outlined by Foreign Secretary John Major at the
United Nations and by Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher speaking at
a Wednesday night reception in London.
   ``What we have offered is certain help after requests from the
Colombians,'' Mrs. Thatcher said. ``Of course we, in any event, try
to intercept drugs before they come on the seas.''
   Mrs. Thatcher said there were three steps to tackling the global
drugs problem.
   The first was ``to stop the countries from growing it, because
that's where the trouble starts,'' she said. The second was to
track down the people who were laundering drugs money and the third
was ``to try to stop the demand by warning people,'' she said.
   The Royal Navy is experienced in maritime surveillance, having
for many years patrolled the seas around Hong Kong searching for
vessels carrying illegal immigrants, drugs and other illicit
merchandise to the British colony.
   Capt. Richard Sharpe, editor of ``Jane's Fighting Ships,'' said:
``The Royal Navy has developed great expertise, both in Hong Kong
and in the fisheries protection role, in detecting and intercepting
vessels. Often these people are armed so you really need people who
are highly skilled.''
   ``Finding a drug runner is no different to finding a fast attack
craft coming in to fire a missile at you,'' Sharpe said.
   ``To sort out what you are interested in from a mass of radar
contacts is where military expertise is invaluable and it is
something the Royal Navy trains vigorously for.''
</TEXT>
