<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 0543EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Cambodia-Fighting     09-28 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia-Fighting,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thai Army says Cambodia Guerrillas Seize Many Areas in West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANUDEE SIASAKUL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodian guerrillas have after fierce
fighting seized many areas of western Cambodia from which
Vietnamese troops have recently withdrawn, a Thai army spokesman
claimed today.
   Lt. Gen. Naruedol Dejpradiyuth said fighting between rival
Cambodian factions had intensified over the past month in parts of
the country close to the Thai frontier.
   He said it appeared that the three guerrilla factions opposing
the Hanoi-backed Phnom Penh government were taking the opportunity
of the Vietnamese troop pullout to capture key positions.
   Vietnam said that it had completed the withdrawal of its last
26,000 troops from Cambodia on Tuesday.
   Naruedol said a civil war was inevitable in Cambodia now that
the Vietnamese have gone. Hanoi's withdrawal has given the
guerrillas their best opportunity yet to oust the Phnom Penh
government, he said.
   He said heavy fighting has been reported in the Ratanamondol
district near the important gem-trading town of Pailin.
   There were also battles at Sisophon in Battambang province and
in the northwestern province of Oddar Meanchey, he said.
   The guerrillas have taken many important areas formerly held by
government troops, the Thai general said, including positions
opposite the Thai border town of Aranyaprathet and another further
north opposite the town of Ta Phraya.
   He said the guerrillas killed many government troops and
captured 15.
   The Phnom Penh army was forced to bring in 3,000 extra troops to
help defend areas in Battambang and Oddar Meanchey, he said. The
new troops came from Phnom Penh and included draftees from Kompong
Cham, located northeast of the capital, he said.
   The general said morale among the government forces seemed low
and that since Sept. 20, 146 Cambodian government soldiers had
deserted their units and fled to Thailand. The latest group of 27
arrived on Tuesday, he said.
   Thailand is a major supporter of the resistance. Details of
Naruedol's battlefield reports could not immediately be confirmed
by other sources.
   Naruedol said that many heavy shells had fallen into Thailand
from the fighting over the past month. Three Thai villagers had
been killed in the southern part of the border between the towns of
Chantaburi and Trat, he said.
   On Wednesday, thousands of refugees at a United Nations refugee
camp on the Thai border were forced to flee as hundreds of shells
landed nearby. They were believed fired by Cambodian government
troops reacting to Khmer Rouge guerrilla operations in the area.
   The strongest of the guerrilla factions, the Khmer Rouge has
claimed several victories recently, both near Sisophon and around
the gem trading center of Pailin.
   Phnom Penh officials recently have admitted some setbacks at
Pailin.
   One official said the Khmer Rouge was firing up to 2,000 mortar
rounds a day at the town.
   The fanatical communist Khmer Rouge was responsible for the
deaths of hundreds of thousands of Cambodians when it ruled the
nation between 1975 and 1978, when Vietnam invaded.
   Many Cambodians have said they fear a return to power by the
Khmer Rouge. But Phnom Penh officials insist their army is capable
of fighting the guerrillas without Vietnamese military support.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890928-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 0616EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MarsMission     09-28 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mars Mission,0648</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cosmonaut, Astronaut Land in Mars, Pa.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PG2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARS, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet cosmonaut and an American astronaut
have landed in Mars on a special educational mission, and Martian
school children and just about everybody else in town are on cloud
nine.
   ``I don't think I'll ever forget this because I'll probably
never see a cosmonaut again or an astronaut for that matter,''
10-year-old Mandy Rooker said after the spacemen visited her
classroom at Adams Intermediate Elementary School.
   ``There's a certain pride today,'' said third-grade teacher Suzi
Wingfield.
   Cosmonaut Sergei Krikalev and astronaut Mario Runco Jr. spent
Wednesday talking about space travel with students and discussing
the need for cooperation between the two countries. They planned to
visit other schools in the district today and Friday.
   ``Children must study for a working future and maybe we will
work together,'' said Krikalev, 31, a flight engineer who lives
near Moscow.
   ``It's important that they learn that the world is becoming a
better place to live,'' agreed Runco, 37, a Navy lieutenant
commander awaiting assignment to his first space shuttle mission.
   During a visit with 367 students at the Mars Primary Center,
Krikalev received gifts of crayon drawings and homemade Soviet and
American flags, letters, fresh-cut flowers and Russian tea cakes.
Dozens of other drawings and greetings adorned the hallways' walls.
   ``Welckim To Mars,'' one first-grader wrote on a note
accompanying a rocket ship made of purple construction paper.
   The cosmonaut handed out autographed photographs showing himself
and his two partners during a five-month French-Soviet Soyuz
mission that ended in April.
   ``It's not so much the gifts. It's the friendliness that went
behind the gifts. It's coming from the insides of the people who
gave the gifts,'' he said through an interpreter.
   Krikalev later was joined by Runco at the intermediate school,
where they addressed 275 second- through fifth-graders. Runco
presented a slide show and gave the school 485 NASA photographs.
   Pupils asked them what it's like to eat and sleep in a spaceship
and whether they are nervous about space travel. They also wanted
to know about life in the Soviet Union and how each man had trained.
   ``I have a question,'' Runco said at one point. ``What's it like
living in Mars?''
   ``Out of this world,'' several in the crowd replied.
   Krikalev and Runco were invited to this small community 25 north
of Pittsburgh by the Mars Area Foundation for Educational
Excellence.
   ``The goal was to bring unusual cultural programs to the school
district, and it has blossomed beyond anything I had imagined,''
said Ralph Terrell, foundation chairman.
   The two visitors were thrilled at the prospect of being the
first spacemen to set foot in Mars.
   During a brief jaunt into the center of town, each man put on a
rubber boot and stepped into a tray of brown clay and signed his
name in the clay. The footprints and signatures were sealed in
glass and marked with a plaque noting that both men ``stepped on
Mars, Sept. 27, 1989.''
   They also posed for pictures near a spaceship 10 feet in
diameter made from the lids of steel barrels.
   ``I didn't think I'd get there this soon,'' Runco joked as he
accepted a blue T-shirt emblazoned with the words ``I've already
been to Mars, Pennsylvania.''
   Krikalev said he consulted numerous maps and even an American
acquaintance to find out where Mars was before leaving on his first
trip to the United States. He could not locate it and was forced to
bring clothes for all kinds of weather.
   Krikalev knows how he will describe Mars when he returns home
early next week.
   ``I'll say it's a small town,'' he said, ``and the town is very
friendly.''
</TEXT>
