<FIRST>r i PM-China-Vietnam     09-28 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Vietnam,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Calls Vietnam Withdrawal A Fraud</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Cambodia-Vietnam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China charged today that at least 30,000
disguised Vietnamese soldiers remain in Cambodia and indicated it
will continue to arm guerrillas fighting that country's pro-Hanoi
government until a political settlement is reached.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Li Zhaoxing, devoting much of a
weekly briefing to criticism of Vietnam, also renewed charges of
Vietnam's ``brazen violation'' of China's territorial sovereignty
in occupying islands in a disputed South China Sea chain.
   Li refuted Vietnam's claims of a troop withdrawal and said at
least 30,000 Vietnamese troops have changed to the uniforms of
Cambodian government troops.
   He contended that large amounts of weapons and military
equipment have been left behind and that Vietnamese officials
continue to control administrative organs in the ``puppet regime.''
   He said, ``hidden among the over 1 million illegal Vietnamese
settlers in Cambodia are many Vietnamese militiamen and special
agents. Clearly there has been no change in Vietnam's basic scheme
for keeping Cambodia under its control and creating an Indochina
federation.''
   Li's statement came a day after Vietnam proclaimed it had
completed the withdrawal of its last 26,000 troops in Cambodia,
ending an 11-year military presence in that country.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in December 1978, ending nearly four
years of rule by a Khmer Rouge regime that sent hundreds of
thousands of people to their deaths in trying to turn the country
into a primitive agrarian commune.
   Asked whether China will continue to arm the Khmer Rouge and
other resistance forces, Li said all countries should stop military
assistance to Cambodia _ but only after the warring factions in the
country reach a political settlement and Vietnam genuinely
withdraws all its troops.
   Vietnam has urged those countries supporting the Cambodian
resistance _ China and Thailand chief among them _ to stop arming
the guerrillas, saying that only then can a political settelement
be achieved.
   On another matter, Li said that since June, Vietnam has sent
troops to invade and occupy a reef and two shoals in the Spratly
Islands, an archipelago in the South China Sea claimed by both
China and Vietnam.
   ``This is a brazen violation against China's territorial
sovereignty,'' he said, adding that those islands and others in the
area ``have been part of China's sacred territory since ancient
times and China has irrefutable sovereignty over all these islands
and their adjacent waters.''
   In March, Chinese naval forces sank three Vietnamese ships in an
exchange of fire off the islands that left more than 70 Vietnamese
sailors dead or missing.
   The Philippines, Taiwan and Malaysia also claim the islands and
the surrounding seas, which are thought to contain large oil
deposits.
</TEXT>
