<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 0627EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-USAirInvestigation     09-28 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-USAir Investigation,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rudder Found Turned Left; Airline, NTSB Discount Report of Crew Drinking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL GEITNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rudder of a USAir jetliner was set wrongly
before last week's fatal skid into the East River, and that could
explain the drift the captain said led him to abort takeoff,
according to investigators.
   An airline spokesman and the National Transportation Safety
Board, meanwhile, dismissed a report Wednesday that the crew of
Flight 5050 had been drinking for five hours before getting into
the cockpit.
   The NTSB said the rudder trim in the 737-400's cockpit, which
holds the rudder steady, had been found in the full-left position.
   ``That would tend to want to move the plane to the left if he
didn't do other things to compensate for it,'' Ted Lopatkiewicz, a
NTSB spokesman in Washington, said of the pilot.
   He said it would be the responsibility of either the captain or
copilot to set the trim before takeoff.
   ``It clearly could have been one of the factors that led to the
crash,'' said Peter Baron, who heads the National Center for Air
Traffic Safety in New York, a nonprofit consumer advocacy group.
   The trim is on the pretakeoff checklist that the captain and
crew are supposed to go through, Baron said. But he added, ``It's
not the type of thing where you're going to get a warning horn if
it was mis-set.''
   The effect of setting the rudder to the left would not become
apparent until the plane built up speed during takeoff, he added.
   Capt. Michael W. Martin told investigators he aborted the
takeoff because the aircraft was moving left and he heard and felt
a strange vibration.
   Two passengers died in the Sept. 20 crash and 59 people
survived. The plane was scheduled to fly to Charlotte, N.C.
   Published reports have said cocaine had been found aboard the
plane. The Cable News Network, citing the NTSB, reported Wednesday
that more than a pound of cocaine was found in a piece of carry-on
luggage, but not among the holdings of the flight crew.
   But the NTSB's chief spokeswoman, Rachel Halterman, said, ``We
don't confirm that. That's absolutely ridiculous. That's nothing to
do with us. If it's true it's not a confirmation that would come
from us.''
   Also Wednesday, Lopatkiewicz and a USAir spokesman said the two
pilots had only about two hours between the time they landed at
LaGuardia from Baltimore and the time Flight 5050 left the gate.
   ``That's documented,'' said David Shipley, an airline spokesman
in Arlington, Va.
   In addition, Lopatkiewicz said the copilot was on the plane for
most if not all of that time, while the captain went to USAir
offices at LaGuardia.
   The New York Post reported Wednesday that a detective close to
the investigation said the crew may have spent as many as five
hours before the flight in bars near the airport.
   The newspaper said a passenger, Eric Trendel, the husband of a
USAir employee, told authorities immediately after the crash he had
been out ``bouncing'' with the captain and the copilot.
Investigators said they believed he meant ``drinking'' or ``bar
hopping.''
   But Lopatkiewicz said the NTSB had not turned up any suggestion
that the pilots went drinking.
   Trendel may be subpoenaed to testify before a grand jury
investigating the crash, the Post said. The Daily News quoted
unidentified sources as saying USAir also was subpoenaed because it
had been reluctant to cooperate with the investigation.
   Drug and alcohol tests on Martin and Kleissas came out negative,
but the urine samples were taken 48 hours after the accident,
making them useless for alcohol testing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
