<FIRST>r a PM-Newspage-Baseball     09-28 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Newspage-Baseball,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>San Francisco Clinches NL West Title; Oakland Takes AL West</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LAD1, LaserColor OAS2C</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dreams of a ``sub-Bay'' series are alive
as the San Francisco Giants and the Oakland Athletics clinched
division titles and earned berths in Major League baseball's
playoffs.
   The A's beat Texas 5-0 in Oakland on Wednesday to take their
second straight American League West title.
   ``This was probably the biggest victory of my career,'' said
Mike Moore, who pitched seven innings of one-hit ball. ``It wasn't
necessarily a do-or-die game, but better to do it now than later.''
   The Giants, the A's National League rivals across the San
Francisco Bay, backed into the league's West title despite losing
their third straight game, 1-0, to the Dodgers in Los Angeles. They
clinched later when the San Diego Padres lost to the Cincinnati
Reds, 2-1.
   ``We wanted to win this thing outright, but right now, we'll
take it any way we can get it,'' Giants slugger Will Clark said
while listening to the Reds-Padres game on the radio.
   San Francisco will take on the Chicago Cubs in the National
League playoffs beginning Wednesday in Chicago.
   The Athletics, whose eighth division title is the most for any
team since divisional play began 20 years ago, must wait for the
outcome of the American League East race between the Toronto Blue
Jays and the Baltimore Orioles for their opponent.
   If Oakland and San Francisco make it to the World Series, fans
can take the BART, the train that runs under San Francisco Bay
between the cities.
</TEXT>
