<FIRST>r a PM-RacialPrank     09-28 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Racial Prank,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ole Miss Ousts Fraternity For Racial Prank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of Mississippi has banned a
fraternity for leaving two members naked and painted with racial
slurs at a mostly black college.
   The university's chancellor Wednesday said the incident had
opened an old wound at Ole Miss, which erupted in violence in 1962
when its first black student, James Meredith, enrolled.
   ``Nothing can totally undo the effects of the deplorable events
of September 18,'' Gerald Turner said in announcing he accepted a
hearing panel's recommendation to shut the Beta Theta Pi chapter
for three years.
   He gave the fraternity a week to close its house.
   ``Unquestionably, this action of the few has reflected very
negatively on the university community in such a way as to deny the
significant advancements in human relations that have occurred on
campus in the past few years,'' Turner said.
   The two fraternity members were carried by car to Rust College,
a small, private school 25 miles to the north, and their hands and
feet bound with duct tape before they were released. The two were
picked up by Rust security officers.
   Members of the fraternity, which had been active at the
university for 110 years, refused to comment Wednesday. Turner said
the 90-member chapter, suspended earlier by its national
organization, wouldn't appeal the ban.
   The chancellor said about 15 students may have had leadership
roles in the incident and some may be expelled.
   Students, faculty and the state chapter of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People had called for
harsh penalties. An NAACP official also asked for a federal
investigation into racial discrimination by fraternities at the
10,370-student university.
   ``It's sad the entire fraternity has to suffer because of the
actions of a few, but the punishment is acceptable to us,'' said
Ishmell Edwards, dean of students at 925-student Rust College.
</TEXT>
