<FIRST>r i PM-Refugees     09-28 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Refugees,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germans Scale Embassy Fence; Czechs Rule Out `Hungarian Solution'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MANFRED HEES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Desperate East Germans today
scaled a fence surrounding the overcrowded West German Embassy
compound and joined nearly 2,000 refugees hoping to emigrate to the
West.
   East German authorities have failed to persuade most of the
refugees to leave their tents in the compound and return home,
despite difficult living conditions that were aggravated by heavy
rain.
   Botho Prinz zu Sayn-Wittgenstein, president of the West German
Red Cross, and Foreign Ministry officials left for Prague to review
conditions in the embassy garden and seek improvememnts.
   After meeting his East German counterpart, Oskar Fischer, at the
United Nations in New York, West German Foreign Minister Hans
Dietrich Genscher told reporters ``he did not rule out'' progress
in the refugee standoff.
   A Czechoslovak government spokesman, Miroslav Pavel, said today
that ``as soon as they (the two German states) reach an agreement,
Czechoslovakia is willing to provide comprehensive humanitarian and
technical help.''
   However, ``a Hungarian solution is out of the question,'' he
told Austrian radio, referring to Hungary's decision earlier this
month to open its borders for thousands of East German refugees to
emigrate freely to West Germany.
   By 7 p.m. Wednesday, 1,882 refugees were registered in the
embassy compound, but more than 100 people climbed over the fence
during the night.
   East Germans filled the grounds with hundreds in tents. Many men
spent the night in sleeping bags in the open air because there was
not enough room in the tents. Some adults slept on stairwells, and
three people shared one cot.
   In Bonn, a Red Cross official said it was impossible to pitch
more tents in the Prague compound. Therefore, the Red Cross has
sent tarpaulins to protect those staying outside the tents against
rain.
   The refugees included almost 300 children, including a
4-week-old baby, refugees told Western reporters talking to them
through the fence.
</TEXT>
