<FIRST>r a PM-KKK-Highway     09-28 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-KKK-Highway,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>KKK Chapter Wants to Adopt Highway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Ku Klux Klan chapter has applied to take
part in North Carolina's Adopt-a-Highway litter program under which
volunteers get a stretch of road to keep clean and a road sign with
their name on it.
   The Department of Transportation is considering the request from
the Rockingham County chapter of The Invisible Empire Knights of
the Ku Klux Klan.
   If it is approved, the state will erect a green-and-white sign
with the Klan name along the adopted highway.
   Rocky Chapman, exalted cyclops of the Klan chapter, said he
filed the application two weeks ago.
   ``I feel it's our constitutional right to adopt a highway,'' he
said. ``It isn't like I was going out here doing something
disruptive. We're trying to do something good for the state. We're
trying to clean up North Carolina.''
   James Sughrue, assistant secretary of transportation for
external affairs, said officials were studying the application.
``It is not a usual request and therefore it is not being handled
in the usual manner,'' he said.
   Sughrue said he did not know if any applications had been
rejected since the program began last year.
   Chapman said a local department official had persuaded the group
to change their original requested stretch of road because it was
in a heavily black area.
   The official told him he was worried that motorists would
intentionally litter there to make more work for the Klan, Chapman
said.
   Under the Adopt-A-Highway program, weekend volunteers from 4,669
civic groups, businesses and neighborhoods pick up litterl from
more than 10,000 miles of roads.
</TEXT>
