<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 1010EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Hugo-KidneyMachine     09-28 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo-Kidney Machine,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Given Generator to Power Daughter's Dialysis Machine</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUMTER, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For three days, Estelle Ray searched
frantically for a generator to power her daughter's kidney dialysis
machine after Hurricane Hugo knocked out electricity to her home.
   Civil defense had none. Each time she heard about one for sale
from North Carolina to Virginia, it was sold by the time she called.
   ``I was real scared,'' she said.
   A generator was finally located Monday with the help of a
supervisor at a bank where another daughter, Wendy, worked. The
generator was working in her home Tuesday.
   ``It was a blessing, I mean a great blessing from God,'' Mrs.
Ray said.
   Until the generator was hooked up, Mrs. Ray had to do the work
of a dialysis machine manually to save the life of her 19-year-old
daughter, Nicole. Without dialysis, poisonous wastes created by her
body could kill her.
   Using the manual method, fluid had to be drained from a tube in
Nicole's stomach and fresh fluid replaced at least four times a day.
   Each time Mrs. Ray or Wendy changed the fluid, there was the
chance for infection.
   ``I almost died one time before and I don't think you could be
that lucky twice,'' Nicole said. ``I just thought maybe I'd be one
of the deaths that Hurricane Hugo caused.''
   Matters were compounded when the city's water system shut down.
   ``I said, `We can't scrub; we're going to have to do the best
that we can,''' Mrs. Ray said.
   Her luck changed when Wendy talked about her sister's problem
with her boss, Kenneth Richey, a senior vice president at a bank.
He rounded up a generator.
   ``I think that was good for someone to care that much about
someone they do not even know and someone who is not their
responsibility, because he never heard of me or met me,'' Nicole
said.
   Richey said he bought 30 generators to operate the bank's
automatic teller machines in Charleston and several other cities,
and he gave one to the Rays.
   ``Somebody's got to help her. You just do it,'' Richey said.
</TEXT>
