<DOCNO> AP890928-0070 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 1015EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Israel     09-28 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rabin Gets Key Endorsement in Quest for Labor Party Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin picked up a key
endorsement today amid growing signs he might be able to unseat
Finance Minister Shimon Peres as leader of the left-leaning Labor
Party.
   Rabin, 67, a career army officer who served as prime minister
from 1974 to 1977, won the backing of Labor Party dove Ezer
Weizman, a former air force chief who is now science minister.
   ``If today the question would be him or my good friend Shimon
Peres to lead the party to peace and elections, I think (Rabin) is
the man to do it,'' Weizman said on Israel radio.
   Another Labor dove, Ely Ben-Menachem, also indicated he favored
Rabin over Peres, who has led Labor since 1977, should early
elections be called and the party convened to choose a leader.
   But Labor legislator Avraham Burg said in an interview that he
believed Peres would win any showdown in the party, even though
Rabin had more public support at the moment.
   ``(Peres) has a firmer grip on the party machinery,'' he said.
   The leadership issue is not likely to come to a decision unless
the coalition between Labor and the right-wing Likud bloc of Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir breaks apart and new elections are called.
   A Labor-Likud split is likely only if there is a serious move
toward Israeli-Palestinian negotiations on the future of the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. Labor favors returning land in
exchange for peace while Likud opposes any yielding of territory.
   Labor Party insiders said Rabin, who has been defense minister
since 1984, improved his standing with Labor doves as a result of
his meeting earlier this month with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak.
   Outside the party, Rabin has garnered the respect of
right-wingers by taking a tough line against the Palestinian
uprising in which more than 570 Palestinians and 40 Israelis have
died.
   ``Rabin has the best of both worlds,'' Hanoch Smith, an
independent pollster, said in an interview. ``By dealing toughly
with the intefadeh (uprising), he has won support from Likud and
religious parties while getting support from Laborites because he
favors a land-for-peace settlement.''
   Smith said a survey now being completed is expected to show a
continuing upward trend in support for Rabin, who has been
outpolling both Peres and Shamir since the coalition government was
created last year.
   Rabin, who served as armed forces chief of staff during the 1967
Middle East war, became prime minister in 1974 after Golda Meir
stepped down.
   He was forced to call new elections after losing the support of
a key religious party. He then lost the party leadership and
resigned as premier after his wife, Leah, was revealed to have an
illegal bank account abroad.
</TEXT>
