<FIRST>r e BC-Opera 1stLd-Writethru a0430 09-28 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Opera, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0430,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Met Opera Restages `Porgy'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: CORRECTS name of singer in role of Clara from Marvin to Marvis
in 9th graf bgng ``Marvin''; ^By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hurricane hit Charleston again, but this time
it struck only on the stage of the Metropolitan Opera as the Met
presented ``Porgy and Bess'' on the third night of its season.
   Director Arvin Brown, artistic director of the Long Wharf
Theater in New Haven, Conn., intensified some of the stage action
and changed the location of one scene _ the hurricane. On Wednesday
night, instead of everybody going to a rickety lean-to near the
ocean, they take shelter in Serena's room. It isn't as
fear-inducing for the audience but it's better dramatically because
it's more sensible.
   Michael Smartt and Priscilla Baskerville sang Porgy and Bess,
making their love story more real than many singers make it.
   They both made their Met debuts in 1985, in small parts in the
opera. Smartt's voice has intrinsic dignity. It isn't loud but his
words can be understood.
   Miss Baskerville isn't a flamboyant Bess. Though Crown turns her
head with sex appeal and Sportin' Life turns it by giving her dope
to sniff, this Bess seems to be her real self when she's with Porgy.
   Ben Holt, tall and slim, was Sportin' Life. He was directed
oddly, being intimidated by the matrons of Catfish Row in Act 1 and
acting rather adolescent. Singing ``It Ain't Necessary So'' in Act
2, he was an entertainer at the picnic, moving like a dancer. Only
in Act 2, singing ``There's a Boat That's Leavin' Soon for New
York,'' did he seem the suave Pied Piper of ``happy dust.''
   His voice was focused with an interesting, attractive timbre.
Oddly, in an opera in which events are large and not genteel,
Smartt, Miss Baskerville and Holt made this listener desire to hear
all of them in recital.
   Gregg Baker was Crown, almost the only cast member recreating
his role from the 1985 Met Opera premiere of Gershwin's 1935 opera.
Surely the Met has nobody else as suitable as Crown. Baker is built
like an athlete, tall and broad. His chest is bare a couple of
times, so the effect isn't missed, and he picks up Bess like she's
a feather. His voice is strong and compelling, too.
   Marvis Martin sang Clara, singing ``Summertime'' with sweet
clarity.
   Camellia Johnson sang Serena and Marjorie Wharton of
Philadelphia, a notable Maria, was one of 10 singers making Met
debuts.
   Mezzo Linda Thompson of Brooklyn and tenor Lynn Randolph of New
York were able to make an impression in the tiny but noticeable
roles of early morning sellers of strawberries and crabs.
   James Levine conducted, without flagging. He's conducting the
first five performances of the Met's opening week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
