<FIRST>r a PM-BankRobbery     09-28 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bank Robbery,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>College Student Arraigned in Robbery-Murder Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA ZAGAROLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CORUNNA, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A criminal justice student troubled by his
mother's illness and the loss of a college grant has been charged
with robbing a bank and killing one of his four hostages by backing
his car over her.
   William Troy McAlister, 21, of Shaftsburg, was jailed without
bail Wednesday on charges of murder, assault with intent to murder,
kidnapping and bank robbery.
   One of McAlister's older brothers, Mitch, said the younger man
had been under stress lately.
   ``Our mother has Alzheimer's and I left him in charge for the
last month and a half, which is hard on him,'' he said. ``He was
going to college and his grant was cut off. I don't know, he just
slipped.''
   Terry McIntosh, whose wife, Sue, was one of the hostages, said
his wife told him the abductor ``was kind of nervous and didn't say
a whole lot, but at one point he said he needed the money for
college.''
   McAlister was studying at Andrews University in Berrien Springs,
his brothers said.
   Police said a hooded gunman Tuesday took an estimated $50,000
from the vault at a bank and took four bank employees hostage as
they arrived for work.
   The gunman then forced the four to drive in two cars about 70
miles, ordered them to lie side-by-side in a field and backed his
car over them, hitting two women while another woman and a man
escaped, police said.
   He shot at the escaping pair but missed.
   One woman was killed. Another was in stable condition with a cut
on her scalp.
   McAlister was arrested hours later at a roadblock. Police said
they spotted money in his car and found a diagram of the bank and
notes on bank procedures at the home of his mother, Catherine G.
Wells, where he had been staying.
</TEXT>
