<FIRST>r w PM-US-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0447 09-28 0799</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0447,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poland Gets Encouragement But No New Aid</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS 3 grafs after 7th pvs, bgng: Delegates have, to UPDATE
with Conable remarks on China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poland's new non-communist-led government is
getting warm words of encouragement from President Bush and other
Western leaders but few promises of fresh aid in the country's
historic economic transformation from state control to free
enterprise.
   Polish Finance Minister Leszek Balcerowicz, warning of
``potentially explosive social conditions,'' appealed to Western
democracies Wednesday for $1.5 billion to maintain essential
imports and stabilize its currency.
   ``We must do more,'' agreed President Bush, speaking at the
annual meetings of the World Bank and the 152-nation International
Monetary Fund.
   However, Bush mentioned no specific figure for U.S. help beyond
the $219 million in food and economic aid already pledged. He told
reporters later the amount of aid hinged on the details of Poland's
reform package.
   ``We want to work with them in every way we can, but I think
it's important to see what their plan is for economic reform,'' the
president said.
   The IMF and World Bank, international lending agencies
established 44 years ago to foster economic stability and
development, are wrapping up their annual meetings today.
   Delegates have been discussing a wide variety of topics in
addition to Eastern Europe, ranging from the Third World's crushing
$1.3 trillion debt burden, environmental problems such as the
global warming trend and efforts to reduce the U.S. trade deficit
by stabilizing currency exchange rates among the major industrial
nations.
   World Bank President Barber B. Conable today said his
organization, before deciding on when to resume lending to China,
will look closely at the outcome of a conference next month at
which Chinese leaders will decide on the country's economic program
for the next three years.
   ``Coming out of that will be interesting signals about their
intention of moving ahead with economic reform,'' he said at a news
conference.
   The World Bank in June held up $780 million in loans to China
following the massacre of student demonstrators in Tiananmen Square
and the imposition of martial law.
   In a development on the Latin debt problem, Argentine President
Carlos Menem, who met with Bush at the White House on Wednesday,
announced that his country had reached agreement clearing the way
for an IMF loan. Argentina is the third largest debtor in the
developing world with $60 billion owed. IMF officials said $1.4
billion would be disbursed through 1990.
   Balcerowicz has been busy drumming up support for his government
with an address to the IMF and World Bank on Wednesday and with a
round of one-on-one meetings this week with world finance officials.
   The most senior Polish leader to visit Washington since a
government led by the trade union Solidarity came to power on Aug.
24, Balcerowicz met with Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady and
the finance ministers of Japan, West Germany, Great Britain, France
and Italy.
   Balcerowicz said, ``I would hope that results would be
forthcoming quite quickly.''
   He has been outlining Poland's plan to curb runaway inflation,
prop up the faltering currency, turn over state-run enterprises to
private ownership, encourage entrepreneurship and create a new
market-based financial system.
   To aid the effort, Poland is seeking two major packages from the
West. One, of $490 million to $500 million, is needed by December
to maintain imports of essentials such as medicine and fertilizer.
Another $1 billion is needed for reserves to stabilize the
faltering zloty, Poland's currency.
   Both requests are separate from Poland's effort to secure loans
from the World Bank and IMF. Balcerowicz did not mention an amount,
but Juergen Warnke, West German minister for economic cooperation,
told reporters the IMF was considering $700 million a year.
   Balcerowicz, stressing that his government's measures likely
will cause unemployment and other distress, focused on the urgent
need for foreign aid, saying the Polish reform movement's chances
of success ``would be considerably enhanced by ... fast, efficient,
substantial and sustained economic and financial support.''
   He drew immediate backing from Democrats in Congress, who are
rallying support for food and economic assistance packages for
Eastern Europe that total at least $3.7 billion, most of it
earmarked for Poland.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., called Bush's aid proposal
``pathetically timid'' and Majority Leader George Mitchell,
D-Maine, said the ``administration's timidity in the face of these
opportunities is puzzling and dismaying.''
   Finance leaders of other nations joined Bush's call for aid to
the Poles, but they shared his concern that aid be linked to
changes in Poland. Japanese Finance Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto,
West German Finance Minister Theo Waigel and Great Britain's
chancellor of the exchequer, Nigel Lawson, said Poland must agree
to a program of economic reforms with the IMF as a first step.
</TEXT>
