<FIRST>u a PM-Bush-Hurricane 1stLd-Writethru a0544 09-28 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Hurricane, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0544,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Traveling to South Carolina to see Hurricane Damage</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: ADDS 5 grafs, bgng, White House xxx, with additional background</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will fly to South
Carolina on Friday for a firsthand look at the devastation spewed
by Hurricane Hugo, the White House said today.
   The hurricane, which killed 28 people on the U.S. mainland and
33 in the Caribbean, left behind upwards of $3 billion in damage.
   The hurriedly arranged trip will complicate a schedule that
already calls for Bush to be in Annapolis, Md., in late morning for
a retirement ceremony for Adm. William Crowe, who has been chairman
of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
   To fulfill his commitment to Crowe, Bush will have to make a
pre-dawn flight to Charleston and complete his tour by mid-morning
in order to leave time to travel to Annapolis, officials said.
   White House officials flew to Charleston late Wednesday to map
out an itinerary for Bush.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Bush wanted
``to make sure that all that can be done is being done'' and to
assure the people of South Carolina the governor will provide
``whatever help we can.''
   Fitzwater was asked about complaints about federal relief
efforts from Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C. ``Hollings' job is to
keep the pressure on,'' said Fitzwater.
   The press spokesman said government agents were fighting
``remarkable odds'' in the relief effort.
   ``We think things are going pretty well,'' Fitzwater said. Asked
if Bush might help cut red tape that is hindering the cleanup,
Fitzwater said, ``If there is any _ yes. We'll take a look at
that.''
   South Carolina Gov. Carroll Campbell said planners were trying
to arrange for Bush to get of view of devastated areas on the coast
as well as inland. Possible stops include Myrtle Beach, Charleston
and Sumpter.
</TEXT>
