<HEAD>President Offers Condolences to Marcos Family</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today said he was
saddened to hear of the death of former Philippines leader
Ferdinand Marcos and offered his condolences to the family.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, in a brief statement
issued from Charlottesville at the education summit, said:
   ``The president and Mrs. Bush were saddened to hear of the death
of former President Marcos. They offer their condolences to Mrs.
Marcos and the members of her family. For over 20 years, Mr. Marcos
was the leader of the Philippines, a nation that has been and
remains a staunch friend and ally of the United States. Mr. Marcos
agreed to leave the Philippines at a critical juncture in his
nation's history. His departure permitted the peaceful transition
to popular, democratic rule under President (Corazon) Aquino.''
   Bush, during a trip to Manila in 1981, five years before the
Philippine leader fled in disgrace, praised Marcos and his
government.
   ``We love your adherence to democratic principles and to the
democratic process,'' Bush said during his visit as vice president.
