<FIRST>u w PM-HUDProbe 1stLd-Writethru a0450 09-28 0798</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0450,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former HUD Official Refuses to Testify</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: INSERTS 4 grafs after 4th graf pvs to update with Adams testimony
today; picks up 7th graf pvs: Alexander Naclerio...</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The
Senate ... this program.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former top housing official was the key
figure to see for developers seeking federal grants _ even after he
left the Department of Housing and Urban Development _ former
regional housing officials say.
   The official, Lance H. Wilson, became the fourth former top HUD
official to refuse to testify when he appeared Wednesday before a
House subcommittee probing alleged influence-peddling and
mismanagement at the agency.
   As former HUD Secretary Samuel Pierce did a day earlier, Wilson
asserted his Fifth Amendment right against self-incrimination.
Wilson said he had been labeled a ``prime candidate for a criminal
investigation'' and said he was convinced ``the subcommittee had
already prejudged me.''
   Also on Wednesday, a former HUD staffer told of investigating a
project on behalf of a contributor to President Bush's 1980
campaign for the vice presidency.
   The Senate Banking Committee, meanwhile, resumed today its
parallel investigation of HUD during the eight years it was headed
by Pierce.
   Paul Adams, HUD's inspector general, described how HUD officials
disagreed with suggestions for tightening the department's troubled
coinsurance program, which used private lenders to handle
HUD-backed loans, and which has led to mortgage losses estimated so
far at $960 million.
   He said his recommendations in audits conducted in 1984 and 1988
were rejected by HUD officials as unfair and likely to discourage
lender participation. Adams credited new HUD Secretary Jack Kemp
with moving to tighten the program.
   But Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., called for a more urgent response
and denounced former HUD management for ``indolence in the
management of this program.''
   Alexander Naclerio, a former director of housing in HUD's New
York area office who became a consultant after retiring in 1986,
told the House panel Wednesday he paid Wilson $15,000 for help in
getting HUD grants for two projects after both men had left the
agency.
   Naclerio said he asked Wilson for help because he felt politics
were harming his ability to get HUD approval for the projects in
Puerto Rico and New York City.
   ``I felt I was getting the political zing,'' Naclerio said. ``I
called Lance Wilson and I related to him the story.''
   Naclerio also said Wilson called him in 1982 and asked him to
look into a project in Puerto Rico. Wilson ``indicated this was on
behalf of a major contributor to George Bush's vice presidential
campaign,'' Delio Rojo, Naclerio testified.
   The Washington Post reported today that HUD officials, whom it
did not identify, had said that an unidentified aide to Bush asked
Wilson to meet with Rojo about the project.
   The newspaper said aides to Vice President Bush said they made
referrals to government agencies without endorsements.
   Rojo' consultant, Carlos Figueroa, said he arranged the
Rojo-Wilson meeting on his own and probably discussed the matter
with Rafael V. Capo, an aide to the vice president.
   Wilson's refusal to testify made him the fourth top-ranking
former HUD official to refuse to answer questions before the House
panel.
   Deborah Gore Dean, who replaced Wilson as Pierce's executive
assistant, and R. Hunter Cushing, a former deputy assistant
secretary at HUD, refused to testify on constitutional grounds in
earlier appearances.
   Another former HUD regional administrator, Dick Eudaley of Fort
Worth, Texas, said Wednesday: ``There were a few people who could
make things happen at headquarters. One of these was Mr. Wilson,
and another was Ms. Dean. She depended on him for a lot of her
instructions.''
   Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., chairman of the House Government
Operations employment and housing subcommittee, said he wanted to
question Wilson about a series of HUD projects he worked on after
leaving the department.
   One, Lantos said, involved a gift to Wilson from developer
Leonard Briscoe of a 15 percent interest in a $24 million Riviera
Beach project in Florida. While at HUD two years earlier, Lantos
said, Wilson had backed a $7 million grant application for a Fort
Worth, Texas, project that was pushed by Briscoe.
   ``I knew the deal was happening but I knew there was nothing I
could do about it,'' Eudaley said. ``The feeling within the agency
was that this project had the personal interest of the secretary's
office and Mr. Wilson.''
   Although he did not testify, Wilson issued a written statement
saying the Fort Worth project met HUD criteria and that he urged it
receive a ``fair hearing'' because ``he felt there was a lack of
receptivity to minority applicants in some HUD regional offices.''
   Wilson is on paid leave from his job as first vice president of
Paine Webber Group Inc.
</TEXT>
