<FIRST>u i PM-Quayle 3rdLd-Writethru a0488 09-28 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quayle, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0488,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede MANILA</HEAD>
<HEAD>Quayle Calls For Support To Non-Communist Factions in Cambodia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads thruout to UPDATE with developments in Malaysia. Changes
byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARI S.MANIAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle today
called for all-out support for non-Communist resistance factions in
Cambodia to help prevent a comeback by the Khmer Rouge.
   Quayle declined, however, to say whether his comments meantthe
United States had been sending military assistance to those
factions.
   ``I don't comment on matters like that. But I want to reaffirm
our strong support for the non-Communist resistance. We need to
make sure that they have credibility, that they have resources,
that they can participate efficiently in a resolution in
Cambodia,'' Quayle told a news conference before leaving for
Washington at the end of his four-nation Asian tour.
   Quayle arrived in Malaysia from the Philippines, where President
Corazon Aquino said today she has accepted an offer to begin talks
on extending the lease on U.S. military bases. But she said there
can be no certainty the talks will produce agreement.
   Quayle said earlier he was confident the two sides would reach
agreement during the December talks that would guarantee the
``longtime involvement'' of the United States in the Philippines.
   The lease expires in September 1991.
   Quayle said that in Malaysia, he had conferred with the U.S.
heads of mission from Thailand, Indonesia, Malaysia and Singapore
on how to cope with the situation in Cambodia following a
Vietnamese troop pullout that Hanoi said was completed this week.
   The talks ``reaffirmed our view the Khmer Rouge must not return
to power'' and ``assistance must be given to the non-Communist
factions,'' he said.
   The fanatical Communist Khmer Rouge ruled Cambodia from 1975
until it was toppled by a Vietnamese invasion in late 1978. It now
is the strongest faction in a resistance coalition that also
includes two non-Communist groups.
   With the Vietnamese troop pullout, the resistance is fighting
troops of the Phnom Penh government installed by Vietnam.
   The issue of American assistance to non-Communist resistance is
sensitive. Vietnam has called on foreign countries to cut off aid
to the resistance.
   Quayle said the Association of Southeast Asian Nations and U.S.
positions on the Khmer Rouge did not differ, and both did not want
to see the Khmer Rouge in power.
   ASEAN, a major backer of the resistance coalition, includes
Malaysia, Singapore, Thailand, Indonesia, the Philippines and
Brunei.
   In the Philippines on Wednesday, police hurled tear gas to
disperse 2,000 leftists demonstrating against Quayle and the bases.
At least 157 people were arrested.
   Quayle handed Mrs. Aquino a letter from President Bush
suggesting new talks on extending the bases' lease, despite growing
opposition among Filipinos to their presence.
   In announcing her agreement to the December talks, Mrs. Aquino
said in a statement:
   ``This only means that a panel, the composition of which is
still under study, will meet with an American panel ... The
discussions may or may not lead to a new bases agreement. The
Philippine panel will be guided by what we believe to be in our
national interest and no other.''
   In a departure statement, Quayle said he would personally convey
Mrs. Aquino's acceptance to Bush when he returns to Washington from
his Asia tour.
   ``I am confident that we will find a mutually acceptable
agreement on the future of the facilities in the Philippines,'' he
added.
   Any agreement on extending the bases' lease must be ratified by
two-thirds of the 23-member Senate, where opposition to the bases
is strong. At least 12 senators have called publicly for them to be
closed in 1991.
   Before departing, Quayle toured the battlefield on Corregidor
island, where U.S. and Filipino forces were defeated by the
Japanese during World War II.
   Quayle's visit was also marked by the killing of two American
civilians slain near a U.S. base hours before he arrived Tuesday.
Police suspect Communist rebels were responsible.
   About 40,000 American troops, civilian employees and military
dependents are stationed at the six U.S. installations, including
Clark Air Base and the Subic Bay naval base.
</TEXT>
