<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 1129EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NASAContractors     09-28 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NASA Contractors,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Times: NASA Fears Dependence on Contractors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top NASA officials have questioned whether the
space agency is depending too much on private contractors and
risking loss of control over operations, costs and safety,
according to a report published today.
   ``I am deeply concerned over the continuing erosion of our civil
service capability,'' wrote James R. Thompson Jr., NASA's deputy
administrator, in a letter to federal Budget Director Richard G.
Darman.
   The letter, written after Darman asked each federal agency to
assess itself, was obtained by The New York Times under the Freedom
of Information Act.
   In the letter, Thompson wrote that the budget office's effort to
``convert more and more critical functions'' to contractors is
taxing NASA's management and supervisory abilities, the Times
reported.
   ``We've been stretched to the point where it's troubling to me,
given the oversight that's required,'' he wrote.
   Crucial parts of NASA's work are dependent on vendors, he noted.
   Thompson said bolts have been falsely certified by contractors
and that substandard or counterfeit electronic parts could have
created safety problems if they had not been detected.
</TEXT>
