<FIRST>u a PM-Hugo 2ndLd-Writethru a0495 09-28 0958</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0495,0982</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aid Flows into Rural Areas Devastated by Hugo</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Jesse Jackson visit; PICKS
UP 4th graf pvs, `The White ...'; SUBS grafs 19-21, `The Rev. ...' with
3 grafs to UPDATE details of Jackson visit.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. STEPHEN, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marines on bulldozers cleared the path
for volunteers driving carloads of baby food, canned goods and
clothing into rural areas cut off by Hurricane Hugo. President Bush
today said he would tour devastated areas Friday.
   ``We need him to understand how deep the human suffering is in
this,'' said Gov. Carroll Campbell. ``I want him to know that it's
a long haul for us, and it's not a quick fix.''
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson, a South Carolina native, visited some
displaced residents today and chided Bush for not having come
sooner. Also this morning, Charleston's airport reopened to limited
commercial flights and the federal government opened five offices
to take applications for relief loans and grants.
   The White House announced the president's hurriedly arranged
trip after officials flew in Wednesday to select sites to inspect.
Bush, who has declared parts of the Carolinas disaster areas, has
been criticized for not responding faster.
   A congressional delegation, led by House Majority Leader Richard
Gephardt, D-Mo., also is scheduled to visit.
   In this isolated area between Charleston and Florence, officials
said that until the Marines arrived Wednesday, some people were cut
off from food and water by Hugo's 135 mph winds and 17-foot tidal
surge a week ago today.
   ``We're trying to get it to people,'' said Gloria Pipkin,
director of a relief station in Jamestown on the edge of the
Francis Marion National Forest. ``We found today a family that did
not have food for three days.''
   Hugo contributed to 29 deaths in the United States mainland, 18
in South Carolina. The storm also killed at least 33 people in the
Carribbean.
   Almost 18,000 miles of South Carolina roads were damaged or left
covered with debris, said state Highway Department Director Joe
Rideoutte. He said it could take 18 months to clean all the roads.
   All major roads in rural Charleston and Berkeley counties are
now passable, but some dirt roads remained blocked by twisted and
fallen trees.
   ``They're coming in cars, pickups, vans and tractor-trailer
trucks,'' bringing food, clothing, baby formula and diapers and
paper plates and napkins, said Bobby Hoffman, mayor of St. Stephen,
a community of 1,970, 40 miles inland from the state's devastated
coast.
   Hoffman said volunteer fire departments and churches have opened
relief distribution points and volunteers were driving into remote
areas to deliver goods.
   To speed access, about 400 Marines from Camp Lejeune, N.C.,
moved into Jamestown and McClellanville with bulldozers to clear
roads and bring generators and water purifiers for residents still
cut off from electricity and drinking water.
   ``I feel good to see them,'' said Earthale Simmons, 53, a relief
worker in nearby Awendaw. ``That makes me think everything will go
smoothly.''
   Relief materials have been flowing into hard-hit Charleston at
an estimated 20 to 30 tractor-trailer loads a day.
   Twelve food and clothing distribution centers opened Wednesday
around the 300-year-old city, handing out everything from water to
donated clothing and canned goods.
   ``The stuff is streaming in and people are pouring in to get
it,'' said Orlando Brockingtn, who was coordinating distribution.
   Many Charleston residents stood in lines run by National
Guardsmen and sailors from the Charleston Naval Base. In addition
to food and clothing, there were ice, disposable diapers, bottled
water, plywood and roofing nails.
   Jackson said he was to be followed by a ``Rainbow Coalition of
Mercy,'' a group of union, church and political leaders who loaded
trailers with essentials to be trucked into the Carolinas this
weekend.
   Jackson, who headed to the Virgin Islands and Puerto Rico after
visiting South Carolina, charged that the federal government has
been ``too slow to move.'' He said Bush should ``not just come and
visit a house or two but to come with a plan and resources.''
   He suggested unskilled youths be trained as carpenters and
masons to help in the cleanup.
   Some officials said they could do with less federal red tape.
Charleston Mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr. said the federal government
has been slow to respond to some aspects of the disaster.
   ``I'm not sure the extent of the damage from Hugo is understood
yet at the federal level,'' he said.
   Riley, full of praise for federal relief efforts earlier this
week, told reporters he has had to seek help from Sen. Ernest
Hollings, D-S.C., to get more electricity generators.
   An estimated 233,000 customers in South Carolina remain without
power, more than half in the Charleston area. An estimated 50,000
Charleston residents remain homeless.
   Charleston International Airport, closed since Friday because of
water damage, reopened today to limited commercial airline traffic.
Seventy-five percent of the airport remained closed to the public
because of leaking roofs.
   Patra Bucher and her 7-year-old son, Beau, waited to take one of
the first flights out. Their Mount Pleasant home was still without
electricity and sustained severe roof damage.
   ``I'm getting him out of this situation, with no power and chain
saws,'' she said. ``We're starting to get real stressed-out. We're
taking him to his grandparents'' in Detroit.
   Hollings and Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., announced efforts to
get $1.1 billion in aid to the state. The Federal Emergency
Management Agency opened five offices across South Carolina today
to handle applications.
   Campbell announced Wednesday the U.S. Department of Labor has
given the state $5 million to hire jobless workers for the cleanup.
An estimated 270,600 people have temporarily lost their jobs
because of the storm.
</TEXT>
