<FIRST>u w PM-HugoHelp     09-28 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo Help,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Approves $1.1 Billion in Hurricane Hugo Disaster Relief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate passed legislation today providing
$1.1 billion for Hurricane Hugo disaster relief assistance to
Puerto Rico, the Virgin Islands, South Carolina and North Carolina.
   The emergency aid program was attached to a stopgap spending
measure aimed at keeping government agencies in business when the
new budget year begins Sunday, which passed on a vote of 100-0.
   Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., had said earlier that the damage
in his state was closer to $3 billion to $4 billion but getting
that amount would be impossible without triggering across-the-board
cuts under the Gramm-Rudman-Hollings budget balancing bill.
   Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., said, ``I have never seen so much
damage in my life. It looked there had been a war there, and we
need all the help we can get.''
   Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., told his colleagues he had been
assured by House leaders that the amendment to the temporary
spending measure containing the hurricane relief assistance would
be quickly approved by the House and sent to the White House for
President Bush's signature.
   Thurmond said the Bush administration, through the Office of
Management and Budget, had supported the request for the $1.1
billion in emergency funds.
