<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 1218EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Marcos-Reaction 4thLd-Writethru a0567 09-28 1287</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos-Reaction, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0567,1321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aquino Says Marcos Cannot Be Buried in the Philippines</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Marcos</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 19 grafs to UPDATE with people in Marcos' hometown
mourning his death. Pickup 15th graf pvs, `Shortly before...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino said today
the body of Ferdinand Marcos cannot be returned from exile for
burial because his funeral could inflame passions and create civil
unrest.
   But opposition leaders, including the vice president, called on
her to reconsider her long-held position in the interest of
national unity.
   In Marcos' home province, where he is still widely revered,
people wept when they learned of his death.
   Senior military commanders met after the death was announced,
but there was no sign of extraordinary security or of any
pro-Marcos demonstrations.
   One Marcos supporter, Oliver Lozano, said loyalists will stage a
symbolic funeral march to protest, but he did not say when.
   ``We consider the banning of President Marcos' return as an act
of unforgiveness and oppression because there is not a
constitutional and factual basis to the reason of President
Aquino,'' he said.
   Mrs. Aquino said in a statement: ``In the interest of the safety
of those who will take the death of Mr. Marcos in widely and
passionately conflicting ways, and for the tranquility of the state
and the order of society, the remains of Ferdinand E. Marcos will
not be allowed to be brought to our country until such time as the
government, be it under this administration or the succeeding one,
shall otherwise decide.''
   Mrs. Aquino _ who came to power on Feb. 25, 1986, after a
military-civilian uprising ended Marcos' 20-year rule _ issued the
statement within an hour of the announcement that he had died in
Hawaii, where he lived in exile.
   Marcos' death was announced after the close of the business day
in the Philippines, and there was little overt reaction to the
passing of the man who ruled longer than any other Filipino leader.
   Manila radio stations interrupted their programming to announce
the death, and news organizations were flooded with calls asking if
the report were true.
   Of three people approached on the street, one had not heard of
the death and the other two said they did not care.
   In the United States, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
said President Bush was ``saddened'' to hear of Marcos' death. He
said Marcos ``permitted the peaceful transition to popular
democratic rule'' by agreeing to go into exile.
   Several U.S. lawmakers said that despite Marcos'
accomplishments, he left power in disgrace.
   Although she offered condolences to Marcos' family, Mrs. Aquino
also urged Filipinos to pray that ``we preserve the gains'' won in
the uprising that ended Marcos' rule.
   She had refused to let him return for the funeral of his mother,
Josefa Edralin-Marcos, who died May 4, 1988. Her body, which has
been embalmed several times, remains at the family home in Batac,
230 miles north of Manila.
   There, people mourned Marcos' death with tears.
   ``We are all sick at heart,'' said Gigi Nalupta, 29, by
telephone from the town in Ilocos Norte province. ``We loved him
very, very much.''
   The Rev. Ruben Abaya, the Roman Catholic priest in Batac, said
special Masses would be celebrated Friday.
   ``In the hearts and minds of the people here, Marcos is the
greatest son of Batac,'' he said. ``I can foresee great mourning in
the entire Ilocos Norte.''
   Shortly before the Aquino statement today, Vice President
Salvador Laurel asked her to consider her long-held position and
let Marcos be buried at home.
   Laurel, a leading opposition figure during the Marcos era, said
his death closed a bitter period in the nation's history and that
the former dictator's body should be returned from exile for burial.
   ``My family and I wish to express our deep sympathy to the
bereaved wife and children of the late President Ferdinand E.
Marcos,'' said Laurel, who broke with Mrs. Aquino last year and
organized his own opposition party. ``The passing of former
President Marcos should now close a painful chapter in our history
and put to rest all bitterness and rancor that have divided our
people.
   ``I know, therefore, ask President Corazon Aquino to allow the
remains of the former president to be brought home and buried in
his hometown with all the honors due a former head of state of this
country.
   ``Let us now strive to bring about national reconciliation,
which we failed to achieve during his lifetime.''
   Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile also urged Mrs. Aquino to allow the
return of Marcos' body. Enrile served as Marcos' longtime defense
minister but then led the February 1986 military mutiny that
triggered the uprising that swept Mrs. Aquino to power. Enrile was
fired as defense minister on Nov. 23, 1986, after a failed coup
against Mrs. Aquino by his followers.
   ``I agree with the position that the Marcoses should return
here,'' Enrile said in a radio interview. ``I am calling on the
president to allow him to return. This would give people who
believed in the former president to give his due.''
   But Senate President Jovito Salonga, a longtime Marcos opponent,
said he will support Mrs. Aquino's decision. Salonga also said he
would ``pray for the repose of the soul and condole with all the
members of his family.''
   In her statement, Mrs. Aquino said Marcos ``touched the life of
every Filipino who was his contemprary as no other Filipino leader
did before him.''
   ``His rule changed our country,'' she said. ``In what ways he
changed it, I leave for now to others and ultimately to history to
describe. For at this moment of passage, we must allow such a loss
to transcend _ for his family _ politics and history, and the
opinions of men and women. No one should trench on the dignity of
this painful moment in the life of a family.
   ``I personally condole deeply with the family he leaves behind
with all sincerity, for I and my children know the pain of such a
loss.''
   Mrs. Aquino's husband, former Sen. Benigno Aquino, was
assassinated in August 1983 moments after he arrived at Manila's
airport to challenge Marcos for leadership of the country. He had
been in self-imposed exile in the United States. Forty people,
mostly soldiers, are on trial for his murder.
   Mrs. Aquino has foiled six armed attempts to overthrow her
government and Marcos' supporters are believed responsible for some
of them.
   Sen. Agapito Aquino, the president's brother-in-law, said he did
not expect major disturbances following Marcos' death. However, he
also said: ``Let's not be complacent because anything that could
lead to a destabilization should be curtailed at the onset.''
   Jesus Valdez, a former commissioner of the Security and Exchange
Commission, said Marcos' death may encourage stability because it
deprived pro-Marcos groups of their symbolic leader.
   In his statement, White House spokesman Fitzwater said: ``For
over 20 years, Mr. Marcos was the leader of the Philippines, a
nation that has been and remains a staunch friend and ally of the
United States.
   ``Mr. Marcos agreed to leave the Philippines at a critical
juncture in his nation's history. His departure permitted the
peaceful transition to popular, democratic rule under President
Aquino.''
   U.S. Rep. Gus Yatron, D-Pa., chairman of the House Foreign
Affairs human rights subcommittee, said any contributions Marcos
made were overshadowed by ``many years of dictatorial rule and
repression, which has left the Philippines in an economic shambles
and threatened by powerful Communist insurgency.''
   Gerald Solomon, R-N.Y., a longtime former member of the House
Foreign Affairs Committee, said Marcos was a ``true friend and ally
of the United States'' but should have relinquished power before he
was ousted.
</TEXT>
