<FIRST>r p AM-MspiElection     09-28 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mspi Election,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Republican, Two Democrats Vying in Mspi Congressional Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mississippi's 5th District congressional
seat is being fought over by a protege of the Republican who held
the seat for 16 years, the state attorney general and a
hard-campaigning state senator.
   The seat became vacant last month when freshman Rep. Larkin
Smith, a Republican, was killed in the crash of a small plane.
   The candidates in Tuesday's open primary _ where all candidates
run in one race _ are Tom Anderson, long-time aide to U.S. Sen.
Trett Lott, R-Miss., state Attorney General Mike Moore and state
Sen. Gene Taylor, who lost to Smith a year ago. Anderson is
Republican; Moore and Taylor are both Democrats.
   Lott held the 5th District post for 16 years before winning
election to the Senate in 1988. Smith, viewed as a rising GOP star,
was sworn into office in January.
   If no candidate wins a majority Tuesday, the top two
vote-getters will meet in a runoff Oct. 17.
   Although Democrats control most statehouse offices, the 5th
District, which skirts the Gulf Coast, has been held by
conservatives since the 1932 election of the late Bill Colmer, a
Democrat. Colmer held the post until 1972 when he was succeeded by
his then-aide, Lott.
   Lott threw his support to Anderson, 45, his chief congressional
aide for 16 years. Anderson has roots in the populous Mississippi
Gulf Coast but has spent his adult life in Washington, where he
owns pizza parlors and rental property. It is his first political
race.
   Moore, 37, took office in January 1988, and also has strong ties
to the Gulf Coast, while Taylor is a two-term legislator who is the
only one of the trio who has ever run for congression.
   Taylor, 36, got 46 percent of the vote against the better-known
Smith in the November 1988 general election. Taylor has counted on
his name recognition to continue his door-to-door campaign style.
   Some people note that Moore and Taylor are both natives who have
stayed in Mississippi, while Anderson worked for Lott in Washington
and served a brief tenure as ambassador to Barbados.
   Moore has been criticized for wanting to leave the attorney
general's office after only 21 months. He is considered as
political ambitious as Mississippi's youthful governor, Ray Mabus.
   Taylor has had to contend with an $8,000 deficit from his 1988
congressional race and deep inroads into his conservative
Democratic support by Moore.
   The war on drugs has been a recurring theme in the campaign with
Anderson contending that during his two years as ambassador to
Barbados he was the Reagan administration's point man against the
drug lords in the Caribbean.
   Moore has countered that he was prosecuting drug dealers while
Anderson was in Washington serving as nothing more than Lott's
right-hand man.
   ``The only thing he pointed at was the planes as they flew over
loaded with dope,'' Moore has said of Anderson's service in the
Caribbean.
   Taylor has stayed out of the political ambushing.
</TEXT>
