<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 1234EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MiscarriageReport     09-28 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Miscarriage Report,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miscarriage Rate in Louisiana `Chemical Belt' Not Out of Line</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. GABRIEL, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rate of miscarriages in this section
of Louisiana's Chemical Belt is no greater than in any other part
of the country, Tulane University scientists said.
   The university's School of Public Health and Tropical Medicine
began the study nearly two years ago after informal research by a
St. Gabriel pharmacist logged more than 60 miscarriages by 50 women
over three years.
   One hundred residents attending a community meeting to hear the
report Wednesday night didn't like what they heard.
   ``I think it was a mockery. The pain we went through in this
community. The team wanted a sterile, statistical report. And
that's what they got,'' said Sandi LeBlanc, who had a miscarriage
in 1986.
   Tulane scientists examined hospital and doctor records and
surveyed women living in St. Gabriel, Sunset and Carrville, all
along the Mississippi River below Baton Rouge. The women had been
pregnant in 1982 through 1987.
   The river area between Baton Rouge and New Orleans is known as
the Chemical Belt. Dozens of petrochemical plants dot both sides of
the river.
   LuAnn White, a toxicologist and member of the Tulane team, said
there was no significant association between the proximity to
industrial sites and the miscarriages.
   The researchers said they were able to identify 372 live births,
seven stillbirths and 69 miscarriages among 354 women. Fifteen of
the miscarriages were disregarded because documentation was
unavailable, said White.
   The overall documented miscarriage rate was 12.7 percent of all
pregnancies, White said. She said that was comparable to figures
anywhere in the nation.
   Peggy Hoffman, one of those interviewed, complained that the
statistics didn't include miscarriages by those who didn't go to
hospitals and those under 18.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890928-0089 </DOCNO>
