<FIRST>r i PM-Rushdie 1stLd-Writethru a0580 09-28 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rushdie, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0580,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rushdie Sues Magazine Over Sexually Explicit Illustrations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd graf, `Passages in...' with 1 graf to ADD that magazine
the first in France to publish excerpts of the novel. Pickup 4th pvs, `Forty-eight...'
Willem is cq as one name in 6th graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYN AUGUST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From his hiding place, author Salman Rushdie has
teamed up with his French publisher to sue a magazine for printing
an unofficial translation of ``The Satanic Verses'' illustrated by
sexually explicit drawings.
   Emil Malet, director of the trendy intellectual magazine
Passages, was quoted today in the daily Liberation as saying
Rushdie is suing the magazine despite the fact that it admitted it
made a mistake and withdrew most of the issues in question.
   Passages in July became the first magazine in France to publish
selections from Rushdie's controversial novel. It published them
along with drawings that Rushdie's publisher, Christian Bourgois,
called ``frankly scatological.''
   Forty-eight hours after meeting with Bourgois, Malet withdrew
the issue from newsstands, he said, and also removed 3,000 posters
advertising the issue. Only 5,000 of 75,000 copies were sold, he
said.
   Nonetheless, Rushdie and Bourgeois filed suit in July, asking
$48,000 for ``counterfeiting'' the translation without Rushdie's
authorization. A hearing is set for Oct. 4.
   The publisher and Rushdie found offensive the magazine's
headline _ ``Explosive _ The Prophet's Satanic Women, Rushdie's
Erotics,'' _ as well as the drawings by illustrator Willem.
   Malet said that by filing suit, Rushdie and Bourgois were trying
to kill the magazine.
   ``Does Rushdie want our death?'' Malet was quoted as telling the
leftist French daily Liberation. ``We have no money, if we're
convicted, we'll go bankrupt.''
   Malet said the magazine has more than made up for its mistake by
withdrawing the offensive material from circulation and later
publishing an editorial admitting ``we had made an error.''
   ``No Moslem association has complained, and the book, published
by Christian Bourgois has sold very well. What's more, we defended
Rushdie, whom we compared to Voltaire,'' he was quoted as saying.
   Bourgois was not available for comment.
   In February, Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini called on Moslems
worldwide to kill Rushdie because, he said, ``The Satanic Verses''
blasphemed Islam.
   After Rushdie was threatened and Islamic clerics placed a
multimillion dollar bounty on his head, Bourgois suspended
publication of the work in French from February until July.
   ``The Satanic Verses'' is now No. nine on the best-seller list
in France.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
