<FIRST>r i AM-Gulf-USCrash     09-28 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gulf-US Crash,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Army Pilots Rescued After Gulf Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two U.S. Army pilots were rescued unhurt
from the Persian Gulf after their small helicopter crashed during a
night patrol exercise, the Navy said Thursday.
   The OH-58D helicopter was operating from the missile frigate USS
Rentz when the crash occurred, 65 miles northeast of Bahrain about
10 p.m. Wednesday, said Petty Officer Joseph Bartlett, spokesman
for the Navy's gulf-based force.
   A Navy helicopter from the Rentz recovered the two pilots, whose
identities were withheld.
   The Army helicopters, part of a special operations unit based at
Fort Bragg, N.C., are equipped to fly in darkness with little noise.
   They were brought to the gulf in 1987 to augment Navy protection
of U.S.-flagged shipping during the Iran-Iraq war. Most were
withdrawn after a cease-fire in August last year.
   Bartlett said two U.S. mine sweepers were ordered to the crash
scene to help determine whether the wreckage could be raised from
about 230 feet of water.
   He said the cause of the crash was not known, adding that there
were no indications of trouble before the craft hit the water.
</TEXT>
