<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 1301EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-ArmsTalks     09-28 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arms Talks,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Meet to Prepare New U.S.-Soviet Round</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Soviet officials met Thursday to prepare
a new round of arms talks, in which negotiators will be under
pressure to get a treaty slashing long-range nuclear arsenals ready
for signing at next year's summit.
   Prospects for progress in the 4{-year-old negotiations were
improved by Soviet concessions at weekend talks between Foreign
Minister Eduard Shevardnadze and U.S. Secretary of State James A.
Baker III in Wyoming. But officials on both sides also warned
against underestimating the work still ahead.
   President Bush said Wednesday the setting of his first summit
with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev early next summer is ``a
catalyst for moving forward'' on the draft Strategic Arms Reduction
Treaty, or START. Shevardnadze told the U.N. General Assembly of
``realistic prospects'' for halving superpower nuclear arsenals by
the summit.
   However, Defense Secretary Dick Cheney said the Soviets are
modernizing their armed forces and still threaten ``the very
survival'' of the United States, despite Gorbachev's promised
cutbacks and pledges of reform.
   Officials met Thursday to set meeting schedules for the new
round of talks. The first full meeting of both delegations is
scheduled Monday. It is not known how long the session will last.
   START is intended to cut by up to 50 percent the land-, air- and
sea-based nuclear missiles with which each superpower can strike
the other. Both sides have already agreed to lowered ceilings of
missiles, bombers and nuclear warheads.
   Yuri Nazarkin, chief Soviet negotiator in Geneva, said he could
predict the chances of early agreement only after Washington
formally responds at the bargaining table to the recent Soviet
moves.
   Shevardnadze removed a long-standing obstacle by announcing
Moscow would no longer let its objections to U.S. plans for
space-based missile defenses block signing of a START pact. Moscow
also agreed to a U.S. demand for dealing with sea-based cruise
missiles outside START.
   The Bush administration earlier dropped its demand for a ban on
mobile intercontinental ballistic missiles provided Congress
approves funding for such missiles. The Soviets have such missiles,
but the United States does not.
</TEXT>
