<FIRST>u w PM-US-Colombia 1stLd-Writethru a0445 09-28 0780</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Colombia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0445,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Weighs Closer Trade Ties With Colombia as Barco Visits</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: TOP 9 grafs news to UPDATE with Bennett-Barco meeting; pickup
4th graf pvs: `` A new:''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombian President Virgilio Barco assured the
United States today it had properly shaped its emergency military
aid to help his government battle drug traffickers, but he sought
more help on the economic and trade fronts, according to drug
control policy director William J. Bennett.
   The administration is weighing options for assisting Colombia
economically while it battles the traffickers. U.S. officials have
said trade concessions are being considered for some Colombian
exports such as cut flowers and textiles, among other products.
Another possibility is providing inducements for U.S. private
investment in Colombia.
   ``President Barco talked about an array of things,'' including
trade issues such as coffee and flowers, Bennett said, adding that
he referred the matters to U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills,
with whom Barco was to meet later today.
   ``A number of these things we'll take up again later at a
meeting at the White House'' with President Bush, Bennett said
after the hour-long meeting with Barco and Colombian Gen. Guillermo
Munoz Sanabria that was held under tight security at the Colombian
ambassador's residence.
   During the meeting, the officials discussed the current
situation in Colombia, where Barco ordered emergency measures to
crack down on drug traffickers following the Aug. 18 assassination
of leading presidential candidate Luis Carlos Gala.
   Those measures, including the resumption of extradition to the
United States of suspected drug traffickers, prompted the
traffickers to declare ``total war'' on the government. They have
set off bombs around the country, killed several people at the
Bogota airport, and have vowed to kill 10 judges for every
trafficker extradited.
   Some Colombian officials have said the $65 million in emergency
U.S. assistance does not suit their needs. They have said they need
better police equipment to help track down the traffickers, while
the U.S. aid is primarily military equipment such as helicopters
and other troop transport vehicles as well as training by military
advisors.
   ``I was reassured by all present that the assistance we were
providing was the right assistance, it helped,'' Bennett said.
   Barco, who is to address the United Nations General Assembly on
Friday, has become a White House favorite since his government
began cracking down in earnest on cocaine cartels last month.
   A report surfaced Wednesday that Colombian drug barons had
threatened to kidnap one of Bush's children if the two governments
don't back off their anti-narcotics campaigns.
   Bush said he won't be ``deterred by rumors,'' adding he has
confidence in the ability of the Secret Service to do its job.
   Bush's meeting with Barco was taking place against a background
of a U.S.-Colombian disagreement over trade in coffee, Colombia's
main legal export.
   Last week, Bush rejected a plea by Barco for a one-year
reinstatement of a coffee-export quota system that had been
beneficial to Colombian farmers.
   Colombian coffee prices have fallen sharply since the 74-nation
International Coffee Agreement collapsed in July after United
States pulled out in a dispute with coffee-producing nations over
prices.
   Colombian officials have suggested they will have an even more
difficult time persuading hard-pressed Colombian farmers to grow
coffee instead of coca if coffee export prices continue to slip.
   The administration announced several weeks ago it is sending $65
million worth of equipment to Colombia's police and military forces
to combat cocaine smugglers.
   Britain announced Wednesday it will give ``substantial''
anti-terrorist aid, training, communications and other help to
Colombia in its drug war. British Foreign Secretary John Major made
the announcement to the U.N. General Assembly in New York but he
did not mention a dollar amount.
   Before leaving for Washington, Barco told Colombians that
democracy was at stake in the fight against cocaine traffickers.
   ``This criminal organization wants to destroy the most precious
thing Colombians have _ their democracy,'' he said in a speech
Tuesday.
   Administration officials said there has been a significant
disruption in the cocaine industry as a result of the Colombian
government's crackdown. The price of semi-refined coca paste is
down to $600 a kilogram, from $1,200 before the crackdown, the
officials said.
   Barco's visit comes on the heels of a peace accord his
government signed on Tuesday with the leftist M-19 guerrilla group.
   The treaty calls for M-19's estimated 2,000 guerrillas to turn
in their weapons in exchange for pardons and the right to form a
political party.
   The treaty also calls for a national referendum on 53 proposals,
including agrarian reform to give land to peasants and programs to
provide more housing for the poor.
</TEXT>
