<FIRST>u a PM-ArtilleryAccident 4thLd-Writethru a0584 09-28 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Artillery Accident, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0584,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>Errant Shell Kills Three Soldiers, Injures 23</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 17 grafs to UPDATE with quotes from hospital commander
and safety official, information about howitzers. PICKS UP 16th graf, `He
said ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LAW1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FERGUSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT SILL, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Victims of a firing-range accident that
killed three soldiers and injured 23 heard the whistle of an
incoming artillery shell just before they were ``blown off their
feet,'' a commander said today.
   Two more soldiers were killed at Fort Stewart, Ga., today during
firing exercises involving 4.2-inch mortars, the Army said. Details
were not immediately released.
   In Wednesday's accident, a round from a howitzer overshot the
target area and hit 10 to 15 feet behind soldiers lined up in
formation on a rifle range, authorities said.
   If the artillery fired from a practice range had hit 10 to 15
minutes later, the rifle range would have been empty, said Lt. Col.
John Dobbs.
   ``If you had to write a worst-case scenario where soldiers are
injured or killed by artillery rounds out of the impact area, this
is it,'' he said. ``The round landed at a time when the soldiers
were in a formation and were in close proximity.''
   The cause of the accident was under investigation. Dobbs said
two possible explanations were that the howitzer was aimed
incorrectly or the wrong amount of gunpowder was used.
   Remnants of uniforms and helmets littered the ground on the
rifle range in the shadow of the Wichita Mountains. The site was
roped off and reporters were kept from talking with soldiers. A
crater a yard across and a foot deep was visible.
   ``They heard a whistle of incoming, a yellow blast and then they
were blown off their feet,'' said Col. William Gonzales, commander
of the post hospital. ``It's amazing what the power of a shell can
do.''
   Pvt. 1 Jimmy N. McCain, 21, of Troy, Ala., and Spec. Thomas P.
Boyle, 25, of Ventura, Calif., were killed, along with a third
soldier whose name was withheld until notification of relatives,
said Master Sgt. Michael Brown, a post spokesman.
   The injured were taken by helicopter and ambulance to Reynolds
Army Hospital. Six soldiers underwent surgery Wednesday night,
Gonzales said. He said one soldier whom he would not identify had a
leg amputated.
   Staff Sgt. Scott Harris of Rockmart, Ga., and Pvt. 1 David
Saltsman of Dayton, Texas, were in critical condition, and Pvt. 1
David Adams of Vinemont, Ala., Pvt. 1 Troy Emmons of Hubbard, Neb.,
Pvt. 1 Charles McCrossen of Mason, Ohio, and Pvt. 1 David Mechem of
Wichita, Kan., were in serious condition, said post spokesman Daran
Neal.
   Sixteen other soldiers remained in hospitals and were listed in
stable or good condition today.
   The soldiers were a week away from completing an eight-week
training course, said Staff Sgt. William Biel, another post
spokesman.
   Fort Sill investigators were joined today by a team from the
Army Safety Center in Fort Rucker, Ala. A preliminary report may
not be ready for a day or two.
   ``We'll review everything that's happened here and use our
findings to prevent future accidents,'' said Gen. Lou Hennies,
director of Army safety at Fort Rucker.
   The Army's Field Artillery Center at Fort Sill has three sizes
of howitzers _ 105mm, 155mm and 8-inch. Hennies said all three were
being used Wednesday and investigators must determine which was
involved in the accident.
   ``We have to analyze the craters and interview all the units on
the range,'' said Jon Long, another post spokesman.
   He said the accident site was about four miles from the
populated area of the post, which has 21,000 soldiers.
   The last fatal accident involving artillery at the post was in
1978, when a shell exploded aboard an ammunition-carrying vehicle,
killing one soldier and wounding four.
</TEXT>
