<FIRST>u a PM-NightStalker 1stLd-Writethru a0499 09-28 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Night Stalker, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0499,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Weighs Life or Death for Serial Killer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with deliberations under way; PICKS
UP 5th graf pvs, `Defense lawyer ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury today began deciding whether the
``Night Stalker'' killer should live or die after a plea from a
prosecutor to ``face this type of evil'' without flinching and give
Richard Ramirez the death penalty.
   The panel on Sept. 20 found the 29-year-old, devil-worshiping
drifter guilty of 13 murders and 30 felonies in the crime spree
that terrorized California during the summer of 1985.
   The jury also found special circumstances that made him eligible
for the death penalty. But the panel could also recommend life in
prison without parole.
   Defense lawyer Ray Clark, acknowledging the horror of Ramirez's
satanic killings, argued that even if Ramirez was possessed by the
devil, he deserves mercy.
   ``I think it's inescapable that something was wrong (with
Ramirez) and we don't know what it was,'' said Clark. ``Let's say
we believe he was possessed, if there is such a thing. Then the
extension of mercy goes to the devil because he is considerably
more in need of mercy than anybody else.''
   ``Richard Ramirez ... has no claim to your kindness,'' Clark
told the jury. ``But if you give him kindness, then that's what
mercy is.''
   Deputy District Attorney P. Philip Halpin urged death in the gas
chamber for Ramirez, whom he described as ``a miserable human
being'' who killed for gratification.
   Halpin argued that jurors must not be afraid to confront the
evil of Ramirez' acts, and vote for his execution.
   ``It is very difficult for us, as human beings, to face this
type of evil, without trying to deny it, without trying to
rationalize it, without trying to explain it away,'' the prosecutor
said in a hushed courtroom.
   ``You have to look this case right in the face,'' he told
jurors. ``If anyone has ever earned the death penalty, Richard
Ramirez has. I urge you to vote for the death penalty.''
   The shaggy-haired Ramirez, wearing his blue jail uniform at his
own request, paid no attention to either lawyer, choosing instead
to chat quietly with members of the defense team at the counsel
table.
   Earlier in the day, Ramirez's attorneys announced they would
call no witnesses in the penalty phase of his trial because Ramirez
``didn't see any need to put his life on display.''
   Attorney Daniel Hernandez, who said he had 100 witnesses lined
up to testify about Ramirez's ``value as a human being'' and his
early life in El Paso, Texas, told reporters he abandoned the plan
at Ramirez's request.
   ``I felt and he felt he didn't particularly want to lay his life
out for the public and the court to scrutinize,'' said Hernandez.
``I wanted to give him the last grain of dignity _ human dignity _
and spare him that.''
</TEXT>
