<SECOND>AM-BRF--Illegal Refunds,0137</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Pleads Guilty In Manufacturer Rebate Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNIONTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 68-year-old woman has pleaded guilty to
illegally collecting more than $50,000 in rebates from
manufacturers.
   Marie Haley of Uniontown entered the plea Wednesday to two
counts of mail fraud, and federal prosecutors agreed to dismiss
seven others.
   Ms. Haley was indicted June 6 on the nine counts for collecting
$50,609 in rebates from 1979 to 1988.
   Ms. Haley, a secretary for a coal-mining company for 50 years,
had submitted about 27,000 product refund forms using false names
and addresses and receipts supplied by friends and relatives,
according to Assistant U.S. Attorney Gregory Nescott.
   The woman faces a maximum of five years in prison on each count
and up to $250,000 in fines. Sentencing was scheduled for Nov. 16.
