<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 1355EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Marcos 7thLd-Writethru a0608 09-28 0731</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos, 7th Ld - Writethru, a0608,0747</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos Dies in Exile at 72; `Father's Not Here Anymore'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 10th graf pvs, `In Marcos' ...' to UPDATE
with commentU.S. consulate, FAA on alert; Breaks into two takes.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserColor NY9, LaserPhotos NY10, NY11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ferdinand E. Marcos, former president of the
Philippines, died today, ending in defiant exile a life that took
him to the pinnacles of power and worldwide notoriety in his
impoverished land. He was 72.
   Corazon Aquino, who came to power in the 1986 uprising that
drove Marcos from his homeland, refused again to allow his burial
in the Philippines for the sake of ``the tranquility of the state
and the order of society.''
   Marcos died at 12:40 a.m. (6:40 a.m. EDT), said Eugene Tiwanak,
spokesman at St. Francis Medical Center, where Marcos had been
hospitalized nearly 10 months with kidney, lung and heart ailments,
pneumonia and bacterial infections.
   At 1:17 a.m., Marcos' son, Ferdinand Jr., emerged from the
hospital room and announced his father had been taken to ``a higher
place.''
   ``Hopefully friends and detractors alike will look beyond the
man to see what he stood for _ his vision, his compassion and his
total love of country,'' the younger Marcos said. He said no
funeral arrangements have been made.
   ``Father's not here anymore. He's gone,'' Marcos' widow, Imelda,
told about two dozen supporters outside the hospital room, said
family spokesman Roger Peyuan.
   The canny, combative politician, who governed at times as a
democrat, at times as a dictator, had settled into exile in
Honolulu at a hillside estate overlooking the Pacific. He died
under U.S. indictment on charges he plundered the Philippine
treasury during his two decades in power.
   President Bush, who during a trip to Manila in 1981 praised
Marcos and his government for ``your adherence to democratic
principles,'' said today he was saddened to hear of Marcos' death
and offered condolences to the family.
   Former President Reagan said, ``Nancy and I are deeply saddened
and extend our sympathy and prayers to his family.''
   In Marcos' home province, where he is still widely revered,
people wept when they learned of his death. In Manila, senior
military commanders met, but there was no sign of extraordinary
security or any pro-Marcos demonstrations. One supporter, Oliver
Lozano, said loyalists will hold a symbolic funeral march, but he
did not say when.
   ``I hope it can contribute to the healing process in our
country,'' Narciso Reyes, Jr., spokesman for the Philippine
Consulate at the United Nations, said of Marcos' death.
   In Washington, the State Department, noting the wishes of the
Philippine government, said the Federal Aviation Administration is
taking steps to prevent any flight from carrying Marcos' body to
his homeland.
   Marcos had been hospitalized three times since December, lapsing
in and out of critical condition. The family had instructed doctors
to take every measure to save his life, and life-support equipment
was not turned off until after death, Peyuan said. Doctors had
implanted a pacemaker on Wednesday.
   Peyuan said Marcos' son arrived from California just in time to
see his father alive one last time. Also with Marcos at his death
were his wife and Mrs. Marcos' sister, Peyuan said.
   Peyuan said Marcos opened his eyes briefly about 30 minutes
before his death. ``I think he wanted one last look at his son,''
the spokesman said.
   Of Mrs. Marcos, Peyuan said, ``She is holding up with great
dignity. They were still hoping to give him a more dignified end.''
She left the hospital without comment.
   Mrs. Aquino, who in May rejected appeals from Mrs. Marcos that
he be buried on Philippine soil, again said no after Vice President
Salvador Laurel asked her to reconsider.
   ``In the interest of the safety of those who will take the death
of Mr. Marcos in widely and passionately conflicting ways, and for
the tranquility of the state and the order of society, the remains
of Ferdinand E. Marcos will not be allowed to be brought to our
country until such time as the government, be it under this
administration or the succeeding one, shall otherwise decide,''
Mrs. Aquino said in a statement.
   Mrs. Marcos said in April she would embalm her husband's body
and display it in Hawaii until she could return and scatter his
ashes to ``fertilize'' the Philippines.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
