<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--BullEscape     09-28 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Bull Escape,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bull Traps Five People in Convenience Store</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELLINGHAM, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pet bull named Fernando wandered from
a pasture and trapped five people in a convenience store for 45
minutes, until a veterinarian shot him with a tranquilizer dart.
   No one was injured in the escapade Wednesday, but it prompted
the owner of the 1,500-pound Jersey bull to make plans for his sale
next week.
   The 2-year-old bull hemmed in customers at the Country Market,
charging the building, gasoline pumps and denting a pickup truck,
said store manager Linda Eshuis.
   ``It was as scared as it was angry,'' Trooper Ken Van Kooten
said.
   Fernando broke through a barbed wire fence to escape the nearby
pasture.
   The pet's owner, Ishmael Gomberoff, was called to the store,
along with veterinarian Gordon Plotts, who tranquilized the bull. A
groggy Fernando eventually followed his owner home.
   Gomberoff was charged with allowing the bull on a right of way.
   ``He's just a sweetheart,'' Wayne Davis, an employee of
Gomberoff's, said. ``He's so tame when he's not around filling
stations.''
</TEXT>
