<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Tourism Ads,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>N.C. Pulls Tourism Ad That Tweaked Hurricane-Ravaged S.C.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The damage caused by Hurricane Hugo has led
North Carolina tourism officials to change an advertisement that
would have denigrated golf courses in South Carolina.
   The advertisement, scheduled to start next month in newspapers
north of North Carolina, originally read: ``For Great Golf, South
Carolina Should Be Your Last Resort.''
   ``Those people down there are really hurting,'' Dick Trammell,
new director of the state Travel and Tourism Division, said of
South Carolina. ``We just didn't think this would be appropriate
right now.''
   The ad will be replaced by one that reads: ``For Great Golf,
North Carolina Should Be Your First Resort,'' Rick Myracle of
McKinney &amp; Silver Advertising told tourism officials Wednesday.
   ``Even though we compete with each other, the tourism agencies
in Virginia, North Carolina, South Carolina and the other Southern
states have a good relationship,'' Trammell said. ``We'll fight
each other for tourists, but we help each other when we need it,
too.''
