<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     09-28 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Staying out of your car in this Seattle
suburb can pay off.
   The city will begin next month reimbursing its employees who
carpool, use public transportation, bicycle or walk to work.
   Full-time city employees who use such an alternative at least
three days a week will be paid $25 a month. Part-time employees who
do the same will be paid $15 a month. In addition, the city will
annually reimburse employees for up to 40 miles' worth of emergency
cab fare.
   Kirkland officials say they want to do their part to reduce
traffic congestion in the city of 20,000. They also say they hope
their program, expected to cost up to $16,000 a year, will set an
example for businesses to follow _ on foot, of course. About 92
percent of the city's 230 employees ride to work alone.
   ``We feel it is a good thing for the city to take a leadership
role,'' said Andy Barton, assistant to the city manager.
   Bellevue, another Seattle suburb, has offered similar incentives
for its employees since 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sharon Hope's business is picking up _ after
customers' pets.
   ``When I moved back to Tulsa, I knew I wanted to start a company
and so I tried to find a niche,'' said Ms. Hope, who lived in
Denver for several years before returning to Oklahoma several
months ago.
   Her niche is ``Poop Van Scoop,'' a local cleanup service for pet
owners that lets them have the joy of pet ownership without any of
the smelly side effects.
   ``It's probably not a job everyone would want to do, but it
really isn't bad at all,'' she said.
   For $11.95 a month, Ms. Hope will make a weekly visit and clean
up after one pet. Owners of more than one pet get a discount for
any additional animals.
   Her customer base has grown ``from just a few friends'' to about
50 homes.
   ``It's really not that bad. I use a Sanitary Scooper _ which
used to be named the Pooper Scooper _ and just pick up where the
dog left off,'' she said.
</TEXT>
