<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 1613EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-LowFlying     09-28 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Low Flying,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Minister Proposes Cuts to Reduce Noise, Hazards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced Thursday it
is seeking a 25 percent cut in low-level flying exercises that have
been the target of national protests since a crash at an air show
last year killed 70 people.
   Defense Minister Gerhard Stoltenberg introduced the proposed
reductions, aimed at cutting noise and protecting populated areas
from accident hazards, during a session of the Parliament's Defense
Committee.
   Stoltenberg told reporters later that the changes were worked
out in conjunction with the United States and other NATO countries
that have aircraft and pilots stationed in West Germany.
   One tactical training center involved in low-level flying
exercises is being relocated to neighboring Belgium, and
negotiations are continuing with other allies to export more of the
missions, Stoltenberg said.
   Of the 68,000 hours of low-level training exercises flown over
West German territory this year, only about 23,000 involve West
German air force aircraft and personnel.
   West Germans have staged noisy demonstrations over the past year
against low-flying and other military exercises.
   The protesters have accused the government of failing to assert
its sovereignty in getting NATO to reduce the number of disruptive
maneuvers, turning the issue into a major political battle between
the governing conservative-led coalition and opposition leftists.
   Opposition has intensified since Aug. 28, 1988, when three
Italian planes crashed during an air show at the U.S. Air Base at
Ramstein. Seventy people died when the flaming wreckage flew into
the crowd of spectators.
   Another crash, on Dec. 8 in the city of Remscheid, killed six
West Germans and the American pilot.
   Neither of the disasters involved low-flying exercises, but they
stirred up broad opposition to the foreign military presence in
West Germany.
   The leftist Social Democrats have been campaigning for a ban on
low-level training flights.
   ``A full halt to low-level flying would put our commitment to
the NATO alliance in question,'' Stoltenberg told reporters.
   Instead, he said, the ministry has worked out a number of
measures to address public concerns, including:
   _ A 25 percent reduction in low-level training flights over West
German territory.
   _ A 50 percent reduction of West German air force training
flights, already put into force.
   _ An increase in the number of areas off-limits to exercises,
from 25 to 61 densely populated municipal regions.
   _ A midday break in the exercises in summer months and no
flights on weekends and holidays.
   _ Reduction of maximum allowable speeds from 1,336 mph to 1,244
mph to cut noise from the exercises.
   As the measures already reportedly have allied backing, they are
expected to be approved by the Parliament.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890928-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 1615EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FosterCare     09-28 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foster Care,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Foster Care Children: An Uncertain Existence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A disproportionate number of black children
wind up in foster care homes because of poverty, abuse and neglect,
according to a study released Thursday.
   Such children are also unlikely to be reunited with their
parents ``in a reasonable period of time,'' according to the
report, ``Who Will Care When Parents Can't.'' The study was
conducted by the National Black Child Development Institute, an
educational and advocacy group.
   ``In our study, we found that the black child in foster care has
lived and is still living an uncertain and fragmented existence,''
said Clarice Walker, a Howard University professor and chief
investigator in the study.
   In 1986, when the study was conducted, there were 275,000 to
350,000 children of all races in foster care systems around the
country, she said. Black children accounted for 25 percent to 40
percent of the total; the numbers are approximate because of poor
record keeping, she said.
   The study looked at 1,003 children in foster care programs in
five cities _ New York, Miami, Houston, Detroit and Seattle.
   Almost half the children, or 49 percent, were age 5 or younger
at placement. Forty-six percent came from single-parent households.
The median age of mothers when a child was placed in foster care
was 29; of fathers, 34, the study found.
   Seventy-five percent of all children who entered the foster care
system were there because of abuse or neglect, the study found.
   In Detroit, Miami and New York, neglect was the No. 1 family
factor contributing to foster care placement; in Houston, child
abuse was first, and in Seattle, voluntary placement topped the
list.
   Drug abuse by parents was the second most prevalent family
factor in New York, Miami and Seattle, the study found. Half the
cases in New York and Miami reported drug abuse by parents.
   In New York City alone, 43 percent of the cases studied found
the children were unattended or unsupervised upon entering the
foster care system; 41 percent of the cases reported return of the
parent was uncertain.
   Sometimes the children themselves have physical or emotional
problems that contribute to their winding up in foster care, the
study noted.
   However, it found that overall, ``the proportion of
child-related factors contributing to placement was not very
great.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
