<FIRST>u a PM-CanyonCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0489 09-28 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Canyon Crash, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0489,0681</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sightseeing Plane Crashes Near Grand Canyon; 10 Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with investigators arriving, FAA records
on previous accident. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos PN1,2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM F. RAWSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUSAYAN, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators trying to determine
the cause of a crash that killed 10 people aboard a sightseeing
plane went today to the hill where the aircraft went down on
approach to Grand Canyon Airport.
   The pilot and co-pilot were among those killed Wednesday when
the de Havilland DHC-6 Twin Otter veered from the runway into the
wooded hill 300 yards away, authorities said. Eleven people were
injured, eight critically.
   Tall Ponderosa pines sheared off the wings of the Grand Canyon
Airlines plane, but the fuselage remained intact.
   ``We were very fortunate that this didn't burst into flames, or
we'd have lost a lot more victims,'' said sheriff's Detective Lt.
Jack Judd.
   National Park Service Ranger Paul Crawford said some of the
passengers were walking around when he arrived.
   ``They were shellshocked. They had that empty, dazed look,''
Crawford said.
   A team of investigators from the National Transportation Safety
Board went to the crash site this morning.
   A sheriff's deputy removed a video camera from the wreckage, but
it was not known what the tape had captured, or even if it had been
in use while the plane was landing at the airport, situated about
five miles south of the Grand Canyon.
   Federal Aviation Administration records said the plane on Feb.
27 ``lost directional control on landing. Struck wingtip on runway.
Possible nose-wheel centering problem.'' The records indicated only
two crew members were aboard and neither was injured. The FAA
records listed wind as a contributing cause, and Ronald L. Warren,
Grand Canyon Airlines vice president and general manager, said this
morning he didn't know the final determination of the cause.
   He said the plane veered to the right on Feb. 27 and that it
went off to the left Wednesday. On Feb. 27, the plane was piloted
by a then-new employee who was being checked out by the pilot
killed in Wednesday's crash, Warren said.
   Warren said the plane in Wednesday's crash was on its second
flight of the day and making its final approach to the airport. He
said the plane, with 19 passengers and two crew members, had a
one-hour, 100-mile flight over the canyon.
   The plane hit the runway, bounced back up in the air about 100
feet then veered to the left and struck a power line and into a
ridge, Judd said.
   All the passengers were Americans, Warren said. The dead
included John Sutton, a Modesto, Calif., city councilman, and his
wife, Donna, said Modesto Mayor Carol Whiteside.
   The injured were taken by ambulance, airplane and helicopter to
the Flagstaff Medical Center, about 75 miles away. Eight were
listed in critical condition. The 11th survivor was released from
the hospital.
   Warren said when the 14-year-old plane reached the airport,
skies were clear, winds were light and temperatures normal.
   The pilot was in his mid-40s and had worked for the airline for
4{ years, Warren said. The co-pilot was in his mid-20s and in his
first year with the airline.
   No cockpit voice recorder or flight data recorder was aboard
because the devices are not manufactured for that type of aircraft,
Warren said.
   In 1986, a Grand Canyon Airlines plane collided with a
sightseeing helicopter inside the canyon, killing 25 people. In
1983, 10 people died when a sightseeing charter plane from Las
Vegas smashed into a cliff near the canyon's South Rim. A
crash-investigation report said the pilot encountered rough weather
and could not climb out of the canyon.
   In Washington, NTSB spokesman Mike Benson said the de Havilland
Twin Otter has been involved in 77 accidents since 1962, including
25 that killed a total of 135 people. During that period, the board
lists 89 accidents at the Grand Canyon, including 28 that resulted
in 105 fatalities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
