<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--CDC-Abortion     09-28 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--CDC-Abortion,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Numbers Holding Relatively Steady Since '80</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release 6 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of legal abortions performed in the
United States has held largely steady throughout the 1980s, U.S.
health officials said Thursday.
   A total of 1,353,671 legal abortions were performed in the
United States in 1987, an increase of just under 2 percent from
1,328,112 in 1986, the national Centers for Disease Control said in
its weekly report.
   The total compares with 1,297,606 in 1980 and 1,333,521 in 1984.
   The actual number has risen somewhat, as has the U.S.
population, since 1980, but the rate of abortions has fallen
slightly. In 1987, health officials reported 356 abortions for
every 1,000 live births, compared to 359 in 1980, the Atlanta-based
CDC said.
   Twenty-six percent of the women having abortions in 1987, the
latest year for which statistics are available, were under 20.
Thirty-three percent were 20-24, and 41 percent were 25 or older.
   Seventy-three percent were unmarried, and 54 percent had never
given birth.
</TEXT>
