<SECOND>AM-BRF--Phone Talks,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>Phone Talks Make Little Progress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first informal bargaining in two weeks between
striking telephone workers and New England Telephone Co. began and
ended Thursday when company officials rejected a new union proposal.
   Union officials presented a proposal in which they scaled back
wage increase demands to 4 percent for first year workers and a 1
percent for second and third year in addition to cost-of-living
adjustments, said officials for the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers.
   New England Telephone spokesman Peter Cronin said he could not
comment.
   After the company rejected the proposal, union members requested
a meeting over the weekend. A date has not been set.
   The strike against NYNEX, the parent company of New England
Telephone, in New York and New England has gone eight weeks. More
than 40,000 workers are on strike. It has produced consumer
complaints, allegations of widespread vandalism, and little
movement on the main issue: the cost of health care.
   NYNEX has insisted that its workers assume as much as $1,500 a
year in health costs.
</TEXT>
