<FIRST>r a AM-People-Harmon     09-28 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Harmon,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mark Harmon Welcomes Challenge of Williams Play</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mark Harmon says an actor's goal should be to
reach a level where you can ``work with the great people and say
the great words.''
   He got the chance to do that, he said, working opposite
Elizabeth Taylor in a television version of Tennessee Williams'
``Sweet Bird of Youth,'' directed by Nicolas Roeg.
   Harmon says he made no secret of his admiration for Miss Taylor
during filming of the two-hour movie, which will be broadcast
Sunday on NBC.
   ``I'm a tremendous fan of hers, and I told her that right from
the beginning,'' he said. ``I think she was having fun, too. I
think she's always wanted to play Alexandra Del Lago.''
   Del Lago is a fading movie queen who hooks up with Harmon's
Chance Wayne, a gigolo run out of his hometown after a sex scandal
involving a politician's daughter. A 1962 film version of the play
starred Paul Newman and Geraldine Page.
   Harmon, 38, says he thinks the play has as much power and
relevance now as it did 30 years ago.
   ``It's a story about time, and that's universal, and it's a
story about two people who need each other but have to destroy each
other in order to survive. That kind of relationship transcends
generations.''
   Harmon deliberately seeks parts that play against his clean-cut
good looks to avoid being typecast exclusively in lighter roles.
   ``People in this business love to find a niche for you. But I
need the challenges and I need to do different things.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
