<FIRST>r a AM-SoldiersKilled     09-28 0126</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soldiers Killed,0129</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Soldiers Killed During Exercises at Mortar Range</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Artillery Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT STEWART, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army investigators from Fort Rucker,
Ala., were dispatched Thursday to Fort Stewart, where two soldiers
were killed during live fire exercises.
   The U.S. Army said in a statement that the soldiers were killed
about 8:45 a.m. Wednesday while firing 4.2-inch mortars at the
base's mortar range.
   The three-person investigative team left about 12:15 p.m., said
Lt. Colonel Herbert Blanks, spokesman for the Army Safety Center at
Fort Rucker.
   Identities of the victims were not released pending notification
of relatives.
   A 4.2-inch mortar is a short-barreled cannon which can be fired
from a position on the ground or from a vehicle like an open-back
armored personnel carrier.
</TEXT>
