<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 2025EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-France-Concorde     09-28 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Concorde,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Piece Falls Off New York-Paris Concorde</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Air France supersonic Concorde jetliner on a
flight from New York to Paris lost a piece of the door covering the
landing gear as it was approaching Charles de Gaulle airport in
Paris, the company said Thursday.
   Air France said the piece was not a part of the landing gear
itself, but a part of the outer layer of the left landing gear door
and did not affect landing.
   The incident occurred Wednesday as the plane was flying at 250
mph about 3,600 feet over the French countryside.
   The piece of metal, about 40 inches by 30 inches and weighing 11
to 13 pounds, fell into an empty lot in Sannois, northwest of Paris.
   A man living in a trailer nearby heard the piece of metal fall
to the ground. He turned it over to police.
   Air France said the accident was caused by the breaking of a
connecting rod in the door. The company said all such rods were
being checked by technicians.
   Earlier this year, a Concorde, which flies at more than twice
the speed of sound, aborted its flight to New York and returned to
Paris after cracks appeared in a porthole. The crack was in the
outermost of four panes of glass in the porthole.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
