<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 2026EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-CaribbeanVilla 340   09-28 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Caribbean Villa, 340</SECOND>
<HEAD>`For Rent' Sign Went Up Before Hugo</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Troubled Paradise Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``House for Rent. Beautiful villa ... secluded
pool surrounded by a large patio bordered by tropical flowers and
bushes,'' said an ad in a real estate booklet that arrived in many
Washington area homes this week.
   The rent was $2,100 a week from January to April, $1,080 a week
from August to December.
   The house was in St. Croix, U.S. Virgin Islands, devastated by
Hurricane Hugo on Sept. 17.
   ``At this point, we are basically telling people who call for
the ad that to our knowledge, we have had damage, we don't know the
extent of it, so we are not taking renters at this point,'' Jorgen
Muurman of suburban Arlington, Va., who placed the ad, said
Thursday.
   ``The ad, of course, went into that magazine before the
hurricane struck.''
   Muurman's wife, Laura Del Corona-Borgia, said the house, which
they have owned for about 10 years, was one of two they had in St.
Croix. She said they had recently retired and planned to move to
the second St. Croix house.
   However, she said it, too, was believed to be severely damaged.
   Muurman, a Dane, worked for the World Bank here. Ms. Del
Corona-Borgia, an Italian, worked for the International Monetary
Fund.
   ``At this point, we only have reports from friends who have come
off the island,'' Muurman said. ``None of them have been close to
our houses, but we expect that it won't be in any condition to be
rented out for quite a while.''
   The villa, according to the ad, ``has a magnificent view since
it is situated on a hilltop overlooking the Caribbean Sea, and it
is within walking distance of one of the best and most private
beaches on St. Croix. 5 minutes from Christiansted, tennis and golf
nearby.''
   The house was vacant when the storm struck.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
