<FIRST>r a AM-Mason     09-28 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mason,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mason: I'm a Comedian, I'm Not a Politician, I'm Sorry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Jackie Mason, whose schtick has stung
mayoral hopeful Rudolph Giuliani, apologized Thursday for saying
Democratic candidate David Dinkins looks like ``a black model
without a job.''
   ``I've learned a lesson from the last few days. What's funny on
stage can be insensitive when it's said off the stage and in the
world of politics,'' Mason said in a one-paragraph statement. ``And
for my insensitivity, I apologize.''
   Mason's participation in the Giuliani campaign was severed
Wednesday after the Village Voice reported his remarks, which
included a comment that Jews would vote for Dinkins out of guilt.
   ``I'd like to say something from the bottom of my heart,''
Mason's statement began. ``I'm a comedian, not a politician. ...
The jokes come from affection.''
   Dinkins, asked again Thursday about Mason's comments, expressed
the hope they would not become an issue as the campaign continues.
   ``He has withdrawn from the campaign and, hopefully, that is the
end of that,'' Dinkins said.
</TEXT>
