<FIRST>r i AM-Colombia     09-28 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Source: Government Returns Some Property Seized in Drug War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has returned 100 planes
seized during its crackdown on the cocaine cartels because it had
no proof they were used in drug trafficking, a government source
said Thursday.
   Security was tightened for a second day in the capital as
authorities tried to stop a wave of bombings that officials blame
on the drug lords.
   A high-ranking government official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said in a telephone interview that of the 375 aircraft
seized in the past six weeks, 180 were found to have been used in
drug trafficking and were turned over to the Colombian air force.
   Colombia's National Drug Council has used guidelines of the U.S.
Drug Enforcement Administration to order the seizure of property
believed to have been used in trafficking.
   Since President Virgilio Barco declared war on the nation's drug
dealers Aug. 19, security forces also have seized 525 vehicles and
74 boats.
   The government source said that 100 of the aircraft were
returned to the owners because there was no proof they were used to
haul drugs. The Drug Council has not identified the owners.
   The council consists of five Cabinet ministers, the attorney
general and the chief of the national police. The ministers did not
return telephone calls Thursday and could not be reached for
comment.
   Barco said Tuesday that as part of the crackdown, security
forces also had seized 1,056 mansions, ranches and other property.
   The owners cannot reclaim the property unless they prove in
court that they bought it with legally earned money.
   Traffic was tied up in many parts of Bogota for a second day
Thursday as police at checkpoints searched cars for dynamite and
guns.
   There were two explosions in the city of 6 million people
Wednesday night, one at a bank and another at a gasoline station.
   The bomb at the service station killed two people, who appeared
to be terrorists in a car that was loaded with dynamite and blew
up, said police Gen. Octavio Vargas. Five people were injured.
   In the past six weeks 114 bombs have exploded in Colombia's
biggest cities, killing 10 people and wounding 140.
   No one has claimed responsibility for the blasts, but government
security forces say all were caused by drug traffickers.
  
</TEXT>
