<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Invasion     09-28 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Invasion,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungary's Parliament Condemns 1968 Czech Invasion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament on Thursday condemned
Hungary's participation in the 1968 Warsaw Pact invasion of
Czechoslovakia and called it illegal.
   Hungary joined Poland as the only Soviet bloc governments to
condemn the invasion in which all pact countries _ except Romania _
took part. Hungary's Communist Party previously had condemned the
Aug. 20-21, 1968, invasion.
   Janos Seboek, a member of Parliament who presented the motion,
said that did not represent the Hungarian people to the extent that
Parliament does.
   ``On the basis of the principle of sovereignty and equality of
nations and heeding the lessons of recent Hungarian history,
Parliament condemns the decision which illegally sent Hungarian
troops into Czechoslovakia and intervened in the affairs of a
neighboring country,'' the government statement said.
   Parliament adopted the position with 250 votes in favor and 11
against.
   Earlier in the day, Defense Minister Ferenc Karpati called the
Brezhnev Doctrine ``outdated for good.''
   The doctrine, which allows Moscow to intervene militarily if the
Kremlin considers communism ``in danger'' in other Warsaw Pact
countries, was invoked by the late Soviet leader Leonid Brezhnev to
justify the crushing of the ``Prague Spring'' reforms of Alexander
Dubcek.
   Hungarian leaders, eager to assure their citizens there is no
threat from Moscow to the broad political reforms under way in
Hungary, have said they have assurances from the Kremlin that the
doctrine was no longer in force.
   Seboek said that because the doctrine was an ideology and not a
law, it could be invoked against Hungary at any time.
   It could be used in two ways, he said: ``Either directly, which
is a genuine danger as long as there are Stalinist regimes in the
neighboring countries, or indirectly when the same powers help
domestic conservatives regain power.''
   Hungary's bilateral agreements with allied countries should be
reviewed, Seboek said, noting that Parliament members do not know
``if our fraternal assistance agreements contain military clauses.''
</TEXT>
