<FIRST>u i AM-Glemp     09-28 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Glemp,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Munich Paper Quotes Cardinal as Saying Jews Don't Understand Poles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUNICH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal Jozef Glemp of Poland was
quoted in an interview published Thursday as saying Jews,
especially those in the United States, don't understand the Polish
people.
   The respected Sueddeutsche Zeitung of Munich also quoted the
controversial Polish primate as saying he wants to hold a symposium
to clear up misunderstandings between Jews and Poles.
   Poland's Roman Catholic leaders and Jewish organizations have
been at odds in recent weeks over a Carmelite convent outside the
walls of the former Auschwitz Nazi concentration camp in Poland.
   Jewish and Catholic representatives, including Polish Cardinal
Franciszek Macharski, agreed in Geneva in February 1987 to move the
17 Carmelite nuns from the convent. The convent comes under
Macharski's Krakow diocese.
   Jewish groups claim the convent and a 23-foot cross at the
Auschwitz-Birkenau location are offensive and insensitive. An
estimated 2.5 million Jews were killed at Auschwitz during the Nazi
Holocaust.
   On July 14, an American rabbi and six other Jews staged a
protest at the site because the convent had not been closed, as
agreed. The protesters tried to scramble over a convent wall and
were forcibly ejected by Polish laborers.
   Cardinal Macharski announced Aug. 10 that the agreement to move
the nuns would be abrogated due to the ``aggressive'' atmosphere of
the controversy.
   In a sermon on Aug. 26, Glemp said it was only luck ``that none
of the nuns were murdered,'' further angering Jewish groups.
   He insisted the agreement to move the convent should be
renegotiated, and that the Polish church lacked funds to build a
new facility for the nuns.
   But on Sept. 19, the Vatican announced the convent should be
moved and said it would help finance the relocation.
   Elan Steinberg, executive director of the New York-based World
Jewish Congress, hailed the announcement as a breakthrough.
   Glemp denied in the newspaper interview that his sermon had
anti-Jewish undertones.
   Referring to ``many press comments alleging my anti-semitism,''
Glemp said: ``I counter by saying that this anti-semitism does not
exist in me.''
   Glemp said the Jewish protests against the convent ``offended
our dignity and that of the nuns.''
   ``That is why I had to also protest loudly. This protest was
misunderstood. For me it concerned a more open and deeper
dialogue,'' the newspaper quoted Glemp as saying.
   Glemp, who suggested in his sermon that Jews stirred up
anti-Polish sentiments in the international press, said the
coverage was at times hurtful and showed ``ignorance of Polish
problems.''
   ``I think that after this storm, after these very sharp and
vehement discussions, the weaknesses on both sides are clearer,''
Glemp was quoted as saying when asked how Christian-Jewish
differences could be resolved.
   He said an inter-faith symposium should be convened to discuss
problems.
   ``We want the Jews to understand us, especially the Jews in
America, who talk a lot but do not understand the situation. We
want them to develop a correct respect for the Poles,'' the
newspaper quoted Glemp as saying.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
