<FIRST>r i AM-UN-StolenWatch     09-28 0135</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Stolen Watch,0137</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hiroshima Watch Missing, U.N. Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A partially melted pocket watch recovered
from the debris of the Aug. 6, 1945, atomic bomb blast at
Hiroshima, its hands fixed forever at the fatal time of 8:15, was
stolen from a collection of artifacts, U.N. officials said Thursday.
   U.N. spokeswoman Nadia Younes said the watch vanished from a
display case about a month ago, that an investigation failed to
find it and it is presumed stolen.
   Japan donated the watch for display with a collection of
Hiroshima artifacts.
   Undersecretary-General Therese Sevigny, wrote to Japan's Foreign
Ministry to apologize.
   The United Nations conducts tour groups past display cases of
Hiroshima remnants such as charred clothing, melted coins and fused
crockery as part of a display urging arms control and disarmament
worldwide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890928-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 2046EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Nicaragua     09-28 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Nicaragua,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Balks at Bush Plan To Aid Nicaraguan Candidate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's $9 million plan to help the
Nicaraguan political opposition in next year's election ran into
trouble Thursday at a Senate hearing when some lawmakers said it
was too vague and Sen. Jesse Helms accused the administration of
trying to ``railroad'' it through Congress.
   But Bernard Aronson, assistant secretary of state for
inter-American affairs, urged a Senate Foreign Relations panel to
approve the transfer of money to help opposition candidate Violeta
Chamorro, saying ``this is fundamentally not a fair fight.''
   In a related development, Senate Intelligence Committee Chairman
David Boren, D-Okla., said he had been assured by Bush
administration officials that there would be no attempt to use the
CIA or other means to influence the elections clandestinely.
   ``I've been given absolute assurance,'' Boren said. ``There's
not a glimmer, not a crack, not a loophole of any kind.''
   The overt aid plan calls for giving an additional $5 million to
the National Endowment for Democracy, a quasi-governmental
foundation, to use for election monitoring, voter registration and
other activities deemed non-partisan.
   Another $4 million could go outside NED channels to monitoring
groups, registration and get-out-the-vote activities.
   Aronson asked senators to see that the aid is approved quickly,
since voters may register for the Feb. 25 voting only during
October.
   But Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., said it was unlikely money
could be approved before next week at the earliest, and he
challenged Aronson on how the money would be spent.
   When Aronson began to compare the ``modest'' U.S. proposal with
the billions received by Nicaragua from the Soviets, Dodd halted
him and called it a ``silly point.''
   Aronson protested that the United States is seeking to build
from scratch an electoral mechanism in a country which never has
had free elections, ``educate people about the process and give
them some sense that they can vote safely.''
   ``The question is whether it's well thought out,'' Dodd said.
``There is no question we ought to be involved. The question is
whether we're doing it intelligently.''
   Sen. Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan., echoed those concerns. ``There is
a lot of money going out. In our fervent desire to see a strong
election and hopefully the success of Mrs. Chamorro, we have to be
cautious about how that money is being spent,'' she said.
   NED Director Carl Gershman conceded that ``this dwarfs what the
endowment itself has been able to spend in any other situation,''
including larger countries like the Philippines, Panama and Chile.
   The hearing was cut short because of a Republican procedural
objection, and Helms, R-N.C., entered the room only long enough to
complain that the session had been scheduled without any advance
notice to Senate Republicans.
   ``The minority was not consulted ... and I resent it,'' he said.
   When chairman Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., said the session had been
arranged with the ``Republican administration,'' Helms replied:
``You thought you were going to snooker us.''
   ``I fundamentally object to this thing being railroaded as it
is,'' Helms said outside the hearing. ``If they want to play games
like that I know how to play them as well.''
   Helms' stated objections to the package include a philosophical
opposition to U.S. involvement in overseas elections, disapproval
of the opposition coalition which includes communists and
socialists, and the necessity of paying some of the money in the
form of a tax to the Sandinista-controlled Supreme Electoral
Council.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
