<FIRST>r w AM-FlemmingHonored     09-28 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flemming Honored,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former HEW Secretary Flemming Receives Pepper Award.</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release at 10 p.m. EDT. Time set by source.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Health, Education and Welfare Secretary
Arthur S. Flemming was honored Thursday as the first recipient of
the Pepper Distinguished Service Award, established in memory of
the late Rep. Claude Pepper.
   Flemming, 84, long has been an advocate for Social Security,
Medicare, civil rights and other causes. He served as HEW secretary
from 1958-61, U.S. Commissioner on Aging from 1973-78 and as
chairman of the U.S. Commission on Civil Rights from 1974-82. He
also chaired the first White House Conference on Aging in 1971.
   Flemming for seven years has headed the Save Our Security
Coalition, uniting more than 100 organizations seeking to protect
Social Security. He also is chairman of the National Health Care
Campaign, seeking comprehensive health-care and long-term care
protection for all Americans.
   The award was bestowed by the Mildred and Claude Pepper
Foundation, a non-profit organization established by Pepper in 1986
to support efforts to make lives longer, healthier and happier for
all Americans. Pepper, a Florida Democrat who was known as the
singular champion of senior citizens, died in May at age 88.
</TEXT>
