<FIRST>r w AM-Pentagon-Soviet     09-28 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon-Soviet,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Soviet Defense Minister To Get Tour</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Dimitri Yazov will get a taste of
America's old and new military next week when he takes the
first-ever tour of the United States by a defense minister from the
Soviet Union, officials said Thursday.
   Pentagon spokesman Pete Williams said Yazov will be treated to a
tour of the Civil War battlefield at Gettysburg, Pa., as well as a
number of military installations during his Oct. 1-6 tour.
   Yazov, who arrives on Sunday, will wrap up his week in New York
on Friday, the spokesman said.
   The visit marks another in the series of high-level U.S.-Soviet
military exchanges that have occurred amid the warming of
superpower relations.
   Yazov and former Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci met last year
in Switzerland in sessions that led to an exchange of visits
between the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Adm. William
Crowe Jr. and his counterpart, Gen. Sergei Akromeyev, to each
other's homelands.
   The defense minister's visit to the United States reciprocates a
visit Carlucci made to the Soviet Union in August 1988.
   Yazov is to be greeted at the Pentagon on Monday with a full
honors ceremony by Defense Secretary Dick Cheney.
   The two men will conduct a round of bilateral meetings and Yazov
will remain at the Pentagon for lunch, Williams said.
   Williams cautioned that the general's schedule ``hasn't really
jelled yet,'' but said plans included a wreath-laying later in the
day at the Tomb of the Unknowns at Arlington National Cemetery.
   The Soviet general also intends to visit the Naval Air Station
near San Diego and the Marine Corps training base at nearby Camp
Pendleton.
   Also on his agenda are Luke Air Force Base near Phoenix, Ariz.,
and Fort Bragg, N.C., the spokesman said.
   Williams said the Soviet general will be accompanied by his
wife, Emma, and several other high-level Soviet officials.
</TEXT>
