<FIRST>r i AM-China 1stLd-Writethru a0606 09-28 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0606,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Sentenced to Life Imprisonment for Rioting During Protests</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with official comment; China denying
reporter's story of arrest, abuse. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two people were sentenced to life in prison and
three others to jail terms of five years to 12 years for
``hooliganism'' during rioting in the Chinese city of Xian this
spring, an official report said.
   Also Thursday, China said a French reporter's story of the
arrest and abuse of a student, which he told at a news conference
by China's top leaders, was an ``appalling lie'' and violated
journalistic ethics.
   The life sentences were given to Liu Gang and Sun Guanghu for
allegedly leading others to attack stores and the railroad station
during April riots, said the report in Wednesday's edition of the
Legal Daily.
   Three other people were given jail terms of five years to 12
years. The newspaper did not say when the sentencing took place or
give any details about the defendants.
   Liu Gang also is the name of a student on China's list of
most-wanted leaders of the spring pro-democracy movement. The Liu
Gang mentioned in the Legal Daily report is not believed to be the
same person.
   The provincial foreign affairs office, contacted by telephone,
said it did not know whether the court sentenced the student leader
or another man with the same name. The court refused comment.
   The Xian violence erupted shortly after a memorial ceremony for
ousted Communist Party chief Hu Yaobang, whose April 15 death
triggered massive student demonstrations.
   The newspaper said the five who were sentenced hurled stones and
bricks at buses and other vehicles during rioting.
   Sun, blowing on a whistle, led a group that attacked the train
station, while Liu incited others to destroy the Liberation Road
department store and 13 other private shops, the report said.
   In Beijing, thousands of people, including many students, were
arrested after troops crushed the seven-week democracy movement on
June 3-4. Chinese sources say some have been beaten in prison.
International rights groups such as Amnesty International have
appealed to China to release them as prisoners of conscience, and
say some may have been tortured and executed secretly.
   The official People's Daily party newspaper Thursday quoted
Beijing and Sichuan authorities as denying the story of French
reporter Eric Meyer of Les Dernieres Nouvelles d'Alsace.
   At a Tuesday news conference, Meyer said he knew of a Chinese
woman student wounded June 3 in the army attack, arrested and sent
to work in a brick factory in southwestern China's Sichuan
province, where she was raped three times by peasants.
   ``We feel strongly indignant at this French reporter, for he
dared to brazenly tell such a fabricated story before some 300
Chinese and foreign reporters in violation of the basic principle
of journalism that news reporting must be factual,'' the paper
quoted Beijing's deputy police director, Wang Dingfeng, as saying.
   It quoted Zheng Wenju, Sichuan justice department director, as
expressing ``his deep regret over the French reporter spreading
such an appalling lie.''
   Meyer said Thursday he stands by the story, but refused to say
how he learned of it.
</TEXT>
