<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-28 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Showers And Thunderstorms Over The Southeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain spread over the Southeast on Thursday, with more than 4
inches at one Florida city, and record low temperatures continued
in the Northeast.
   Thunderstorms poured rain on northeastern Florida for much of
the day, causing flooding in Jacksonville, the National Weather
Service said.
   By midafternoon, Jacksonville had gotten 4.28 inches of rain
since midnight, including 3.56 inches in the six hours up to 2 p.m.
EDT. That made a total of 5.48 inches at Jacksonville since noon
Wednesday.
   Showers and thunderstorms also extended over the Tennessee
Valley, from Florida and Georgia across the lower Mississippi
Valley, and scattered along the Texas Gulf Coast.
   During the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT, 1.48 inches of rain fell
at Marietta, Ga., and Meridian, Miss., got 1.37 inches.
   Elsewhere, showers reached from eastern South Dakota into
northwestern Iowa and southwestern Minnesota. And light showers
extended over southwestern California.
   Afternoon temperatures were only in the upper 50s and 60s across
New England. But more seasonable temperatures were expected during
the night and Friday morning, when readings were expected to be 10
to 15 degrees warmer than Thursday morning.
   Record lows Thursday included 40 in Baltimore; 30 in Binghamton,
N.Y.; and 32 in Toledo, Ohio. Mansfield, Ohio, tied its record of
36 and Pittsburgh tied its record of 34.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 47
degrees in Caribou, Maine, to 99 in Palm Springs, Calif., and Yuma,
Ariz. Thursday's low for the Lower 48 states was 24 in Houlton,
Maine.
</TEXT>
