<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 1725EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Yugoslavia     09-28 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Serbians Denounce Slovenian Constitutional Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SLOBODAN LEKIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of angry Serbs
rallied on Thursday to denounce the Slovenian republic's adoption
of major changes in its regional constitution, including the right
to secede.
   The Yugoslav parliament asked the Supreme Court Thursday to rule
urgently on whether the amendments were allowed under the federal
constitution.
   The changes, adopted by the Slovenian parliament on Wednesday,
give that small northern state the right to secede from the
six-republic federation and to control use of the Yugoslav military
in Slovenia in peacetime.
   In the southern republic of Serbia, at least 10,000 people
rallied in Novi Sad, 50 miles north of Belgrade, to hear speakers
describe Slovenia's action as ``a lunatic act of hatred'' and
``high treason.''
   ``The integrity of this country will be defended by armed force
if necessary,'' one speaker told a cheering crowd.
   The gathering was broadcast live by state television.
   An additional 15,000 Serbs protested in the town of Leskovac,
and ``hundreds'' of other rallies were held elsewhere throughout
Serbia, the official Tanjug news agency said.
   The meetings were organized by supporters of the Serbian
communist leadership, which advocates more central control in the
country.
   The amendments in Slovenia pave the way for introduction of a
Western-style multiparty democracy in the state, where independent
opposition parties have already been formed. Slovenia borders on
Italy and Austria.
   The federal constitution's preamble also stipulates the right to
self-determination and the right of individual republics to secede,
without specifying how this could be achieved.
   Slovenian authorities have stressed they do not intend to secede
and that the changes only provide ``an added sense of security''
for the 2 million Slovenes, who make up about 8 percent of
Yugoslavia's population.
   Joze Smole, head of the communist-led Socialist Alliance of
Slovenia, told the Belgrade daily Borba, ``Not a single Slovene
wishes the republic to secede from Yugoslavia.''
   Up to 50,000 people demonstrated on Wednesday in the southern
republic of Montenegro, demanding the Slovenian leadership be
``toppled.''
   The protests appeared similar to those preceding imposition of a
state of emergency last February in Serbia's Kosovo province, where
ethnic Albanians make up 85 percent of the population.
   That measure was immediately followed by a constitutional change
limiting Kosovo's autonomy and giving Serbia a greater say in its
affairs. Subsequent ethnic Albanian riots left 24 people dead.
   The Slovenian Delo daily said Thursday that to opponents, ``We
can only say: we are Yugoslavs but we are Slovenes first ... and
the constitutional changes reflect our national interests.''
   Yugoslavia has a decentralized system of government and
collective federal presidency, fashioned in 1974 to keep one
republic from gaining sway over the others, but resulting in an
ineffective government by compromise.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
