<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 1732EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-DrugShootout     09-28 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Shootout,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents Reach Tentative Truce After Shootout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police mediated a truce between armed
residents of a drug-ridden neighborhood and alleged crack cocaine
dealers after simmering tensions erupted into a cross-street
gunbattle, officers said Thursday.
   The truce, in which neighbors agreed to put firearms away and
drug dealers agreed to keep dealing off the street, has brought a
measure of calm to the nervous Hilltop neighborhood.
   Police said the two sides exchanged 300 shots Saturday during an
anti-drug block party at the home of Army Ranger Staff Sgt. Bill
Foulk, who summoned 11 off-duty Rangers as reinforcements.
   No one was injured, however, until the next day when fistfights
broke out and some neighbors suffered scrapes and bruises from
thrown bricks. Only two arrests were made Saturday, both of alleged
gang members, although the Rangers' weapons were confiscated.
   Patrol Officer Lee Giles, who helped arrange the meeting
Wednesday that led to the truce, said the alleged drug dealers
``agreed that selling of drugs on the street or in the area was
unacceptable'' and would stop.
   For their part, Foulk and his neighbors agreed not to use
weapons.
   ``I don't want to say we're friends yet, but it's a start,''
Foulk said.
   ``We won't be in the open selling drugs,'' said Robert Brown,
who negotiated with Foulk and his neighbors on behalf of the youths
and alleged drug dealers on the block.
   Telephone numbers were exchanged and both parties said they
would try to talk out any disagreements, Giles said.
   ``All the people involved felt it was better to talk than
shoot,'' said police Sgt. Steve Smith, another mediator.
   Foulks and neighbor John Harper said their key concession was to
realize that neighbors cannot stop drug dealing entirely.
   ``All we can hope to do is get the drug dealing off the street _
the violence associated with it _ so we can start to feel safe,''
Foulk said.
   Police participation does not mean they are sanctioning drug
sales on or off the street, Giles said.
   ``We're not so naive as to say we're going to stop all drug
sales,'' he said. ``Let's be real. But at least we're giving them
the message we will not condone that.''
   ``We're still going to go after them as aggressively as we
can,'' added police spokesman Mark Mann. ``If they think we're
going to back off because they've moved inside, they're wrong.''
   Foulk, 32, and his fellow negotiators said a key to the
agreement will be Brown's ability to convince his side to abide by
the terms.
   Brown, 28, said the residents ``made it plain and clear they
were going to keep on fighting'' if the dealers did not leave the
street.
   Mayor Doug Sutherland said the terms of the agreement are
``certainly different,'' but praised the unusual pact.
   Fort Lewis officials, where the Rangers are stationed, said they
would not take action against their personnel involved and leave
the matter to local authorities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
