<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0704 09-28 0700</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0704,0717</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Outlaws Islamic Movement, Announces Gaza Closure</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 4th pvs, `The death ...' to UPDATE with
Rabin endorsement. Picks up graf 5 pvs, `Hamas emerged ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel outlawed the radical Islamic
fundamentalist movement Hamas on Thursday, and announced it will
bar the 700,000 Palestinians in the Gaza Strip from entering Israel
during the Jewish New Year holiday.
   Troops shot and killed a Palestinian in the West Bank town of
Nablus during a stone-throwing confrontation and wounded 17 others
in clashes in the Gaza Strip, Arab reports said.
   The army said it was checking the reports.
   The death of Bilal Einab, 20, brought to 575 the number of Arabs
killed by Israeli troops or civilians since the start of the
Palestinian uprising in December 1987. An additional 121
Palestinians have been killed by fellow Arabs, most on suspicion of
collaborating with Israel. Forty Israelis have died.
   Also Thursday, Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin picked up a key
endorsement amid growing signs he may be able to unseat Finance
Minister Shimon Peres as leader of the left-leaning Labor Party.
   Rabin, 67, who was prime minister from 1974-77, won backing from
Labor Party doves Ely Ben-Menachem and Ezer Weizman, the science
minister.
   The leadership issue is unlikely to come to a head unless
Labor's coalition with the right-wing Likud bloc breaks apart _
likely only with serious movement toward Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations.
   Hamas emerged soon after the start of the revolt, spreading its
influence from Gaza to parts of the West Bank. The movement
advocates an Islamic state including the occupied lands and Israel.
   ``This movement has a religious character, is very radical and
is using very cruel means. It pledged violent struggle not only
against Israel but also against Judaism and Zionism,'' said Shmuel
Goren, Israel's coordinator for the occupied territories.
   The army announced a three-day closure of the Gaza Strip from
Friday through Monday during Rosh Hashana, the New Year holiday.
Security throughout the country will be reinforced over the weekend.
   Also Thursday, Palestinian activist Faisal Husseini warned the
uprising will intensify if peace efforts fail, but he rejected the
idea of armed struggle.
   Husseini and three other prominent Palestinians, speaking on a
panel, also said the 10-point Egyptian peace plan, aimed at ending
the impasse over Israel's peace initiative, does not go far enough
in pressing for Palestinian independence.
   ``We are ready to deal with any proposal, we are ready to start
any negotiations if we will be addressed as a people, not as a
minority or as refugees or as inhabitants of a certain place,'' he
said.
   Husseini, a pro-PLO activist, told the forum sponsored by the
Foreign Press Association that if peace efforts fail, ``We will
escalate our struggle. We will cover more areas, cover more
people.''
   But ``we will not be provoked. The Israelis will not push us to
use weapons,'' Husseini said.
   He and the other activists said the Palestinians were ready to
open peace talks with Israel but criticized the Israeli
government's peace initiative and the plan put forward by Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak.
   The Israeli government has called for elections in the occupied
territories to select Palestinians to open talks with Israel on an
interim period of self-rule.
   Mubarak, in an effort to overcome Palestine Liberation
Organization objections to the Israeli plan, has urged Israel to
hold preliminary talks with a delegation including Palestinians
from outside the territories, and to consider accepting the
U.S.-backed formula of trading land for peace. There is opposition
in Israel to both moves.
   The Palestinian human rights group Al-Haq, meanwhile, charged in
a statement that tax raids in the Wst Bank town of Beit Sahour by
army troops were ``blatantly illegal'' and conducted with
``extraordinary ... savagery and violence.''
   Troops have been entering homes in Beit Sahour, a town of about
5,000 people near Bethlehem, and confiscating goods since Sept. 20
in lieu of unpaid taxes.
   A PLO-ordered tax boycott has been widely observed in Beit
Sahour, a hotbed of activism against Israeli occupation. Residents
closed shops and offices Thursday at the start of a three-day
strike to protest the raids.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
