<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-Spending     09-28 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Spending,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Passes Stopgap Spending Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo Help</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress passed and sent to the White House on
Thursday a stopgap spending bill to keep government agencies in
business while lawmakers continue work on appropriations bills for
the new budget year.
   The measure, which has the support of the White House as well as
both the House and Senate, continues funding for these agencies
through Oct. 25.
   The Senate passed the measure on a 100-0 vote after the House
had approved it 274-152 earlier in the week. Because the Senate
attached an amendment providing $1.1 billion in disaster relief for
areas stricken by Hurricane Hugo, the measure had to go back to the
House for final approval. Lawmakers there passed the bill by voice
vote.
   The temporary spending measure had to be passed because Congress
has been immersed in an array of disputes that have kept lawmakers
from finishing work on the 13 annual appropriations bills for
fiscal 1990, which begins Sunday.
   The Senate also passed, on a 92-8 vote, a $67.2 million measure
financing federal housing, veterans, space and environmental
programs in the new budget year. The measure also provides $1.85
billion for NASA's space station project.
   One key element of the bill was an amendment boosting the price
ceiling on home mortgages the Federal Housing Administration can
insure. Adoption of the measure increased the current $101,250
limit to $124,875.
   Voting against the bill were Sens. William Armstrong, R-Colo.;
Alan Dixon, D-Ill.; Jesse Helms, R-N.C.; Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H.;
Robert Kasten, R-Wis.; William Roth, R-Del.; Steve Symms, R-Idaho,
and Malcolm Wallop, R-Wyo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
