<FIRST>u i AM-UN-PLOVisas     09-28 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-PLO Visas,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Groups Protest U.S. Visas for PLO Leaders to Visit UN</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Jewish organizations on Thursday
protested the granting of visas to three Palestine Liberation
Organization leaders to attend the U.N. General Assembly this year.
   ``The three PLO representatives who have received visas are
among the most radical members of the PLO leadership,'' said a
statement from the Conference of Presidents of Major American
Jewish Organizations.
   ``Their record of terrorist activity and rejectionist statements
makes clear that they come not in the cause of peace, but of
propaganda,'' the statement said.
   The visas, granted by the State Department, were announced
Wednesday and diplomats said they expected PLO Chairman Yasser
Arafat also to apply for a visa. The approval of visas for Arafat's
lieutenants, they said, increases the likelihood that Arafat will
be allowed to visit.
   After he was denied a visa last year, the 159-nation General
Assembly in protest moved to Geneva for a special session to hear
Arafat. From that podium he announced the renunciation of terrorism
and recognition of Israel's right to exist _ demands made by the
United States.
   On Thursday, however, the Jewish organizations said his
representatives _ Farouk Kaddoumi, Yasser Abed Rabbu and Sulim
Najib _ have been involved in terrorist acts and called for the
destruction of Israel.
   Seymour D. Reich, chairman of the conference, said: ``These are
not the words or deeds of peacemakers, but rather of violent men.
... That they should have been chosen to represent the PLO confirms
once more that the PLO remains committed to its (stated) goal'' of
purging Israel from the region.
   The conference is an umbrella group representing such
organizations as Hadassah, B'nai Brith, the American Jewish
Congress.
   The statement of protest was sent to the State Department.
</TEXT>
