<FIRST>u w AM-Capital-Gains-South 560   09-28 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Capital-Gains-South, 560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0748 to remove Bjt designation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Southern Democrats Provide Margin Of Victory In Capital Gains Fight</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Capital Gains, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southern Democrats provided the margin of
victory Thursday as the House rejected an effort by its Democratic
leaders to derail a capital gains tax cut.
   Southerners accounted for 42 of the 64 Democrats who joined with
a nearly solid bloc of Republicans in a 239-190 vote to defeat the
leadership plan to replace the capital gains tax cut with expanded
deductions for Individual Retirement Accounts financed by higher
taxes on the wealthy.
   The winning coalition was similar to the one that enacted many
of former President Reagan's economic programs. But Southerners who
supported President Bush in the capital gains fight were quick to
reject the boll weevil label that was applied to Southern Democrats
who backed Reagan eight years ago.
   ``I'm not even a member of the boll weevils,'' said Rep. Ed
Jenkins, D-Ga., one of the authors of the capital gains tax cut in
the House Ways and Means Committee. ``You'd have to call me a
liberal boll weevil.''
   Jenkins said the capital gains reduction had broad support among
both conservative and moderate Democrats, and the leadership
alternative failed because it didn't address that issue.
   ``There are a large number of Democrats who simply are not going
to vote for a tax increase,'' he said, ``and the alternative had
nothing to do with capital gains. That was the real weakness of
their proposal.''
   Rep. Ronnie Flippo, D-Ala., another sponsor of the capital gains
proposal, said moderate and conservative Democrats supported it as
``a pro-growth, pro-jobs issue'' even though it put them at odds
with party leaders and aligned them with Bush, who had promised
such a tax cut during his campaign.
   ``We did it because we thought it was the right policy and
because we thought the leadership was going in the wrong
direction,'' Flippo said. ``We're going to continue to do
everything we can to see that the Democratic Party at least
considers a more conservative viewpoint.''
   Rep. Ben Jones, D-Ga., said the leadership made a mistake in
trying to portray the capital gains issue as a tax break for the
wealthy.
   ``This was a main street issue,'' he said. ``The people I've
been hearing from on this are not the country club people, they're
the barber shop people. ... The leadership misjudged it.''
   Voting for the capital gains reduction were eight of the nine
Democrats from Georgia, four of five from Alabama, three of four
from Louisiana, three of four from Mississippi, all four from
Kentucky, three of four from South Carolina, both from Arkansas,
and half of the 18 from Texas.
   Southern support for the leadership position was concentrated in
North Carolina and Florida, where seven of eight Democrats in each
state opposed the tax cut; in Virginia, where three of five opposed
it; and in Tennessee, where four of six opposed it.
   Jones said many of the Southern Democrats who voted for the
capital gains reduction represent districts dominated by ``small
farmers, timber interests and people with a little bit of real
estate.''
   ``These are the very people we've been losing'' in presidential
elections, he said. ``We're an inclusive party, why not include
some successful people?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
