<FIRST>u w AM-HugoHelp 2ndLd-Writethru a0745 09-28 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo Help, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0745,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress OKs Record Relief Aid; Bush Will Sign Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Eds: New material, editing thruout with White House saying Bush
will sign legislation.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress on Thursday approved $1.1 billion in
emergency aid for the victims of Hurricane Hugo, Capitol Hill's
largest disaster-relief package ever. The White House said
President Bush will sign the legislation, perhaps when he visits
South Carolina on Friday.
   ``There never was this much money,'' said Bill McAda, a
spokesman for the Federal Emergency Management Agency. ``But this
also may well be the most damaging one (hurricane) in history.''
   The aid was attached to a stopgap spending resolution intended
to keep government agencies operating when the new fiscal year
begins Sunday. The spending measure passed the Senate on a 100 to 0
and cleared the House by voice vote.
   ``I have never seen so much damage in my life,'' Sen. Strom
Thurmond, R-S.C., told his colleagues before the vote. ``It looked
there had been a war there. ... We need all the help we can get.''
   At the White House, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said
Bush would fly to South Carolina Friday to get a first-hand look at
the devastation left in the wake of Hugo's passing a week ago and
may sign the legislation while he is there.
   Fitzwater said the president wanted ``to make sure that all that
can be done is being done'' and to assure the people of South
Carolina that Gov. Carroll Campbell will provide ``whatever help we
can.''
   Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., had said Wednesday that damage in
his state was closer to $3 billion to $4 billion but that getting
that amount would be impossible without forcing across-the-board
federal budget cuts.
   McAda said the aid cannot go for home or business repairs to
people who have insurance. But he did say that the assistance
provides for loans of up to $10,000 for people ``who have needs and
cannot qualify for (private) loans for some reason or other.''
   Fitzwater defended the emergency relief agency against
accusations by Hollings that help was being help up in ``red tape.''
   The presidential spokesman said that ``Hollings' job is to keep
the pressure on'' and said government agents were fighting
``remarkable odds'' in the relief effort.
   ``We think things are going pretty well,'' he said. Asked if
Bush might help cut red tape that is hindering the cleanup,
Fitzwater said, ``If there is any _ yes. We'll take a look at
that.''
   In South Carolina, Campbell said people planning Bush's trip
Friday were trying to arrange for the president to see devastated
areas on the coast as well as inland. Possible stops include Myrtle
Beach, Charleston and Sumter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890928-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 2056EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-Democrats     09-28 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Democrats,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>DNC Chair `Disappointed' in Number of Defectors on Capital Gains
Issue</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Capital Gains, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Party chairman Ronald H. Brown,
insisting his party still must get tough with the president, said
Thursday he was ``disappointed'' with the number of House Democrats
who sided with President Bush on his proposal to cut capital gains
taxes.
   But Brown, who had called the Bush proposal ``a tax giveaway to
the ultra rich,'' said the House defectors from their party
leadership ``are certainly good Democrats, they are certainly
Democrats we are proud to have as members of our party.''
   Forty six Democrats sided with the president on the capital
gains vote, which occurred while the Democratic National Committee
was meeting across town and hearing Brown excoriate Bush for a lack
of leadership and a continuation of ``the ethic of greed.''
   After the House vote, Brown said, ``I think it's very important
that we draw the line, that we make the distinctions, that we make
choices.''
   In his speech to the DNC, Brown called on Bush to begin
``matching his actions to his charming words.''
   Brown attacked the Bush anti-drug program as ``big words
followed by limited action. ... They declared war and decided
somebody else is going to have to find the bullets.''
   Some of his harshest rhetoric was directed at the plan to cut
tax rates on capital gains, which he called a ``massive, needless
tax break to the wealthiest 1 percent _ a giveaway that will cost
working Americans billions.''
   But the chairman sidestepped any confrontation with the
Democrats who supported Bush.
   He called capital gains ``a tough vote'' and said, ``Many of the
members who didn't vote with the (Democratic) leadership position
thought they were doing what was in the best interests of their
constituents.''
   ``I am not here to criticize Democrats,'' he said.
   During their meeting, the Democrats undid key elements of the
agreement reached between Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson at the
party's 1988 convention.
   The DNC voted to restore its members to their status as
unpledged delegates to nominating conventions. The body also voted
to require that any future convention deals be ratified by the DNC.
   Brown, who was Jackson's chief negotiator at the 1988
convention, supported the changes and said he also would back a
requirement that presidential candidates receive a minimum of 15
percent of the vote in primaries and caucuses to qualify for
receiving delegates. Part of the Jackson-Dukakis deal was a rules
change that eliminated thresholds.
   The DNC also elected former Louisiana Democratic Party chair
Kathy Vick to succeed Dorothy Bush as party secretary.
   Mrs. Bush retired after 46 years in the office, which placed her
in the spotlight every four years when she called the roll of the
states on the ballot for the presidential nomination.
   The Democrats also announced that seven cities are the finalists
to host the 1992 Democratic National Convention. They are New York,
Houston, Detroit, Cleveland-Brook Park, New Orleans, Miami Beach
and Seattle.
   Party officials also had expected Atlanta, site of the 1988
convention, to bid, but city officials notified the Democrats they
would not enter the competition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
