<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 2056EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AntarcticSpill     09-28 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Antarctic Spill,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Diesel Fuel Spilled At South Pole, Agency Reports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leaky pipe spilled 44,000 gallons of diesel
fuel into the snow at an American station at the South Pole, but is
not expected to cause any environmental damage, the National
Science Foundation said Thursday.
   Jeffrey Norris, an NSF spokesman, confirmed in response to an
inquiry that the fuel leak was discovered on Aug. 21 by personnel
spending the Antarctic winter at the United States' Amundsen-Scott
South Pole station.
   He said the fuel drained down through the snow and is expected
to be trapped against an ice layer 150 feet below the surface.
Environmental impact, said the spokesman, is expected to be
``minimal.''
   ``There are no plants or wildlife in the area to be affected,''
Norris said.
   Norris said the spill represented no health hazard to personnel
at the station and noted, ``There is no immediate plan to clean it
up.''
   Antarctica now is in the midst of deep winter cold, with
temperatures continuously staying far below zero.
   Norris said the 20 scientists and technicians wintering at the
station started searching for a leak in July when measurements
showed that nine fuel tanks at the station were being drained
faster than could be explained by ordinary usage. The diesel is
used to operate generators.
   The leak was found in a pipe that carries the fuel from the
storage tanks to the power generators, Norris said.
   NSF officials made no public announcement of the spill, but
Norris said the incident was reported to the U.S. Department of
State. The Antarctic is controlled by an international treaty, and
the National Science Foundation is operates the U.S. outposts at
the bottom of the world.
   The Amundsen-Scott station sits on 9,200 feet of snow, and is
the only outpost at the South Pole.
   Norris said the incident is the second major spill of diesel
fuel at the South Pole station. In 1975, 22,000 gallons of diesel
fuel escaped into the snow when a storage tank collapsed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
