<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 2056EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SeafoodInspection     09-28 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seafood Inspection,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bills Requiring Seafood Inspection Introduced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bills requiring seafood inspection were
introduced in Congress Thursday as lawmakers search for a way to
protect humans from contaminants eaten by sea life.
   Agriculture Chairman Kika de la Garza, D-Texas, offered
legislation he calls Federal Inspection for Seafood Healthfulness,
or the FISH Act of 1989. It puts the Agriculture Department in
charge of inspecting seafood much the way it does meat and poultry.
   Rep. Dan Glickman, D-Kan., came out with the Consumer Seafood
Safety Act, which splits the responsibility between USDA and the
Food and Drug Administration.
   ``The FDA and National Academy of Standards have the most
experience in establishing scientific standards to protect against
adulteration by which food should be inspected,'' Glickman said.
``The USDA has inspection expertise that can be relied upon to
effectively carry out the guidelines established at FDA.''
   De la Garza said the ``inspection should be in USDA where
historically the food inspection process has been from the
beginning.''
   Another seafood inspection measure is being worked on by the
House Energy and Commerce Committee, and similar proposals also
have been introduced in the Senate.
   All are attempts to reassure consumers, who cut back their
consumption of seafood last year after 10 years of steady increases.
   Seafood is the only flesh food in the United States not subject
to comprehensive and rigorous mandatory safety inspection by the
federal government.
   Both consumer and industry groups favor strengthening the
regulations.
   Public Voice, a non-profit organization that has been seeking
mandatory seafood inspection since 1983, praised both Glickman and
de la Garza for their efforts, but favors Glickman's bill.
   Glickman's measure would ``establish a strong federal program,
driven by public health considerations,'' said Ellen Haas,
executive director of Public Voice.
   The National Fisheries Institute, a trade association of 1,000
seafood companies, supports de la Garza's bill. It ``contains the
authority and direction needed to provide comprehensive regulation
and inspection of seafood products and plants,'' said Lee Weddig,
the institute's executive vice president.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890928-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 2057EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FAA-FuelTanks     09-28 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FAA-Fuel Tanks,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>FAA Orders Fuel Tank Work On Big Jets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal aviation officials ordered airlines
Thursday to strengthen fuel tank covers on all large jetliners to
reduce the chance of fire when a plane crashes.
   The new regulation will cost airlines $19.7 million and require
changes in nearly 27,000 fuel tank access doors, the Federal
Aviation Administration estimated. The order, which will take
effect 30 days after official publication, gives airlines two years
to comply.
   The agency said there have been several incidents where fuel
tank access panels on airliners' wings have failed, including an
August 1985 accident involving a British Air Tours Boeing 737 in
Manchester, England, that killed 55 of the 137 people on board.
   That incident led to an order to strengthen fuel tanks in all
U.S. 737s. The new action extends the order to all large jets that
have fuel doors that might be exposed to damage from flying engine
parts, pieces of tire tread or other debris in an accident.
   The FAA said Boeing-built airliners would be most heavily
affected because they have fuel access covers on the bottom
surfaces of the wings where they are most likely to be damaged.
Most other aircraft have them on the top, the FAA said.
</TEXT>
