<FIRST>u a AM-MarcosWealth     09-28 0778</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marcos Wealth,0797</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mrs. Marcos Now Faces Racketeering Charges Alone</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Obit-Marcos, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Imelda Marcos, unwavering in her assertions of
innocence, now stands alone to face charges that she and her late
husband stole millions from their Philippine homeland.
   Mrs. Marcos, 60, is scheduled for trial in New York in March,
along with the eight others who were indicted with her and her
husband, former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos. The
72-year-old Marcos died Thursday in Hawaii.
   ``I look forward to defending myself,'' she said recently. ``If
I have to face the court alone, so be it. I will walk into the
courtroom with my head held high.''
   She said she expects to be acquitted, return to private life and
participate in Philippine politics _ from a distance if she is
never allowed to return from Hawaii, where she and Marcos lived in
exile.
   Until her legal problems are resolved, Mrs. Marcos is barred by
court order from transferring most of the couple's alleged vast
wealth. On June 9, federal prosecutors in Manhattan filed a civil
racketeering lawsuit to guarantee claims against the deposed
Philippines president after his death.
   On Oct. 31, 1988, Mrs. Marcos pleaded innocent in U.S. District
Court in Manhattan to racketeering charges. Her husband's ill
health kept him from making the trip from Hawaii to New York for
arraignment and he was severed from the case last April.
   Tobacco heiress Doris Duke put up $5 million to secure Mrs.
Marcos's bail.
   ``I was born ostentatious,'' said Mrs. Marcos, who wore a
full-length chiffon aquamarine gown to her arraignment. ``They will
list my name in the dictionary someday. They will use `Imeldific'
to mean ostentatious extravagance.''
   It wasn't until after the Marcoses' February 1986 exile that the
world glimpsed the full meaning of `Imeldific' _ symbolized by the
former first lady's 3,000 pairs of shoes.
   The Marcoses' Philippines palace, opened to the public in March
1986, revealed bulletproof powder rooms, a bedside grand piano, and
a videotape of a birthday party _ the guests in baby clothes and a
fat man in diapers jumping out of the cake.
   At the couple's Manhattan townhouse, representatives of
President Corazon Aquino's government recorded neglect and evidence
of a hasty retreat: rare books beneath a boiler; Steuben stemware
worth $150 to $200 per glass scattered inside an oven; two smashed,
Louis XV mirrors lying in water.
   Fueled by the public's fascination with the Marcos frippery,
collectors eagerly shelled out $850,000 for antiques, plastic palm
trees and trinkets from the townhouse at an August 1986 auction
held by the Aquino government.
   The federal indictment issued in New York last October accuses
Mrs. Marcos and her husband of stealing $168 million.
   But the Philippine government accuses them of walking off with
from $3.5 billion to $10 billion in cash and property. If
recovered, the money could help reduce that nation's large foreign
debt.
   Either directly or indirectly, the money allegedly was spent on
prime Manhattan real estate, a $4 million home in Beverly Hills,
Calif., paintings by artists including Picasso and Van Gogh, among
other purchases.
   Marcos' 20-year rule came to a swift end in a public uprising
after he was accused of stealing a presidential election from Mrs.
Aquino.
   When the Marcoses fled to the United States on Feb. 26, 1986,
the Customs Service impounded more than $7 million in cash,
valuables and jewelry, including 48 square feet of pearls, from
their plane.
   Included in the indictment against the Marcoses and eight others
were racketeering charges that couple looted more than $103 million
from the Philippines to buy art and real estate in New York City.
The indictment also said they defrauded lending institutions of
more than $165 million in buying and financing the real estate.
   A superseding indictment in March accused them of illegally
funneling an additional $77 million into this country _ at least
$65 million of it allegedly stolen from the Philippines.
   Indicted along with the Marcoses was Adnan Khashoggi, 54, a
flamboyant Saudi financier once reputed to be the world's
wealthiest man. He was also accused of siphoning money from the
Philippines into the United States to buy real estate and art.
   The death of Marcos will not change the thrust of the defense,
said Robert Morvillo, attorney for Khashoggi.
   The Aquino government also sought $50 billion in punitive
damages in a lawsuit filed in federal court in California against
the Marcoses and an aide, Ramon Azurin. The Marcoses were accused
in the suit of bribery, extortion, theft and other charges in a
scheme to steal billions of dollars in public money for their
personal benefit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
