<DOCNO> AP890928-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 2058EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NASASafety     09-28 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NASA Safety,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Development of New Shuttle Boosters Questioned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of a NASA advisory panel said
Thursday that he questioned the space agency's decision to develop
a new generation of shuttle booster rocket.
   Joe Sutter, chairman of the Aerospace Safety Advisory Panel,
told a House subcommittee on space science and applications that
NASA could continue to rely on the redesigned solid rocket motor
that has been in use since the 1986 Challenger explosion.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration, Sutter said,
should instead focus its attention and limited financial resources
on safety programs within the current shuttle program.
   That need is critical while NASA accelerates the shuttle
program, building up to 14 annual launches by 1994, he said.
   ``We still consider the space shuttle an inherently high-risk
endeavor,'' he said. ``The present NASA management organization
with its greater emphasis on safety and quality assurance, which is
excellent, should be maintained and strengthened.''
   The hearing of the Science, Space and Technology subcommittee
was called to review the annual report of Sutter's panel. The
report in March had contained a recommendation to postpone
development of a so-called advanced solid rocket motor and focus on
the redesigned version.
   However, NASA decided to procure the new rocket, saying it can
deliver heavier loads and, more important, addresses a number of
safety problems brought out by the Challenger disaster.
   The new design emphasizes welds over bolts, allows for
mechanical closing of joints and has different seals that permit
more visual inspection, NASA said. The joints were blamed in the
Challenger disaster.
   NASA in April awarded a $1.1 billion contract to Lockheed to
develop 44 advanced motors, with the first to be delivered in 1994.
   ``It is still the No. 1 priority with me,'' said J.R. Thompson,
NASA deputy administrator. ``It is the last system that failed.
(When it fails) it always fails catastrophically.''
   Thompson also said the manufacture of the new rocket motor would
be less labor intensive and thus less prone to human error.
   The panel said that many of the improvements could be
incorporated into the current design.
   Sutter told the panel that NASA needs to have a tried-and-true
shuttle rocket ready for the space station program in 1995, since
it will rely on the shuttle for construction, supply and operation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
