<DOCNO> AP890928-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 2021EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Hugo-PriceGouging     09-28 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Price Gouging,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economist: Price Gouging Law May Slow Recovery</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laws designed to protect victims of
Hurricane Hugo from price gouging may actually delay the flow of
supplies to rebuild this storm-ravaged city, an economist says.
   ``There are strong needs for certain items. When the word gets
out you are willing to pay $200 for a sheet of plywood ... 20
million self-employed contractors will start shipping in plywood,''
said David Laband, an associate professor in economics at Clemson
University in western South Carolina.
   If there is no potential for a sizeable profit, there is no
financial incentive to send additional supplies into the area,
Laband said Wednesday in a telephone interview.
   Charleston has imposed a price-gouging ordinance that calls for
fines of $250 and jail terms upon conviction.
   Mayor Joseph Riley Jr. defined price gouging as selling items at
prices substantially higher than prices before the storm. ``It's
hard to define but I know it when I see it,'' he said.
   Earlier this week, an out-of-town contractor was arrested for
allegedly charging $20,000 to remove downed trees from a yard.
   Gov. Carroll Campbell has said the state also will prosecute
suspected price gougers under anti-trust laws.
   But Laband said any price increases as a result of price gouging
tend to be temporary. ``Prices fall almost as immediately as they''
rise, he said.
   There are similar supply issues in other areas that people do
not get as excited about, Laband said. For instance, he said, math
and science teachers are in short supply and can demand higher
salaries.
   ``The people who have the goods are in a position to `gouge'
their employers,'' he said.
   The same theory applies to ice.
   ``Prices come down for an item when there is plenty of it,'' he
said. ``When prices are artificially low and there is no supply
side pressure, you end up having no ice for two weeks and people
are worse off.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
