<FIRST>r w AM-SkinheadLawsuit     09-28 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Skinhead Lawsuit,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homosexual Files Suit Against Skinhead Group for Assault</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Note content of 4th graf may be objectionable to some readers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A homosexual man said Thursday he is seeking
$20 million in damages against members of a ``Skinhead'' gang for
alleged anti-homosexual violence.
   The D.C. Superior Court suit alleges the group of shaven-head
men and women planned and executed ``a vicious gay-bashing
campaign'' in which Rodney Johnson was beaten and robbed.
   Johnson said he was walking home from work at a restaurant in
the Georgetown section of Washington during the early morning hours
of Sept. 17, 1988, when he was attacked by a group of men with
baseball bats.
   ``While I was being beaten they were shouting `die, faggot,
die,''' the 37-year-old admitted homosexual said in a telephone
interview.
   Johnson suffered a concussion, fractured skull, collapsed lungs
and broken bones in the attack.
   Six men and two women, all believed to be minors from the
Washinton area, are named in the suit. Three of them were charged
with assault in connection with the incident.
   ``I felt that there should be some other form of justice or some
way to get at these guys and all the other people responsible for
this type of thing,'' said Johnson of his suit, which was filed
earlier this month.
   ``I feel we all have the right to walk down the street without
being attacked, either physically or verbally,'' Johnson said.
``Gays are not protected in lot of ways under some of these laws.''
   ``I think this case is an unprecedented case. It is the first
time the Skinheads have been sued for their violent, hateful
behavior,'' said Paula Ettelbrick, Johnson's attorney with the
Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund.
   ``It's also the first time that a gay victim has sued the
Skinheads under the federal civil rights laws,'' she added,
explaining damages were being sought under a 100-year-old law,
known as the Ku Klux Klan Act.
   ``We want to set a precedent that the Skinheads are the present
day embodiment of a hate group,'' she said.
   Other lawyers, civil rights and homosexual support groups
joining the suit include attorney Linda Delaney of Lyons, Mack,
Delaney & Young; the D.C. Gay and Lesbian Activists Alliance; the
Atlanta-based Center for Democratic Renewal; the National Gay and
Lesbian Task Force; and the Anti-Defamation League.
</TEXT>
