<FIRST>r w AM-RedDye     09-28 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Red Dye,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Files Suit Against FDA Over Red Dye No. 3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A public interest group filed suit Thursday
against the Food and Drug Administration, trying to force the
agency to ban Red Dye No. 3 as a cancer-causing food additive.
   The additive, which among other things gives marachino cherries
their bright glow, ``represents a completely unnecessary risk of
cancer to American consumers,'' said William B. Schultz, an
attorney for Public Citizen.
   The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court, cites repeated
extensions of the FDA's deadline for ruling on the safety of the
additive as evidence that FDA Commissioner Frank Young has acted in
bad faith.
   FDA spokesman Jeff Nesbitt said the agency had no comment on the
suit.
   The FDA on Aug. 30 extended for two months its deadline for
deciding whether to ban Red Dye No. 3. That pushed the dealine to
Oct. 30.
   The House in July passed legislation calling for further study
of the food coloring. The Senate has not acted on the legislation.
   Since 1960, when Congress called for a ban on foods that cause
cancer in laboratory animals, Red Dye No. 3 and other additives
have been on a provisional list that allowed them to remain on the
market for an additional two years pending further study.
   Public Citizen said that since then, the FDA has granted 40
extensions to the provisional listing of Red Dye No. 3.
