<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Budget     09-28 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Budget,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Slash Projected Budget Deficit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet government has slashed its projected
budget deficit for 1989 from an estimated $187 billion to $143
billion largely through cuts in government spending on
construction, factory equipment and defense, Tass said Thursday.
   Since nearly all businesses in the Soviet Union are
government-owned, the budget includes most of the capital
investment projects in the country.
   The official Tass news agency report did not say if Vladimir
Panskov, a deputy finance minister, detailed the defense cuts in
his testimony to a committee of the Supreme Soviet legislature.
   Soviet officials said earlier this week they planned to trim the
defense budget from $119 billion this year to $109 billion in 1990
as part of a planned 14 percent cut in military spending by 1991.
   Separately, Gen. Anatoly Shabanov told Tass that projected
military spending cuts would save the Soviet Union $46 billion. But
the report did not say when that budget reduction would occur. Nor
did it say if he was counting from the current budget or from
once-projected increases.
   Shabanov also said the military will shift to the civilian
economy 45,000 pieces of major equipment in 1989 and 1990,
including trucks, earthmovers and telephone facilities. He said the
amount to be transferred by the army this year is valued at $774
million.
   Legislators continued debating the budget in Supreme Soviet
committees Thursday. Alexander Orlov from the Ural Mountains
criticized the $155 billion food subsidies, Tass said. Orlov
suggested such funds would be better spent improving agricultural
efficiency.
   The committee on law added a clause to a strike bill that says
only the Supreme Soviet or its parent body, the Congress of
People's Deputies, would have the power to ban strikes. That panel
also debated a blanket prohibition on strikes in certain areas of
the economy but came to no decision, Tass said.
</TEXT>
