<FIRST>u w AM-FBI-RapSong 1stLd-Writethru a0708 09-28 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FBI-Rap Song, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0708,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>ACLU Criticizes FBI Letter About Rap Song</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to explain song title, UPDATE with Justice
Department comment and include sample of lyrics. Picks up 10th graf pvs,
`Ahlerich said...' Note contents of 3rd graf and 10th graf may offend some
readers. `Tha' in the title of the song is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A civil righs group Thursday accused the FBI
of trying to intimidate a music company for distributing a
controversial record that the FBI contends encourages violence
against police.
   ``It's extraordinarily frightening to get a letter from the FBI
saying the FBI has officially decided they don't like your music
... and to intimate that the music is going to cause violence,''
said Barry Lynn, legislative counsel for the American Civil
Liberties Union.
   The letter was written by Milt Ahlerich, FBI assistant director
for public affairs, to Priority Records about the song ``---- Tha
Police'' by the rap group NWA. The song's title contains an
obscenity.
   ``It (the letter) intimidates the recipient because the source
is the federal government ... (and) is likely to have a very
chilling effect on that record company and that artist,'' Lynn said.
   Lynn said he and representatives of Music in Action, a group
concerned with censorship of rock music, met with a Justice
Department official Monday to demand a retraction of the letter.
   Thomas Boyd, director of the department's office of policy
development, didn't take a position on the letter but said he would
look into it, Lynn said.
   Justice Department spokesman Dan Eramian said Thursday that the
department ``will review all of their concerns and points of view
and try to be helpful where we can.''
   Eramian said Ahlerich was ``expressing his point of view and
that's his right under free speech. He is not advocating taking
action. He's just saying I don't believe you should be doing
anything that advocates violence against police.''
   Ahlerich, in an interview Thursday, said the letter was
``absolutely not'' a threat against the Los Angeles record company
and that ``it's their decision to distribute it.''
   The song includes lines such as ``beat a police outta shape,''
and ``takin' out a police will make my day.'' The song says police
believe ``every nigger is selling narcotics.''
   Gunfire is heard in the background of the record.
   Ahlerich said ``We wanted to take the opportunity to supply
(Priority) with information about violence associated with police
officers ... and concern about violence in this country. It was not
anything past that.''
   Ahlerich said he had received a ``couple of letters'' from
anti-censorship groups but no response from Priority.
   The Associated Press obtained a copy of the Aug. 1 letter from
the trade publication Radio &amp; Records. The letter, written on
official FBI stationery, was addressed to Gui Manganiello,
Priority's national promotions director.
   ``Advocating violence and assault is wrong, and we in the law
enforcement community take exception to such action,'' Ahlerich
wrote, adding that he felt the song advocated such violence.
   ``Seventy-eight law enforcement officers were feloniously slain
in the line of duty in 1988, four more than in 1987. Law
enforcement officers dedicate their lives to the protection of our
citizens, and recordings such as the one from NWA are both
discouraging and degrading to these brave, dedicated officers. ...
I wanted you to be aware of the FBI's position relative to this
song and its message.''
   Manganiello did not immediately return a call seeking comment
Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
