<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 2154EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-PostalService     09-28 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Postal Service,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Postal Equipment Firm Was Victimized, Attorney Tells Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top executives at Recognition Equipment Inc.
of Dallas were victimized by a Michigan consultant and the former
vice chairman of the postal board of governors, a defense attorney
said Thursday.
   The postal governor, Peter Voss, and Detroit-area consultant
John Gnau ``played us like a violin,'' atorney Robert Bennett said
in federal court at the criminal trial of REI and two of its
officers.
   REI hired Gnau at Voss's urging and the company agreed to pay
Gnau $325,000 in a little more than a year in an attempt to get
$400 million in postal service contracts.
   ``They were pumping us up'' into believing REI would get the
postal business, Bennett said.
   The company, along with chief operating officer William Moore
and marketing vice president Robert Reedy, are accused of
conspiring with Voss, Gnau and others to fraudulently obtain the
postal contracts to build mail-sorting equipment.
   U.S. postal inspectors uncovered an arrangement in which Gnau
allegedly agreed to share some of the money he got from REI with
Voss.
   Bennett, who represents Reedy, said REI executives were unaware
of Voss and Gnau's ``hidden agenda.''
   Voss and Gnau ``were looking for pigeons,'' Bennett said. If a
company was ``trying to get business with the postal service and
not doing very well, they would be targeted'' by Voss and Gnau,
said Bennett.
   Voss and Gnau agreed that REI would never be told about the
arrangement, the lawyer added.
   Bennett said that in order for the government to prove REI was
part of a conspiracy, it would have to show that Voss and Gnau told
REI executives, ``We can make music together. Here is how much it
will cost.''
   ``That didn't happen,'' Bennett said.
   The attorney said Reedy failed to tell postal inspectors the
truth just once, an incident for which Reedy later apologized to
the government and for which he hasn't been charged with a crime.
   A U.S. postal inspector asked Reedy on April 8, 1986, how Reedy
had met Gnau. Reedy told the inspector it was through a public
relations executive, according to Bennett.
   In fact, it was Voss who urged Reedy in the fall of 1984 to hire
Gnau's firm.
   The first witness in the trial, postal contract officer John
Simmons, testified that Voss at one meeting in 1985 criticized
postal official Currie Boswell, who favored the type of
mail-sorting equipment that was manufactured by REI's competitors.
   Voss ``kind of blamed Mr. Boswell's group for going down the
wrong path,'' Simmons testified, adding that Voss had leveled a
parting shot at Boswell as people filed out of the meeting.
   ``Maybe we'll send you some flowers,'' Voss told Boswell,
according to Simmons, signifying that Boswell's career was in
peril. Boswell currently is director of the postal service's office
of operational requirements.
   Voss, who headed Ronald Reagan's 1980 Ohio presidential
campaign, received a four-year prison term in 1986 after pleading
guilty to expense account fraud and taking an illegal gratuity from
Gnau in connection with efforts to steer postal contracts to REI.
   Gnau, who headed Reagan's 1980 Michigan campaign, was sentenced
to three years for conspiracy and paying an illegal $2,500 gratuity
to Voss in connection with work on behalf of REI.
   Voss and Gnau are to be government witnesses in the non-jury
trial before U.S. District Court Judge George Revercomb.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
