<FIRST>u a AM-MineRescue     09-28 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mine Rescue,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cub Scout Describes Five-Day Ordeal In Abandoned Mine</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Quotes in graf 12 are cq.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SK1,2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE CARTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When 10-year-old Joshua Dennis was rescued
from an abandoned mine after five days, he had long since exhausted
his tiny supply of licorice but thought he'd been missing only a
couple of days.
   ``Mostly I just slept a lot of the time. I got tired of looking
around and just sat there,'' the boy said Thursday. ``I wasn't
feeling very lonely or scared ... but I cried once.''
   His feet mottled purple with mild frostbite and propped on a
pillow, Joshua spoke from his hospital bed just 24 hours after
rescuers found him on a ledge some 2,000 feet inside the mine where
he got lost during a scouting expedition.
   ``I was just following the wall,'' after being separated from
his father inside the mine last Friday night, he said. ``There was
a whole bunch of exits and I went down the wrong one.''
   Joshua is in good condition and expected to go home to suburban
Kearns over the weekend, his doctor at Primary Children's Medical
Center said.
   ``He's squared away. ... He'll do just fine,'' Dr. Ted Jenkins
said.
   The boy's father, Terry Dennis, said Joshua went into the Hidden
Treasure mine with 10 bite-size pieces of licorice in his pocket.
He exhausted the meager cache only after slowly sucking one piece
at a time. He had no water and was dehydrated when found Wednesday
afternoon.
   Joshua, Cub Scout, strayed from the Boy Scout group his father
was helping supervise on an expedition into the former silver, lead
and zinc mine in the Oquirrh Mountains 45 miles southwest of Salt
Lake City.
   After five days, hope had all but vanished that the boy would be
found alive. Then a search team that had passed within 150 feet of
him in half a dozen sweeps heard his faint cry and discovered him
on the ledge.
   Joshua said that during his vigil he had heard searchers' voices
a few times but his cries for help weren't heard.
   ``I wondered how long it was going to take me to find my way
out,'' he said. ``I couldn't really hear what they were saying. I
called for help, but not one of the times they couldn't hear me.''
   At the head of his bed was a white hard hat inscribed with the
names of the two Utah Power &amp; Light Co. mine rescue team members
who found him.
   ``I was thinking if it was day or night, or what day it was. I
thought it was night, and when they told me it was Wednesday I
thought it was Sunday,'' Joshua said.
   Sheriff's deputies, utility crews, search dogs and dozens of
volunteers had scoured the mine's tunnels and surrounding canyon
areas in their search, finally concluding that Joshua probably had
left the mine only to fall into one of hundreds of other abandoned
mines nearby.
   But Ray Guymon and Gary Christensen returned to double-check an
ore pocket with a local historian, John Skinner, whose grandfather
once was superintendent of the same mine.
   Christensen found Joshua in a 6-by-20-foot cavity in the ore
pocket about 500 feet from where he was last seen.
</TEXT>
