<FIRST>u i AM-US-Mideast     09-28 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mideast,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Raises Hope For Mideast Negotiations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III held
out hope Thursday of Israel and Palestinian Arabs holding
negotiations on the future of the West Bank and Gaza.
   But Baker was cautious at a news conference after meeting
jointly with Foreign Ministers Moshe Arens of Israel and Esmet
Abdel-Meguid of Egypt.
   ``There may be some potential for progress,'' he said. But,
Baker added, ``we really will not know'' until key members of the
Israeli Cabinet meet in Jerusalem next Wednesday.
   Baker again endorsed a plan by Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir for negotiations with Palestinian Arabs to be elected on the
West Bank and in Gaza.
   He said a 10-point formula for negotiations advanced by Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak ``was not, in any sense, a competing
proposal.''
   Some of Mubarak's points upset Shamir, particularly having one
or two of the Palestinians deported during the rebellion
participate in the negotiations.
   Mubarak also demanded that Israel commit itself to relinquishing
territory in exchange for peace.
   Baker stressed the U.S. goal was ``to look for ways to move the
process forward.''
   He added: ``We're in this thing to try to find a way to move
toward peace.''
   Baker has been in New York all week meeting with foreign
ministers who are attending the special session of the United
Natiions General Assembly. He will hold a news conference Friday
before returning to Washington.
   Arens told Israeli reporters, meanwhile, that he would like
Mubarak to endorse the entire Shamir proposal.
   The Egyptian president, who is due to address the assembly on
Friday, met separately with Israeli Deputy Prime Minister Shimon
Peres.
   He told Peres no Palestinian objedtionable to Israel would be in
the negotiating delegation.
   He also said he would be willing to meet with Shamir to launch
tne negotiations.
   In a sudden flurry of Mideast diplomacy, Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard A. Shevardnadze met with Arens and offered to act as an
intermediary between the Palestinians and Israel.
   Baker was not impressed. Noting the complications in getting
Mideast talks started, he said ``I don't react positively to this.''
