<FIRST>r w AM-GenericDrugs     09-28 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Generic Drugs,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDA Downgrades A Hypertension Drug</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration on Thursday
formally downgraded its rating of a generic drug made by Bolar
Pharmaceutical Co. for treating high blood pressure, saying it is
not equivalent to Dyazide, the brand-name product.
   By changing the code it assigns Bolar's product, the FDA is
telling physicians that it does not consider the generic drug to
have the same therapeutic value as the brand-name drug.
   The FDA had announced plans for the change on Aug. 28 when it
also began moving to withdraw the generic from the market because
of questions about whether the drug has the same effect as Dyzaide.
The removal process is still under way.
   In a letter to Copiague, N.Y.-based Bolar, Carl C. Peck,
director of the FDA's Center for Drug Evaluation and Research, said
``significant questions remain as to the reliability'' of the data
the company submitted to the FDA as part of safety and
effectiveness tests conducted last year.
   ``There appear to be significant misrepresentations in your
documentation of this raw ingredient testing which you have not
adequately explained,'' he said. ``These facts alone warrant a
change in the therapeutic equivalence rating.''
   He also cited ``unorthodox practices and inconsistent
representations of information'' in the reporting to FDA of
bioequivalence testing results. This testing, required for FDA
approval to make and sell copies of brand-name drugs, is designed
to show that a generic drug dissolves in the body at roughly the
same rate and produces approximately the same effect as the
brand-name product.
   Bolar officials could not be reached for comment. Their offices
said they had left for the day.
   Bolar is one of 11 generic drug companies the FDA is
investigating after disclosures of fraud and corruption involving
some companies and employees in FDA's generic drug division and
admissions by some companies that they had provided false data to
the agency.
   The agency is also sampling 30 of the most prescribed generic
drugs and their brand-name counterparts to test the safety of these
products.
</TEXT>
