<FIRST>r w AM-Yeutter-Durum     09-28 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yeutter-Durum,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeutter Refuses to Intervene With Canada For Durum Producers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP BRASHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter refused
to take action against Canada for its U.S exports of durum wheat,
saying there is no proof of a ``lack of cooperative spirit on
Canada's part.''
   In a letter to Rep. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., Yeutter blamed a sharp
rise in Canadian durum exports on periodic shortfalls in U.S.
production and tight supplies caused by use of Agriculture
Department loan and export subsidy programs.
   The administration is committed ``to take action against
Canada's wheat export policies in the event that trade problems in
this sector cannot be resolved cooperatively between our two
countries,'' Yeutter wrote.
   ``However a look at the facts surrounding recent increases in
U.S. imports of durum from Canada does not indicate a lack of
cooperative spirit on Canada's part.''
   Canada, which did not ship any durum to the U.S. before 1985,
now has 13 percent of the U.S. market.
   Canada exported 2.3 million bushels to the U.S. in the 1986-87
marketing year, 7.4 million bushels in 1987-88 and 6.84 million
bushels for the 1988-89 marketing year that ended July 31.
   Durum, which is grown primarily in North Dakota, is used to make
pasta.
   Dorgan has been urging Yeutter to pressure Canada to reduce its
durum exports and charged Thursday that he reneged on a promise to
ensure Canada didn't dump grain on U.S. markets after the two
countries' free-trade agreement took effect this year.
   American producers are prohibited from selling wheat in Canada
until the levels of government subsidies in the two countries are
determined to be equal.
   ``I'm terribly disappointed that the secretary has taken the
position that American durum producers are on their own and don't
deserve protection from unfair exports from Canada,'' Dorgan said.
</TEXT>
