<FIRST>u a AM-CanyonCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0779 09-28 0713</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canyon Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0779,0730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Passenger: A Pilot Struggled With Controls Before Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS lead to reflect that survivor saw either pilot or co-pilot
struggling with controls; INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd to raise reference to
plane's previous landing problem; SUBS 5th graf pvs, `John Lauber ...'
to CLARIFY Lauber a member of safety board; SUBS 12th graf pvs, `Ms. Mayes
...' to CORRECT that she heard and felt, not saw, wheel touch and conform
to lead; SUBS 19th graf pvs, `The records ...' to CORRECT Warren is not
attribution on FAA records.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FLS1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUSAYAN, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who survived the crash of a
sightseeing plane on approach to Grand Canyon Airport said Thursday
a pilot struggled with the controls before the aircraft ``shot
straight up'' and flipped over.
   ``I crawled as far away as I could and I waited for the
medics,'' Katherine Mayes told reporters from her hospital bed in
Flagstaff.
   ``I'm sure they got there as fast as they could, but it seemed
an eternity,'' said the 66-year-old woman from Nashville, Tenn.
   The Federal Aviation Administration, meanwhile, disclosed that
the same plane also lost control while landing in February and
cited a ``possible nose-wheel centering problem.''
   Ten of 21 people on board the de Havilland DHC-6 Twin Otter were
killed Wednesday when the Grand Canyon Airlines plane veered from
the runway into a wooded hill 300 yards away, authorities said.
   John Lauber, a member of the National Transportation Safety
Board, said transcripts of radio communication between air traffic
controllers and the pilot revealed nothing unusual.
   ``They were cleared to land and that was the last communication
with the aircraft,'' he said.
   The two crew members, pilot William Welch, 47, of Sedona, Ariz.,
and co-pilot Keith Crosson, 43, of Kailua Kona, Hawaii, were among
those killed. The twin-engine plane was returning from a
sightseeing trip over the Grand Canyon.
   Ms. Mayes was among 11 people injured. Three survivors were in
serious condition, one was in guarded condition and seven were in
stable condition Thursday at Flagstaff Medical Center, about 75
miles away.
   Federal investigators were at the crash site Thursday. NTSB team
and representatives of the plane's manufacturers were expected to
spend four or five days at the site.
   The investigation will be ``somewhat more difficult'' by the
lack of a cockpit voice recorder or flight data recorder, Lauber
said. The devices are not required for the DCH-6.
   Investigators had not spoken to survivors by Thursday, Lauber
said.
   Ms. Mayes, who had a severely bruised right shoulder and a
broken pelvis, said she heard and felt the right wheel of the plane
touch the runway. Then she heard the aircraft skid and looked up to
see either the pilot or co-pilot struggling with the controls just
before the airplane ``shot straight up.''
   She said she heard a buzzing sound before the plane flipped over.
   ``I'm really fortunate. God really blessed me. He blessed us
all. He worked a miracle right there before our eyes,'' Ms. Mayes
said.
   She vowed never to fly again, and said she would travel home to
Tennessee by van when she is released from the hospital.
   ``I'm not going back on any plane. I'll crawl before I do
that,'' Ms. Mayes said.
   Welch had worked 3{ years for Grand Canyon Airlines and logged
about 2,000 hours of flight time, Lauber said. Crosson was in his
first year with the airline, said Ronald L. Warren, vice president
and general manager of the airline.
   FAA records showed the 14-year-old plane had a problem while
landing at the airport last Feb. 27. The plane ``lost directional
control on landing. Struck wingtip on runway. Possible nose-wheel
centering problem.''
   The FAA records indicated only two crew members were aboard and
neither was injured. The records listed wind as a contributing
cause in that incident. Warren said he did not know the final
determination of the cause.
   Warren said the plane veered to the right on Feb. 27 but went to
the left Wednesday. On Feb. 27, the plane was piloted by a then-new
employee who was being checked out by the pilot killed in
Wednesday's crash, Warren said.
   FAA spokeswoman Elly Brekke said controllers in the airport's
tower reported seeing the aircraft veer right, then left.
</TEXT>
