<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 2127EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-RoyalBallet     09-28 0163</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Royal Ballet,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sadler's Wells to Take a New Name</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sadler's Wells Royal Ballet, an illustrious name
in the dance world since 1946, will become the Birmingham Royal
Ballet next year when it moves to the English Midlands city.
   The Royal Opera House, parent company of the ballet, announced
the name change Thursday along with plans to premiere four new
works in the two years after the move.
   Birmingham, 100 miles northwest of London, has drawn the company
with offers of increased funding, and on Thursday the Opera House
general director Jeremy Isaacs said the city also offered $6.4
million for a new headquarters and studios.
   The company was formed in 1931 by Dame Ninette de Valois as the
Vic-Wells Ballet, performing at Sadler's Wells Theater and the Old
Vic.
   It went to the Royal Opera House in Covent Garden after the
theater was bombed in World War II, and was named the Sadler's
Wells Royal Ballet in 1946.
</TEXT>
