<SECOND>AM-China-Cambodia,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Denies Contacts With Phnom Penh Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China said Thursday that reports it had begun
unofficial talks with the Vietnam-backed government in Cambodia are
``entirely groundless.''
   China ``has never had any relations with the illegal Phnom Penh
regime,'' the Foreign Ministry said in a statement.
   The chief editor of a government-sponsored magazine in Phnom
Penh recently told The Associated Press that three Chinese
officials had discussed resumption of trade ties during a visit to
Cambodia early this year as part of a Thai business group.
   A Foreign Ministry official said another group of 15 Chinese
officials was expected in January, and an East European diplomat
said he believed Cambodian military officials had conducted talks
with Chinese officials in the Laotian capital of Vientiane.
   China is the main backer of the Khmer Rouge and other resistance
factions fighting Vietnamese troops and the forces of the Phnom
Penh government.
   Earlier Thursday, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said Vietnam's
claimed withdrawal of the last of its troops from Cambodia was a
sham, and indicated China will continue to arm the resistance
forces until a political settlement is reached among the warring
factions.
   The ministry said: ``Before a comprehensive, just and reasonable
political settlement of the Kampuchea (Cambodia) issue is realized,
China will never establish economic relations'' or any other
relations with the Phnom Penh government.
   ``It is despicable and futile for the Phnom Penh side to
fabricate lies with ulterior motives, split up and sow discord and
confuse public opinion.''
