<DOCNO> AP890928-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 2131EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Colombia 4thLd-Writethru a0810 09-28 0970</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Colombia, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0810,940</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barco Seeks Help from US on Trade Issues</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: TOPS with 24 grafs new or rewritten to reflect Fitzwater comments
on the Bush-Barco meeting; picks up 25th graf: ``Barco ordered,'' drops
last three grafs to trim. Stands for AMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush welcomed Colombian President
Virgilio Barco to the White House on Thursday evening with praise
for Barco's crackdown on drug traffickers and assurances of help to
improve trade to support Colombia's economy.
   However, there was no movement to help raise the price of coffee
_ Colombia's major legal export and the subject of dispute between
the two countries rising from U.S. attacks on international price
supports.
   At the meeting, which stretched from the originally scheduled
half-hour to about 1{ hours, Bush ``indicated his intention to work
closely with President Barco to expand bilateral trade and
investment opportunities in order to spur Colombia's economic
growth,'' White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said in a
statement.
   Bush said he had asked U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills
``to lead an interagency effort to examine urgently what can be
done'' to improve trade benefits, according to Fitzwater.
   U.S. officials have said trade concessions are being considered
for some Colombian exports such as flowers and textiles. Another
possibility is providing inducements for U.S. private investment in
Colombia.
   But on coffee, Bush only reiterated that the United States is
prepared to resume talks with Colombia and others on renewal of the
International Coffee Agreement, Fitzwater said.
   Last week, Bush rejected a plea by Barco for a one-year
reinstatement of a coffee-export quota system that had helped
Colombian farmers.
   World coffee prices have fallen by about a third sharply since
the 74-nation cartel suspended export quotas after the United
States, backed by some Central American countries who wanted larger
quotas, blocked a new agreement in July.
   Colombian officials have suggested it will be difficult to keep
farmers from switching from coffee to coca. Most cocaine entering
the United States is grown in Peru and Bolivia and processed in
Colombia, where the major cocaine gangs are based.
   Another issue raised at the meeting was U.S. drug consumption,
which Barco has long criticized as the fuel supporting the violent
drug traffickers who plague his country.
   ``The two presidents talked about the domestic drug problem in
the United States and the administration's efforts to reduce
consumption,'' Fitzwater said.
   The Colombian president, making his first visit to Washington
since launching the crackdown on drug traffickers last month, told
reporters before the meeting that he was seeking no additional
financial help in his country's battle against traffickers.
   ``We have received ... help with our problem,'' Barco said,
referring to $65 million in emergency assistance from the United
States, during a photo session with Bush in the White House Rose
Garden.
   Bush expressed appreciation ``on the part of the American
people'' for Barco's efforts to combat drug traffickers, but he
declined to say during the photo session what help the United
States might provide on trade matters.
   Participants in the White House meeting included national drug
policy director William J. Bennett, Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh, National Security Advisor Brent Scowcroft, White House
Chief of Staff John H. Sununu and Deputy Secretary of State
Lawrence Eagleburger.
   Barco met earlier Thursday with Bennett under tight security at
the Colombian ambassador's home.
   At that meeting, Bennett said later, Barco raised various
issues, including trade matters such as coffee and cut flowers. But
Bennett declined to provide details of the help Barco wants,
saying, ``We were mainly there to listen.''
   During a meeting with members of the House, Barco raised the
issue of U.S. assault-style weapons being smuggled into his country
for use by drug traffickers, said Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y.,
chairman of the House Select Committee on Narcotics Abuse.
   Barco stressed not only the need for Americans to reduce their
consumption of cocaine, ``but also the manufacture of automatic
weapons that are being distributed in international markets that
are killing his people,'' Rangel said.
   Bennett said he and Barco had discussed this problem at an
earlier meeting, but the Colombian president did not raise it again
today.
   ``It's a matter I'm concerned about,'' Bennett said, adding that
he had spoken with Stephen Higgins, the director of the Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms who ``assured me there will be more
attention paid to this, more resources, more of his people are
going to be one this.''
   The Bush administration has banned the import of assault rifles,
but has not acted against domestic manufacture of such weapons.
   Among other subjects raised by Barco with the House members were
his concerns over the manufacture of chemicals used to process
cocaine, foreign mercenaries and laundering of drug money.
   ``He emphasized that while he didn't need troops, he needed a
lot of help in these other areas,'' Rangel said.
   Barco ordered emergency measures to crack down on the drug
traffickers after the Aug. 18 assassination of leading presidential
candidate Luis Carlos Galan, an outspoken foe of the drug trade.
   Those measures, including the resumption of extradition to the
United States of suspected drug traffickers, prompted the
traffickers to declare ``total war'' on the government. They have
set off bombs, killed several people at the Bogota airport and
vowed to kill 10 judges for every trafficker extradited.
   Since 1981, about 50 judges and 170 judicial employees have been
killed and judges this year have repeatedly walked off the job or
threatened to strike over a lack of security. Colombia's former
justice minister, Monica de Greiff, resigned last week after
receiving numerous death threats.
   Bennett said he stressed to Barco ``that American public opinion
was strongly behind what he is doing. Americans salute his courage,
his resolution, his bravery and the bravery and resoluteness of the
Colombian people.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
