<FIRST>r i AM-FallsDaredevils     09-28 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Falls Daredevils,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Decade Of The Daredevil' Continues at Niagara Falls</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto CPP8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON LESKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NIAGARA FALLS, Ontario (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When frustrated stuntman Karel
Soucek became the first person in 23 years to take the plunge over
Niagara Falls in a barrel in 1984, he proclaimed himself ``the last
of the Niagara daredevils.''
   But the Czech-born Canadian Soucek was no prophet. On Wednesday,
Canadians Peter DeBernardi and Jeffrey Petkovich became the third
and fourth men to accomplish the stunt since Soucek's ride and the
first duo to ever go over the falls together.
   ``Perhaps Karel Soucek's success motivates them,'' Niagara Parks
Police Chief Wilfred J. Derbyshire said Thursday of the increase of
attempts during this decade.
   Overall, 12 adventurers have gone over the falls in a barrel.
Nine have survived the 176-foot plunge. Five men have gone over the
falls in the 1980s, a record for one decade.
   Derbyshire said the increase of successful attempts can be
partly attributed to the proximity of recent launches to the shore.
   With a short stretch of river before the infamous drop, the
barrels often stay clear of most rocks hidden under the cascading
water.
   The high-tech construction of the barrels, Derbyshire admitted,
is probably most responsible for the successful attempts.
   DeBernardi solicited $50,000 from local businesses to construct
the barrel, and had planned the stunt and the construction of the
barrel since the spring of 1988.
   The two survived the voyage with minor cuts and no serious
injuries.
   ``Were we scared?,'' Petkovich, 25, said, ``What for? There's no
doubt that I'd do it again. No sweat.''
   DeBernardi, 42, was more reserved. ``It's something I always
wanted to do. It's a challenge. It's the greatest stunt in the
world, and I'm glad to be alive.''
   The romanticized stunt has been performed for different reasons
since Annie Edson Taylor became the first to survive the plunge on
Oct. 24, 1901.
   Some did it for profit, like Red Hill, Jr., who died performing
the stunt in 1951 to raise money for a memorial to his father, a
famous riverman along the Niagara.
   Others, like Soucek and Steven Trotter, who went over in 1985,
did it in an attempt to bolster their careers as stuntmen.
   Petkovich and DeBernardi, however, said their motivation was to
show kids there is an alternative to drugs.
   ``If you can make that connection, you've got a better
imagination than me,'' retorted Dennis Schafer, general manager of
the Niagara Parks Commission.
   Petkovich and DeBernardi were charged with unlawfully performing
a stunt in the park, which carries a fine of $500. DeBernardi also
faces an additional $1,000 fine for trespassing after he was warned
18 months ago not to perform the stunt.
   Derbyshire and Schafer said the Parks Commission will be on the
lookout for attempts in the near future.
   ``It is not whether you fail or triumph,'' reads the inscription
on the grave of Soucek, who died six months after his falls stunt
during a barrel drop in the Houston Astrodome. ``It's that you keep
your word ... and at least try.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
