<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 2316EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SmoggyLA     09-28 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smoggy LA,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experts: September Means Smog and This Month is Typical</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Memory is playing tricks on Southern
Californians who think the current smog siege is any worse than
usual, experts said Thursday.
   The dirty, brown-tinted air that has prompted first-stage smog
alerts in some areas this week is a seasonal tradition, said
Claudia Keith of the South Coast Air Quality Management District.
   ``I think people kind of forgot what it's like here now,'' Ms.
Keith said. ``We had strange weather last week, foggy and rainy,
and they thought fall had started. We sort of got a resurgence of
summer this week.''
   A mild August with relatively cool, low-smog days also may have
lulled Southern Californians into a false sense of security, she
said. The smog season traditionally runs from May to October.
   Forecaster Bob Grebe of the National Weather Service concurred.
   ``September is hot and smoggy in Southern California,'' Grebe
said Thursday. Atmospheric conditions create an inversion layer
that works to trap pollutants, he said.
   Contributing to the burning eyes and breathing problems that
smog inflicts is a buildup of nitrogen dioxide that is common in
the fall, Ms. Keith said.
   The pollutant stems primarily from vehicle emissions and without
summer's strong sun to burn it off, it ``just sticks in the air,''
she said. Nitrogen dioxide is responsible for the brown-tinged look
of Southern California skies.
   ``It was very smoggy this week, there's no doubt about it,'' Ms.
Keith conceded. ``On top of that there was the nitrogen dioxide, so
it was a double whammy.''
   In 1989 overall, there were somewhat fewer smog alerts than in
years past, Ms. Keith said.
   ``Mostly that was because we had such a good August,'' with
nature lending a hand by providing favorable weather conditions,
she said.
   ``I'd love to say it was because no one was driving, but I
can't,' she added.
   Fifty-two first-stage smog alerts were declared this year after
the pollution index rose above 200 parts per million. There were no
second-stage alerts, which Ms. Keith said are rare in any year.
   The district advises children and the elderly to curtail
activities and remain indoors during a first-stage smog alert.
</TEXT>
