<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 2336EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Anderson Adv02   09-28 0936</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Anderson, Adv 02,0972</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday AMs, Oct. 2, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>An Avant-Garde Artist Who's Still Avant-Garde</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laurie Anderson became America's best-known
performance artist in the early 1980s. And, unlike some avant-garde
artists, with whom the mainstream catches up, she's still
avant-garde.
   She opens the Brooklyn Academy of Music's Next Wave Festival on
Tuesday with a piece called ``Empty Places,'' which she premiered
this year at the Spoleto Festival in Charleston, S.C.
   ``Empty Places'' has Anderson on stage singing without a band.
Screens on two 20-foot towers show computer-controlled slides and
film. Images range from grim homelessness to bluebirds of happiness.
   ``I love the way pictures and music can be made to work
together,'' Anderson said.
   ``It's never one of my goals to be a cutting-edge artist. I
think of myself working in the world's oldest art form _
storytelling. There's nothing new about that. The trick is, how do
you tell a good story?
   ``I suppose my goal in `Empty Places' is to describe how much
the world seems to me to have changed in the last few years. It
tries to describe suffering and people's ideas of utopia,'' she
said.
   ``This is going to look very different than things I've done
before. I have absolutely no interest in whether they're
avant-garde or not. Of course artists don't want to bore people and
it's important to invent things. I love things that are surprising
and shocking; I actually consider it a kind of responsibility to do
things not in a usual way.''
   A new Laurie Anderson record, ``Strange Angels,'' which she
worked on for two years, will be released by Warner Bros. on Oct.
24. Seven of its songs are in ``Empty Places.'' Anderson will tour
the show, starting in December in Canada, returning to the United
States in February.
   She has changed the show since Spoleto.
   ``There were a few `head-scratchers' in there,'' she said. ``I
love things that are puzzling in good ways. I had to take out a
couple that were just plain puzzling. I kind of ripped the whole
show apart.''
   Then she got sick and spent time visiting doctors. ``I went to
Rio to do a concert; there were eight people in my group. From
eating fish, quite a few of us got one of these strange new poison
ocean diseases that nobody knows very much about and can't fix very
easily. I got the version of being completely dizzy. We're all a
lot better than we were.
   ``I'm putting the show back together. It is becoming a lot more
political than it was before. The more I look around and also try
to understand what this particular piece is about, the angrier I
get, mostly with things that not too many people seem to be really
talking about.
   ``Everybody in New York knows what it's like to walk out and see
six people lying in their little sidewalk dormitory. It was just so
odd that nobody talked about that in a coherent way in the last
elections. You look around at the eight years that Reagan created
and it is so horrifying to see the results of this rampant `gimme,
gimme' economy,'' she said.
   ``I'm really trying to look at that from a few different angles.
I'm in the midst of redefining the introduction. It is places that
I've shot pictures of, mostly in downtown New York. They're not
exactly ruins but they look like it.
   ``That has been one of the nicest things about working on this
piece,'' Anderson said. ``I go out at night a lot, real late, and
shoot a lot of places. I've shot thousands of things for this
piece, slides, moving images and films that were sent through a
visual digital computer and look very grainy. It's a beautiful look.
   ``Stories work so much better at night and these aren't exactly
bedtime stories. I find some of them kind of horrifying. People
have drifted into the shots. It's a whole different world from
midnight on out there. It's making me feel at home in New York in a
way I never have before.''
   The show also has some cheery animation. ``I was trying to make
a real cartoon with all these screens. I thought, `I need some
Disney-type bluebirds.' Bluebirds make me happy. I drew them on the
computer, with picket fences and roses. There are songs about
Utopia.''
   Are they ironic?
   ``Some of them are; some aren't,'' she replied. ``Irony is a
really tricky thing. I try to use irony sparingly. I'm doing a lot
more singing in this show. I find I can say ironic things but I
can't sing ironic things.
   ``The other big difference in this show is that I've been taking
singing lessons three years. This is the first performance where
I'm trying to use that. To my shock I discovered I was a soprano. I
thought I'd be a low alto. When you sing high, it's a very
vulnerable feeling and you really have to believe what you're
singing. That's not to say some of these songs aren't silly and
preposterous.
   ``There are fewer computerized filters changing my voice. I'm
trying very hard to be truthful. Sometimes that's not very clever
and I don't mind that it's not. These things don't have triple and
quadruple meanings. They have one meaning.''
   Anderson performed her six-hour ``United States Parts I _ IV''
at the 1983 Next Wave Festival. Her last big performing tour was in
1986.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday AMs, Oct. 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890928-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 2338EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Brightman Adv03   09-28 0817</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Brightman, Adv 03,0834</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tuesday AMs, Oct. 3, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sarah Brightman and ``The Songs That Got Away''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some good theater songs just disappear. They
vanish because they are in flop musicals or are overshadowed in hit
shows by more persistent melodies.
   Now there's an attempt to resurrect a dozen or so mostly
forgotten treasures in a new PolyGram release by Sarah Brightman
called ``The Songs That Got Away,'' produced by her husband, Andrew
Lloyd Webber.
   It was one of Lloyd Webber's own unknown efforts, ``Half a
Moment,'' that led to the recording, says Brightman. The song,
which has lyrics by British playwright Alan Ayckbourn, is from
``Jeeves,'' a rare Lloyd Webber failure that ran for only 48
performances in London's West End in 1975.
   Brightman, who starred in the London and New York productions of
``The Phantom of the Opera,'' sang the song as an encore during a
concert she gave in England in 1987.
   ``The audience went mad about it, and then it happened twice
again during two more concerts,'' she recalled during an interview.
``I thought `There must be a lot of lost songs like this one.'''
   So did Lloyd Webber and Thomas Z. Shepard, a veteran New York
record producer who has made many of the best original cast albums,
from ``Company'' to ``La Cage aux folles.'' To find the songs, the
two men culled their extensive record collections of theater music
and started sorting out songs with Brightman.
   ``We kept writing down different lists and from there narrowed
it down to about 100 songs and finally to 14,'' she said.
   The recording was made after Brightman completed her run on
Broadway in ``Phantom,'' an engagement she got through with grace
and good humor after Actors' Equity made noises about not letting
her appear in her husband's show because they thought the role
should go to an American.
   ``I didn't feel part of it in a funny sort of way,'' she said.
``I just got on with my role as well as I could. After all, I'm a
working artist and the public came and paid their money to see me
do my thing.''
   The final selections for the recording include little-known
works of such well-known composers as Richard Rodgers, Leonard
Bernstein, Stephen Sondheim and Marvin Hamlisch.
   Bernstein's calyso-tinged ``Lud's Wedding'' from ``1600
Pennsylvania Avenue,'' a seven-performance flop about the occupants
of the White House, suggests the show's failure was due to its
lugubrious book rather than Berstein's eclectic music that had
lyrics by Alan Jay Lerner.
   Rodgers is represented by two works, ``I Am Going to Like It
Here,'' an affecting lesson in confidence-building from ``Flower
Drum Song,'' and ``Away From You,'' a soaring love song with lyrics
by Sheldon Harnick from their 1976 collaboration about Henry VIII
called ``Rex.''
   When Brightman recorded ``Mister Monotony,'' it was a cult
Irving Berlin song cut first from his ``Miss Liberty'' and then
from ``Call Me Madam.'' Since then, it has found a home _ and a
wide audience _ in ``Jerome Robbins' Broadway.''
   The most unusual selection is Frank Loesser's ``Three Cornered
Tune,'' which was an early version of his famous ``Fugue for
Tinhorns'' from ``Guys and Dolls.''
   Now, instead of extolling the joys of betting on the horses,
Brightman, in three-voice harmony, trills a sweet number about ``a
tender sound, this little tune I found.''
   Most of the recording was done in London and Vienna with several
different orchestrators, although ``Dreamers,'' a song from Marvin
Hamlisch's short-lived musical ``Jean Seberg,'' was done in New
York.
   ``Marvin wanted to use his own musicians and to conduct it
himself. He did it beautifully, giving the song sort of a baroque
quality,'' Brightman said.
   Much of her fall will be occupied with ``The Music of Andrew
Lloyd Webber,'' a concert tour featuring her husband's music done
by soloists and a symphony orchestra. Brightman won't appear in all
the cities on the tour but will sing in some of the major stops
like Los Angeles.
   She also is working on a television project _ tentative title:
``Shooting Star'' _ about the life of Jessie Matthews, the British
musical comedy star known in the United States primarily for her
recording of a Rodgers and Hart classic, ``Dancing on the Ceiling.''
   ``She was a wonderful performer,'' Brightman said. ``She nearly
got the first Ginger Rogers role with Fred Astaire but lost it
because she was contracted to do a musical on Broadway and they
wouldn't let her out of it.
   ``Her whole life was like that. For America, there always was
something that nearly came up and was taken away from her. So she
was only a very big star in Britain and Australia. Now I have a
chance to make her better known.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tuesday AMs, Oct. 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890928-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 1357EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-SpendingJunkies Adv01   09-28 0925</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Spending Junkies, Adv 01,0956</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 1, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>While a Boon to Retailers, Compulsive Spenders Face Addictions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writier</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At last count a woman had 187 belts crammed into
closets and stuffed into drawers, most of them never worn and
hardly even looked at.
   A man thinks only the most expensive exercise bicycle will help
enhance his physique, never mind that he already owns a battery of
body-building equipment that he doesn't use.
   Such people are compulsive spending addicts, and therapists at a
New York psychiatric treatment center take the affliction as
seriously as the problems of alcoholics and drug abusers.
   ``They think that owning things makes them feel better,'' says
Dr. Francesca Kress, director of psychological assessment at the
Hapworth Centers, located an easy browsing distance from the city's
Fifth Avenue shopping mecca.
   ``As their lives become more and more of a disaster, they will
treat themselves to something they can't afford,'' says Kress,
adding that maybe at the back of a buying fanatic's mind is the
thought ``Mommy and Daddy gave me presents and it made me feel
better.''
   Not everyone who occasionally splurges suffers from the
addiction, but people who use shopping to salve troubled minds
might need help.
   ``When material objects are used as a way to assuage feelings of
discomfort, there's a problem,'' according to Kress, who treats
addicts at Hapworth's compulsive spending addiction program.
   From bargain hunters who scour discount outlets to well-heeled
patrons of chic boutiques who think it is beneath them to buy
anything on sale, compulsive spending addiction takes many forms.
   A person might develop the syndrome for any number of reasons.
   There is the case of a patient who, as a child, was given gifts
when being told of divorce plans. The parents planted the mistaken
notion that presents make difficulties go away or at least make
distress easier to bear, which might have caused abnormal spending
desires when the child grew up, Kress suggests.
   ``Rather than deal with a problem they think that they can go
out and buy something to make themselves feel better,'' she says.
   The phenomenon of people living beyond their means or being
obsessed with possessions probably has been around as long as
people have. Cultures that revere wealth have turned the
acquisition habit into an accepted measure of self-worth and
personal success.
   In modern times, explosive growth in credit card ownership has
made it easier for people to indulge their spending passions.
   The powerful pull of plastic has cast credit-card-carrying
consumers adrift in a sea of debt. Groups like New York-based
Budget &amp; Credit Counseling Services Inc. have sprung up to help
consumers get their heads back above water and keep them there.
   The New York budget-counseling office is one of more than 400
offices nationwide affiliated with the non-profit Maryland-based
National Foundation for Consumer Credit.
   The need for such services probably has intensified in recent
years, due to the legacy of the self-indulgent 1970s Me Decade. In
the 1980s, a period of prolonged economic growth has put money into
people's pockets while the you-can-have-it-all yuppie attitude has
meant money did not burn many holes there.
   ``In our societies w're terribly materialistic _ especially in
America,'' Kress says. ``We believe there's a God-given right to
acquire, to be capitalistic. It's almost a holy thing.''
   Hapworth's compulsive spending treatment program is one of
several that the medical and psychiatric facility provides. It also
runs specialized programs for people addicted to alcohol, drugs and
tobacco and people with eating disorders. In addition to addicts,
it treats patients seeking help with sexual dysfunctions, stress,
depression and other problems.
   A 90-minute behavior evaluation costs $150 and Hapworth charges
$90 for a private behavior therapy session and $50 for group
therapy. The center says most insurance companies cover its
compulsive spending addiction program.
   Besides helping patients stick to a budget and break the
credit-card habit, Hapworth seeks to get to the root of their
problems. Sometimes the sense of loss associated with giving up
another habit, such as smoking, drinking or drug use, leads
troubled people to seek solace in shopping.
   In simple terms, a woman fixated on belts might be
subconsciously seeking to restrain herself. A man who cannot do
without the latest high-tech sports gadgetry might be trying to buy
youth or a good body in compensation for some perceived failing.
   Typically, compulsive spending addicts plan sprees with great
longing and go into almost hypnotic trances or feel out of control
while shopping, Kress says.
   To control spending while being treated for the addiction,
Hapworth has numerous do's and don't's for patients such as:
   _Never shop alone.
   _Never use credit cards.
   _Always use cash if possible.
   _Stick to shopping lists.
   _Don't keep purchases a secret.
   _Return or give to charity any duplicate items you own.
   The addiction affects rich and poor, but wealthy people do not
wind up in financial difficulty unless they really go overboard.
   Both women and men suffer from uncontrollable spending urges
contrary to the TV sitcom stereotype of the dizzy female going
ga-ga over sales.
   ``We're trying to point out that this is not something
frivolous. It's a serious problem that no one takes seriously,''
Kress says.
   But not everyone should automatically feel guilty about shopping.
   ``I'm not anti-materialism; it's fine to like beautiful
things,'' Kress says. ``When you use it to avoid your feelings
that's when it becomes a problem.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 1</NOTE>
