<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 1331EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--GreyhoundResearch Adv02   09-28 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Greyhound Research, Adv 02,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, Oct. 2, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Greyhound Research Lab Seeks To Get Injured Dogs Back On Track</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A quarter-mile oval track nestled among
the towering oaks will let researchers study the stresses of racing
and the peak performance of a breed of highly trained athletes _
racing greyhounds.
   The $300,000, year-old track is ``the only one of its kind at an
academic institution built purely for research,'' said Dr. Mark
Bloomberg, director of the University of Florida's Center for
Veterinary Sports Medicine.
   The track, financed by the Florida Division of the American
Greyhound Track Operators, also lets veterinarians treat dogs that
are injured or have problems racing, he said. ``The idea is to get
them back winning. Some of these dogs are very valuable. It will be
an environment for diagnosis and prognosis.''
   Projects by students and 20 faculty members include research
into the incidence and characteristics of injuries, hypothyroidism,
changes in fluid in the joints, and exercise-induced bleeding. The
injury study involves a survey of racing greyhound injuries that
occur in training and on commercial tracks.
   With the dogs hitting 40 mph in sprints, leg injuries are
common, Bloomberg said, and the track will be used ``to evaluate
dogs with orthopedic injuries. We want to really get into is the
bio-mechanics of the race track itself.''
   Composition of the track surface, banking and other factors will
be examined, he said. ``We want to provide a safe running surface
that decreases the rate of injuries and prolong racing careers,''
he said.
   Most tracks use a mixture of sand and clay, though others have
been tried.
   Researchers also are examining greyhound reproduction. Racing
females are are given male hormones to disturb their fertility
cycle. When their careers end, it can take 18 months or more before
they return to full fertility.
   Another study examines whether racing dogs have the same
problems as race horses that bleed into their lungs, and whether
this affects performance.
   The spread of infectious disease through a kennel is another
concern of the industry, Bloomberg said.
   Greyhound pups begin training when they are 16 months to 2 years
old and most run until they are about 5. Some kennels, with
excellent breeding stock, may race 90 percent of their dogs, while
others have only 25 percent to 50 percent of their dogs heading for
the track.
   Greyhounds run instinctively, he said, and the training ``is
designed to teach them to chase the lure.'' The training also gets
the dog into shape and ``good training even helps the average dog.''
   Racing dogs are, in many ways, like human athletes, he said, and
some will perform when injured, while others won't. ``The ones with
the most heart may beat the best athletes.''
   Bloomberg hopes the track will draw more researchers as more
states legalize racing. Texas and Kansas are each building three
tracks and Wisconsin is building five. Greyhound racing also is
popular in England, Ireland, France, Spain, Mexico, Australia and
the Scandinavian countries.
   In addition to the track operators, money comes from the
greyhound industry, private companies financing research and the
university's Division of Sponsored Research. Since its founding in
the 1940s, the greyhound industry in Florida has blossomed into the
largest in the country.
   In fiscal 1987, ``racing at Florida's 18 tracks raised $80
million in tax revenues for the state, compared to about $29
million for jai-alai, $12 million for thoroughbred horse racing and
$1.5 million for harness racing,'' said George Johnson, executive
director of the Florida group.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday, Oct. 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890928-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 1339EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--Briefs Adv02   09-28 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Briefs, Adv 02,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, Oct. 2, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Women, Whites at Greater Risk of Thyroid Disease</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women and whites are at greater risk of
thyroid disease than other groups, according to a study that found
nearly 9 percent of people over 55 suffer from some thyroid gland
dysfunction.
   In the Wayne State University study of 488 whites and 480
blacks, 8.9 percent suffered some thyroid dysfunction, said Dr.
Nanda Bagchi, a professor of medicine at the school. Two percent of
the total suffered hyperthoidism, or excessive thyroid function,
and 6.9 percent had hypothyroidism, too little.
   The thyroid, located in front and to each side of the trachea,
secretes thyroxine to regulate growth and metabolism.
Hyperthyroidism can cause weight loss, nervousness, rapid pulse and
muscle weakness. Hypothyroidism can cause sluggishness, puffiness,
constipation, depression, weight gain and hair loss.
   About half the cases of hypothyroidism were caused by underlying
autoimmune thyroid disease, a condition that causes the body to
react to the thyroid and diminishes its function, Bagchi said.
Two-thirds of the hyperthyroidism cases were attributable to too
much thyroid hormone prescribed by doctors, he said.
   Treatment of hyperthyroidism is particularly important among
older people because it can aggravate heart disease, he said.
Thyroid disease strikeds about 15 percent of people aged 75 and
over, about twice as often as those 55-64.
   The study, reported last month at a meeting of the American
Thyroid Association, also found that 12.7 percent of whites had
dysfunction, compared with 6.9 percent of blacks; and 11.2 percent
of women vs. 6.2 percent of men.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Study Finds Drug-Exposed Children Face Learning Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toddlers exposed to cocaine in the womb are
shorter, have smaller heads and are more likely to have learning
handicaps than children who have not been exposed, according to a
study on drugs and pregancy.
   ``We foresee that many of these children will end up in special
education, or classes for the learning disabled,'' said Dr. Ira
Chasnoff, the director of the Chicago-based study of 277 children,
including 228 exposed to drugs. Two-thirds of the mothers used
other drugs in addition to cocaine, he said.
   The problems include a lack of concentration and inability to
accomplish tasks easily performed by other children, concluded the
study released to the National Association for Perinatal Addiction
Research and Education.
   The association estimates that 375,000 babies are born each year
in the United States to mothers who used drugs during their
pregnancy.
   A Boston University study earlier this year found similar
results on stature and head size. Chasnoff said, `This has a lot of
implications for long-term development'' since head circumference
is an indication of brain growth.
   ``These children, on the whole, are not mentally retarded.
Overall, these babies cognitively and functioning normally,'' he
said. The tendency to become distracted and troubled by
unstructured tasks holds back the exposed children.
   On tests calling for blocks to be put in appropriate-shaped
holes, drug-exposed children were more likely to become confused
and overwhelmed.
   ``What I hear teachers telling me are the same things I'm
telling you right here,'' Chasnoff said at an association
conference last month. ``The teachers are calling this to the
attention of the school systems, but the school systems are not
ready to deal with it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday, Oct. 2</NOTE>
