<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 0303EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-IMF-Argentina     09-28 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-IMF-Argentina,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Accord on Loan to Argentina</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Argentina has reached agreement with the
International Monetary Fund for a $1.4 billion loan to help the
government cope with the country's financial troubles, President
Carlos Menem and the IMF said.
   Argentina owes nearly $4.5 billion in unpaid interest on $60
billion worth of foreign debt. It has been paying little for the
last year and a half. The country is the Third World's third
largest debtor, after Brazil and Mexico.
   Menem, speaking Wednesday at the National Press Club, did not
divulge details of the agreement reached during the annual meeting
of the IMF and its sister group, the World Bank.
   He said Argentina wants to honor its debt commitments but added
that the country's creditors should take into account Argentina's
needs, including its struggle to achieve economic growth.
   Argentina, he said, is facing ``the most dangerous economic
crisis in our history'' because of recession, hyperinflation,
disinvestment and debt.
   Menem's predecessor, Raul Alfonsin, was unable to make the
promises that the fund requires in return for help _ cuts in
government spending and other austerity measures that could have
led to serious disturbances.
   Last February in Venezuela an estimated 300 people were killed
in rioting when a new government took measures in agreement with
the fund that raised prices for gasoline, bus fares and other vital
products.
   It takes several weeks or months before money from an IMF loan
is actually disbursed. It was widely expected that soon after an
agreement was reached between the fund and Argentina, a bridge loan
from the United States and other countries would be granted to help
tide Argentina over.
   Argentine negotiators met Wednesday with Richard Erb, the fund's
deputy managing director, and representatives of leading countries
among the 152 in the fund. The United States is the largest
contributor.
   Last October, Argentina got $1.25 billion in loans from the
World Bank. The bank suspended much of its disbursement when
Argentina failed to meet its conditions.
   Officials estimated that Argentina only received about $300
million of the money.
</TEXT>
