<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 0304EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Pepsi-Restructuring     09-28 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pepsi-Restructuring,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pepsi-Cola International Announces Restructuring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pepsico Inc.'s foreign beverage operations are
being realigned into six new units carved out along geographic
lines in an attempt to expand Pepsi's international soft drink
business, the company said.
   Roger Enrico, president and chief executive of the company's
Pepsico Worldwide Beverages division, on Wednesday named presidents
of each of the six units, which he said would be self-sufficient
with broad local authority in areas such as marketing, sales and
technical operations.
   Christopher A. Sinclair, a veteran Pepsico executive who most
recently had headed the central division of Pepsi-Cola USA with
responsibility for 11 Midwest states, was named president of
Pepsi-Cola International.
   Previously, the foreign operations were divided into 15 regions
that reported to four middle-managers based in Somers, N.Y. Under
the new foreign alignment, the regional presidents report directly
to Sinclair in Somers.
   Enrico had headed Pepsi-Cola International as well as handling
his worldwide posts since February, when Robert Beeby left to head
Pepsico's Frito-Lay Inc. snack food subsidiary.
   Beverage industry analysts said the realignment reflects the
importance Pepsi is placing on the international beverage
marketplace where it long has trailed Coca-Cola Co. by a wide
margin.
   Many industry observers say soft drink makers view the
international market as offering the most promising opportunity for
growth.
   Industry analysts said Pepsi derives slightly less than 50
percent of its soft-drink volume from international sales, or about
2 billion of its 4.2 billion cases sold worldwide annually. But
international sales account for only about 20 percent of the
company's $5 billion in worldwide revenue.
   Jesse Meyers, publisher of the industry journal Beverage Digest,
said foreign markets are appealing to soft drink makers because
average per capita consumption of soft drinks is only a fraction of
what it is in the United States, affording greater growth
opportunities.
   Pepsi-Cola International said the realignment will place some of
its ``most seasoned international executives on the front lines of
the international soft drink market.''
   The six foreign regions, the presidents and base of operations
are: Western Europe, Frederick Meils, London; Latin America, Luis
Suarez, Rio de Janeiro; Middle East-Africa, David Jones, Nicosia,
Cyprus; Asia Pacific, Richard Blossom, Singapore; China-India-West
Asia-Eastern Europe, Les Ham, Hong Kong; and Canada, Wayne
Mailloux, Toronto.
</TEXT>
