<FIRST>r f PM-GeneralDynamicsChief     09-28 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-General Dynamics Chief,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Successor Appointed for General Dynamics Chief</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: National Aeronautics and Space Council in 5th graf is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Dynamics Corp. announced that William
A. Anders, a high-ranking Textron Inc. executive, will replace
Stanley C. Pace as chairman and chief executive of the defense
contractor.
   Anders is senior executive vice president of operations and a
director of Textron, which has interests in aerospace technology,
commercial products, including automotive components, and financial
services.
   He will join General Dynamics on Jan. 1 as vice chairman and
will become chairman and chief executive when Pace retires Jan. 1,
1991, the St. Louis-based company said Wednesday.
   Pace has been chief executive since 1986.
   Anders, 55, is a former executive secretary of the National
Aeronautics and Space Council, commissioner of the Atomic Energy
Commission and chairman of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission. Prior
to joining Textron in 1984, he was with General Electric Co.
   Anders also is a former astronaut with NASA's manned spacecraft
program. He was one of three crew members aboard the 1968 Apollo 8
lunar mission and served as a backup pilot for Apollo 11, the first
lunar landing.
   Pace, who had previously announced his intention to retire at
the end of next year, said Anders' military, government and
industry background ``represents an ideal fit with the company's
management style and philosophies and many of its key government
production programs.''
</TEXT>
