<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 0242EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Columbia-HollywoodReax Bjt   09-28 0779</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Columbia-Hollywood Reax, Bjt,0806</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sony Purchase Should Stabilize Columbia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Betting lines on the effects of Sony Corp.'s
$3.4 billion buyout of Columbia Pictures Entertainment Inc. emerged
quickly, with the deal evaluated as:
   _Bearish for present Columbia management, with Chief Executive
Victor Kaufman probably to be replaced by producer Peter Guber
(``Batman,'' ``Rain Man,'' ``Flashdance''), and studio chief Dawn
Steel's future uncertain.
   _Bullish for struggling Columbia, with Sony likely to bring
stability to a studio beset by shifting management strategies and
persistent rumors that controlling shareholder Coca-Cola Co. was
shopping for a buyer.
   _Bearish for the U.S. economy, as profits from yet another
all-American business go abroad.
   _But bullish for producers of movies, TV shows and recordings,
who sell to the entertainment giants that feed the world's
insatiable appetite for U.S. entertainment.
   Many in Hollywood were uneasy about Sony's purchase, the latest
and largest in a string of foreign investments in show business.
   ``The Japanese are buying up a vital American institution,
something that no one else in the world can do as well as we can,''
said an independent movie producer who insisted on anonymity
because he hopes to do business with the Columbia and Tri-Star
studios, both owned by Columbia Pictures.
   ``There just aren't that many people that know the music
business and the movie business, and you have to count on them to
run things.
   ``They're characters. They're flakes. And they're essential to
the business. ... I'm sure there must be a kind of culture shock to
the Japanese,'' the producer said.
   However, Alex Ben Block, editor in chief of Show Biz News, said
foreign investment, or at least ownership by internationally
oriented businesses, is inevitable. Only ``global mega-studios''
with multiple businesses can take full advantage of the booming
worldwide demand for U.S. entertainment, he said.
   Added Dale Pollock, vice president in charge of production at
A&amp;M Films, ``We're entering a new era of communications.
   ``It's global and it's not just studios,'' said Pollock, noting
that his company's parent, A&amp;M Records, is being bought by
Dutch-owned Polygram for $500 million.
   Another key example of the internationalizing of Hollywood:
media baron Rupert Murdoch, whose Australia-based News Corp. owns
20th Century Fox Film Corp.
   Murdoch's Fox TV network here and fledgling four-channel British
satellite TV network needs programming. He was outbid this month
for MGM-UA _ which like Columbia has a huge library of movies and
TV shows _ by another Australian outfit, Qintex Group.
   In researching a book on Fox, Block talked to Murdoch, who
``made it clear that strong, American-made programming opens doors
all over the world,'' Block said.
   ``It leads to advertising, joint ventures, a multitude of ways
to do business, and it all comes back to the American creative
force.''
   The big Hollywood outfits need legions of small companies to
feed them movies, television shows and recordings _ a boon for
Hollywood's creative forces.
   The deals bode well for moviegoers, Block said.
   ``It's going to stabilize these big companies, they're going to
make more movies and there will be that much more to choose from,''
Block said.
   But, he added, ``It's distressing to see this industry, one of
the last of the big purely American industries, be so bought up.''
   Block said he expected Sony to follow Japanese business practice
by asking trusted executives at CBS Records, which Sony bought two
years ago, and perhaps at SVS Films, a small movie company Sony
recently started, to help manage Columbia.
   The Columbia studio has swung from one end of the movie-making
spectrum to the other in recent years.
   High-toned British producer David Puttnam (``Chariots of Fire,''
``The Killing Fields'') ran it for 18 months but alienated such
Hollywood stalwarts as producer Ray Stark. Puttnam was replaced two
years ago by Dawn Steel, regarded as much more in the Hollywood
mainstream. But the studio's recent movies have had a mixed
showing, although its production of TV shows for the networks has
been very strong.
   Regardless of the makeup of Sony's management team for Columbia,
most observers believed that once set, it will remain in place for
a long time.
   Sony bought prestigious CBS Records in late 1987 for about $2
billion, and since has taken a hands-off approach, letting Walter
Yetnikoff run the nation's second-largest record company his way.
   CBS' artists, who include Michael Jackson and Bruce Springsteen,
don't seem to have minded Sony's ownership.
   ``I haven't really seen any major changes since the whole Sony
thing,'' said record producer Narada Walden, speaking in a
telephone interview from Kalamazoo, Mich. Walden has produced
records for Whitney Houston, Barbra Streisand and comedian Eddie
Murphy. ``They're very trusting.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890928-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 0241EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Columbia-Analysis Bjt   09-28 0758</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Columbia-Analysis, Bjt,0787</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sony Will Control All Aspects of Movie Business</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unlike any company before, Sony Corp. will
control every aspect of the motion-picture business with its
purchase of Columbia Pictures Entertainment Inc.
   Sony will own or produce the movie, the movie theater, the snack
bar, the soundtrack album, the television series adaptation, and
the VCR and stereo system on which the videocassette and album can
be played.
   In addition to yielding this fully integrated entertainment
power, Wednesday's Sony-Columbia deal will give the Japanese
electronics giant a repository of films and television programs to
show the world over.
   While not in the same league as the $14 billion Time-Warner
merger earlier this year, the $3.4 billion Sony-Columbia pact does
share the same motivation: survival in the booming international
entertainment emporium.
   ``We're entering a new era of communications,'' said Dale
Pollock, vice president in charge of production at A&amp;M Films.
   ``It's global and it's not just studios,'' said Pollock, noting
that his company's parent firm, A&amp;M Records, is being bought by
Dutch-owned Polygram for $500 million.
   Sony's new multinational enterprise follows a yearlong effort to
establish a Hollywood foothold.
   It will wed Sony's dominance in stereo, television set and tape
player manufacturing with Columbia's proficiency in movie and TV
production and motion-picture distribution and exhibition.
   More important, Sony will have the supply to meet international
demand. Entertainment is the United States' second-leading export,
accounting for a net trade surplus of about $5 billion. In the past
four years, overseas revenues from U.S. films have risen to $1.13
billion from $800 million.
   ``Fatal Attraction,'' for instance, recovered all of its
production costs in Japanese theaters alone. French channel TF1
recently paid $11 million for 200 episodes of ``Knots Landing.''
   With the coming deregulation of most of European television and
increasing sales of prerecorded videocassettes overseas, the
equation should continue to shift in favor of U.S. products.
   Columbia has a library of 2,770 feature films and 23,000
episodes of 260 television series.
   Movies in Columbia's collection include ``The Last Emperor,''
``Gandhi,'' ``Kramer vs. Kramer'' and ``The Natural.'' Sony also
will take over Loews Theater Management Corp., with more than 820
screens in 220 locations and a national theater snack bar operation.
   The marriage between Sony and Columbia resembles Sony's
acquisition of CBS Records. Sony purchased CBS Records _ home label
to Michael Jackson and Bruce Springsteen _ for about $2 billion in
late 1987, and let label head Walter Yetnikoff continue to run the
company the way he wanted. The label continues to be dominant.
   Early speculation, though, holds that Columbia studio chief Dawn
Steel will not remain at the helm.
   For Coca-Cola Co., Columbia's controlling stockholder for the
last seven years, the studio never proved to be the revenue center
the soft-drink giant hoped it would be. In the current movie
season, 28 movies from Columbia and its sister company, Tri-Star,
have accounted for only 14 percent of all admissions sold.
   Paramount Pictures, on the other hand, claimed 14.6 percent of
the box-office gate with just 10 titles.
   Tri-Star's ``Lock Up,'' Sylvester Stallone's new prison movie,
was a dud, grossing only $20.7 million in its first 52 days of
release. Columbia's ``The Karate Kid Part III'' made only $38.8
million, far less than its two predecessors.
   ``Casualties of War,'' Columbia's Vietnam film featuring Michael
J. Fox and Sean Penn, probably won't cover its $25 million cost at
the nation's theaters. The romantic comedy ``When Harry Met Sally
... '' was perhaps Columbia's most profitable title this year,
grossing more than $78 million through Tuesday.
   But as weakly as Columbia performed under Steel's leadership,
its fortunes have improved sharply from David Puttnam's reign of
error.
   Puttnam, the producer of such acclaimed films as ``Chariots of
Fire'' and ``The Killing Fields,'' was appointed president of
Columbia Pictures in the fall of 1986. His film slate was marked by
ambitious yet ultimately unpopular fare such as ``The Adventures of
Baron Munchausen,'' ``Housekeeping'' and ``Punchline.''
   In acquiring Columbia, Sony is following a path taken by other
overseas companies in recent months.
   MGM-UA, maker of last year's Oscar-winning ``Rain Man,'' is
being sold to a subsidiary of Australian entertainment company
Qintex Group for $15 billion. Australian-based News Corp. already
owns 20th Century Fox.
   Just weeks ago, Japanese hardware mammoth JVC teamed with
producer Larry Gordon (``Die Hard,'' ``Field of Dreams'') in a $100
million movie production joint venture.
  
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Editors' Note: John Horn has reported on the entertainment
industry since 1984.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
