<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 0325EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CommodityComputers     09-28 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commodity Computers,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Comex To Test Hand-Held Computer Terminals for Traders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commodity Exchange says it will test
hand-held, tamper-proof computer terminals for traders by early
next year, getting a jump on the Chicago futures exchanges.
   Floor traders in the pits will enter orders on the terminals
instead of on paper cards, making it all but impossible to change a
recorded transaction to conceal fraud, Comex said Wednesday.
   Federal investigations of allegations of fraud have resulted in
indictments on the Chicago exchanges. A separate probe is on
commodity exchange trading floors in both Chicago and New York. The
fraud supposedly involved brokers changing the size or time of a
trade on their cards to disguise wrongdoing.
   Chicago's two big exchanges, the Chicago Board of Trade and
Chicago Mercantile Exchange, are ``still in the talking stage'' on
their hand-held terminals, CBOT spokesman Mark Prout said.
   ``We'll be very interested to see what the Comex comes up with
and how it works,'' Prout said.
   The Commodity Exchange said it began planning the computer
system four years ago, well before the recent fraud allegations.
Spokesman Robert McGrath said he could not say when the system
would go into operation because it would depend on how the testing
goes.
   ``Hopefully the results of this project will be an important
step toward helping Comex to fully meet the proposed, new
regulatory mandates of the CFTC (Commodity Futures Trading
Commission) and the U.S. Congress,'' Commodity Exchange Chairman
Robert Fink said in a statement.
   The Commodity Exchange, which trades gold, silver, copper and
aluminum futures contracts, is one of five futures exchanges that
share space in the World Trade Center in New York.
   McGrath said the other exchanges have not committed to adopting
the system, but added, ``There is some excitement about cooperating
and looking into the technology.''
   The other exchanges are the Coffee, Sugar and Cocoa Exchange,
the New York Cotton Exchange, the New York Futures Exchange and the
New York Mercantile Exchange.
   The computer terminals, costing $2,000 to $3,000 each, will
weigh less than a pound and will be supplied by AGS Information
Services Inc., a unit of NYNEX Corp.
   At first trades will be recorded on tiny disks that will be
collected periodically by runners. Eventually the terminals
probably will be equipped with radio transmitters, AGS official Don
Rosen said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
