<DOCNO> AP890928-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 0044EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0329 09-28 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0329,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Share Prices Bounce Back</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with morning Nikkei, comments.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar remained lower against the Japanese
yen Thursday morning, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange bounced back from the previous day's losses.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average regained 192.72 points, or
0.54 percent, ending morning trading at 35,563.29, the highest
morning closing ever. It had lost 74.25 points Wednesday.
   The dollar ended the morning session at 140.83 yen. It opened at
140.70 yen, down 0.65 yen from Wednesday's 141.35-yen close, and
moved in the range of 140.65 to 141.00 yen.
   The dollar's lower opening followed its overnight decline on
overseas markets, triggered by central bank intervention for the
third consecutive day to push the U.S. currency down, traders said.
   Toru Kanai, foreign currency analyst with New Japan Securities
Co. Ltd., said the dollar-yen rate was moving closely around 140.70
yen in Tokyo as market players were discouraged by the Bank of
Japan's dollar-selling intervention.
   Following the Group of Seven industrial nations' agreement on
coordinated intervention last weekend in Washington to halt the
dollar's rise, the Japanese central bank has intermittently
conducted dollar-selling operations since Monday, he said.
   The Bank of Japan sold the dollar Thursday immediately after the
dollar exceeded 140.80 yen, and again sold more dollars when it
almost touched 141.00 yen, Kanai said.
   The amount of selling was unknown. The central bank does not
comment on its monetary actions.
   ``The only thing that keeps the dollar lower now is the closely
coordinated central bank intervention after the G-7 meeting,'' he
said.
   When the central banks loosen their intervention, the dollar
might rise back, but not as high as the level before the G-7
agreement, he said.
   On the stock exchange, dealers said the index rebounded as
market players were reassured by the stability in the dollar-yen
rate.
   Investment trust companies, which had been reluctant to make
major moves while the dollar's fluctuations were uncertain, started
buying, encouraging other market players' to increase their own
purchasing, they said.
</TEXT>
