<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 0336EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Bilzerian     09-28 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bilzerian,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Singer Chairman Gets Longest Term in Fraud Crackdown</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former corporate raider Paul A. Bilzerian
received the stiffest sentence yet in the government's three-year
corruption probe but a federal judge said it won't necessarily
deter other financial crimes.
   ``I have been around the criminal justice system for 40 years,''
U.S. District Judge Robert J. Ward said Wednesday before sentencing
Bilzerian to four years in jail and a $1.5 million fine.
   ``When I began my experience there were wheeler-dealers,'' he
said. ``As I sit here today I am fairly certain there is
wheeler-dealering going on within five miles of this building.''
   Bilzerian, a high-school dropout and Vietnam veteran who capped
a meteoric business career with the $1.06 billion takeover of
Singer Co., was convicted June 9 on nine counts of securities
fraud, conspiracy to commit tax fraud and making false statements
to the government.
   He also was sentenced to two years probation and 250 hours of
community service for a pattern of lawbreaking in three failed
takeovers and another stock deal in 1985 and 1986 that netted him
more than $12 million.
   Bilzerian had faced a maximum 45 years in prison and $2.25
million in fines. Still, his sentence was the longest to date in
cases derived from the confessions of jailed stock speculator Ivan
Boesky, who is serving a three-year term.
   ``The lure of money has caused him _ an intelligent young man _
to lose what I perceive to be proper perspective,'' Ward said. ``In
short, he lies.''
   The charges involved raids on apparel maker Cluett, Peabody &amp;
Co., building supplies maker H.H. Robertson &amp; Co. and Hammermill
Paper Co., and another transaction of Armco Inc. stock.
   Bilzerian plans to appeal, said his attorney, Arthur F. Mathews.
   ``My trial and conviction has publicly humiliated me and I am
sorry for any sorrow and shame I have caused my family and
friends,'' Bilzerian stated in a pre-sentencing letter to Ward. ``I
wish I could turn back the clock of time and correct whatever
mistakes I may have made.''
   Bilzerian was freed on bail pending appeal but Ward ordered
Bilzerian, who in July reported a net worth of $81.4 million, to
pay the fines within 30 days.
   None of the charges against Bilzerian involved his 1988 takeover
of Singer, the sewing-machine maker turned defense contractor.
   The Bilzerian conviction was the first jury verdict in the
government's continuing white-collar corruption probe, which began
with the May 1986 arrest of former trader Dennis Levine, who led
investigators to Boesky.
   Bilzerian was convicted of submitting false documents to the
Securities and Exchange Commission, filing false tax returns and
rigging transactions to skirt federal tax and disclosure laws in
tandem with Los Angeles stockbroker Boyd L. Jefferies, who
testified against Bilzerian.
   Jefferies, who testified against Bilzerian, recently received a
suspended sentence. Sentencing is pending for others, including six
former Princeton-Newport Partners LP defendants found guilty of
fraud and racketeering and former Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
managing director Martin A. Siegel.
   Bilzerian, who resigned as Singer chairman in June, still faces
civil securities charges filed by the SEC seeking $31.3 million in
alleged illegal profits.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney David Brodsky cited Bilzerian's alleged
``arrogance and utter disregard for the law,'' said Bilzerian
committed perjury during the trial and said a lengthy prison term
would deter similar behavior on Wall Street.
   The case was the first criminal trial of illegal stock
``parking,'' in which securities ownership is disguised to dodge
federal tax or disclosure laws.
   ``Over an 18-month period Bilzerian committed serious securities
crimes over and over again,'' Brodsky said.
   Mathews sought a suspended sentence on the grounds that
Bilzerian was a first-time offender, that his prosecution was a
``novelty,'' that his crimes had no identifiable victims and that
deterrence had been achieved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890928-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 0317EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-HyattJobSwitch Bjt   09-28 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hyatt Job Switch, Bjt,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hotel Executives Learn How Their Employees Work</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Laserphoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The newest doorman at the Hyatt Regency Chicago
hotel appeared impressed with his job as he emptied a wad of
rumpled dollar bills from his uniform pocket.
   ``See, they even tip me,'' said the doorman, Darryl
Hartley-Leonard, president of Hyatt Hotel Corp.
   After his stint Wednesday at the front door, Hartley-Leonard was
headed to the check-in desk for a few hours, then an evening shift
as a bartender. It was all part of a program called ``Hyatt
in-Touch Day,'' under which 400 of the hotel chain's executives and
managers took service-level jobs for a day.
   Even Hyatt Corp. Chairman Thomas J. Pritzker, of the Chicago
family that owns the chain, did his bit, serving as a bellhop at
the Grand Hyatt Hotel in Washington, D.C.
   ``It's an attempt to stay in touch with the customers and the
line employees,'' said Hartley-Leonard, who intends to make the job
switch a yearly event.
   Wednesday was chosen because it was the 32nd anniversary of the
company's founding, he said.
   ``I started working for Hyatt 26 years ago as a desk clerk in
one of the California hotels, and I worked on the `line' until 11
years ago, when I had a chance to take a management job,'' said
Hartley-Leonard, 45. ``I only realized recently that of the 426
executives and employees in our corporate headquarters, 340 had
never actually worked in a hotel.
   ``By doing service jobs for a day, maybe they'll understand a
bit more what service means,'' he said.
   The experiment meant sending computer experts out as
chambermaids and business analysts as busboys.
   At the Hyatt Regency Chicago, General Manager Rod Young was busy
just keeping track of where each of his new employees was.
   One of them, Jim Evans, senior vice president for sales, was
assisting Roosevelt Moncure, a convention services floor manager,
who was teaching him how to ``turn'' a banquet room.
   ``This is one of more than 60 banquet rooms in this hotel, and
they're all booked full this week,'' Moncure said. ``We just had it
set `theater-style' for 150 people, and now we're cleaning it out
and setting it `conference style' for 20 people. We've got to have
it ready by 6:30 p.m., and if the guests tell us they're bringing
in 10 more people, we've got to be ready for them.''
   ``I'm learning how to set up tables,'' said Evans. ``I haven't
done this sort of work for 19 years, and then it was for another
chain. Normally, I'd be selling this space to convention groups and
just conferring with Moncure and his people once a week to discuss
the schedule.''
   Despite any slowdowns the managers-in-training may have caused
in the line jobs, the ``Hyatt in-Touch'' day appeared to be good
for customer relations. Outside the hotel, Hartley-Leonard grinned
as he told of one early-morning encounter with a guest.
   ``She looked at my name tag and said, `No, you're not,' but I
told her, `Oh, yes I am,''' he said. ``Another lady, who knew what
was going on, told her friend, `See what a good company does? My
boss would never do this.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
