<FIRST>u f PM-Columbia-Guber 1stLd-Writethru   09-28 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Columbia-Guber, 1st Ld-Writethru,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guber Rumored Sony's Pick For Top Columbia Post</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Grafs 4-5 NEW to UPDATE with Guber-Peters sale. Picks up 4th
graf pvs: Guber and...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Producer Peter Guber, whose productions have
included such megahits as ``Batman'' and ``Rain Man,'' is
reportedly considering running Columbia Pictures Entertainment for
new owner Sony Corp.
   Victor Kaufman, Columbia's president and chief executive, has
said he intends to resign when Sony completes its $3.4 billion
buyout of the company.
   Guber, who was in New York, where Columbia is headquartered, was
unavailable for comment. Andrea Jaffe, a spokeswoman representing
the Guber-Peters Entertainment Co., declined comment on the rumor.
   In a development early today, Guber-Peters announced that it had
accepted a proposal from Sony USA Inc. to acquire the movie company
for $17.50 a share, or about $200 million.
   The deal is expected to be completed before the end of 1989, the
company said in a statement. Under terms of the agreement, Sony
will begin a tender offer next week for all Guber-Peters shares,
which will be followed by a cash merger.
   Guber and his partner, former hairdresser Jon Peters, produced
the summer blockbuster, ``Batman,'' and were executive producers of
the Academy Award-winning ``Rain Man.''
   Guber has received high marks within the industry. ``He was very
smart about how to handle the movie,'' said Mark Johnson, the
producer of ``Rain Man.''
   Independent producer John Davis noted that ``the expertise to
run a studio is so specialized that they (Sony) pretty much have to
pick an insider and let go of the reins.''
   Guber, 47, attended New York University Law School and spent
seven years working for Columbia, including a two-year stint as
vice president of worldwide production.
   He left the company in 1976, joining record producer Neal Bogart
to form Casablanca Records and Filmworks. In 1980, Guber teamed up
with Peters to form PolyGram Pictures. PolyGram was sold in 1983,
the same year Guber-Peters Entertainment Co. was launched.
   Guber-Peters merged with Barris Industries, home of television's
``The Gong Show,'' two years ago.
   In the fiscal year ended May 31, Guber-Peters lost $19.2 million
on revenues of $23.7 million. The company has yet to realize any
profits from either ``Rain Man'' or ``Batman.''
   In addition to their reputation as topflight producers, Guber
and Peters also own the television shows ``The Dating Game,'' ``The
Gong Show'' and ``The Newlywed Game.''
   They are best known, however, for their smash ``Batman.'' So far
the Warner Bros. film, starring Michael Keaton in the title role
and Jack Nicholson as The Joker, has collected $244.7 million,
making it the fifth most successful film in Hollywood history.
Including all ancillary markets and merchandise, ``Batman's'' total
take could exceed $1 billion.
   The producing team also succeeded in delivering last year's best
picture winner ``Rain Man,'' starring Dustin Hoffman as an autistic
adult on the road with his scheming brother, Tom Cruise. The film
won four Oscars in all.
   Guber and Peters also produced ``Gorillas in the Mist,''
``Flashdance,'' ``The Color Purple,'' ``Missing,'' ``Midnight
Express,'' ``The Witches of Eastwick,'' ``Innerspace'' and
``Caddyshack II.''
   The producers' rumored move to Columbia could be complicated
severely by the team's recent renewal of a five-year deal with
Warner Bros.
   The pair had a number of films in development with Warner Bros.,
including a ``Batman'' sequel due in 1991, the film adaptation of
the books ``Bonfire of the Vanities'' and ``A Bright Shining Lie''
and the movies ``Contact'' and ``Damien.''
</TEXT>
