<FIRST>u f PM-Swissair-SAS 1stLd-Writethru f0013 09-28 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Swissair-SAS, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0013,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swissair, SAS Agree to Cooperation Pact</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with cooperation agreement, details;
PICKS UP 7th graf pvs, `SAS, the...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swissair and Scandinavian Airlines
System today agreed to to acquire up to 10 percent of each other
and unify some traffic routes and travel services.
   The cooperation agreement focuses on the airlies' service to
Europe, Africa and the Middle East, and is similar to a joint pact
between Swissair and Delta Air Lines signed earlier this year.
   The airlines said in a statement released in Zurich that the
they will complete acquisition of between 5 percent and 10 percent
of each other during 1990. In addition, the airlines said may
exchange seats on their boards of directors.
   Zurich-based Swissair and Stockholm, Sweden-based SAS said the
deal was undertaken to strengthen the airlines' European market
base and provide more efficient intercontinental services for the
1990s.
   The SAS-Swissair agreement also will cover travel products,
hotels, inflight catering and restaurant operations, aircraft
maintenance, fleet planning and other services, the statement said.
   ``We share the same customer-oriented marketing philosophy, and
both attach great importance to a quality product,'' Swissair
President Otto Loepfe said in the statement.
   Atlanta-based Delta, fearing it could be a takeover target,
agreed in July to sell a 5 percent share to Swissair as a defensive
move. Delta also took a 5 percent stake in the Swiss carrier. The
two also have a marketing agreement, signed earlier.
   SAS and Swissair said they will feed traffic into each other's
routes to and from the Middle East, Africa and the Indian
subcontinent. They also said they will increase service between
Switzerland and Scandinavia.
   SAS, the first foreign airline to buy a stake in a major U.S.
carrier, signed a $50 million cooperation agreement with Texas Air
Corp. last October and holds 9.9 percent of the Houston-based
company. SAS recently was in talks to buy a stake in struggling
Continental Airlines, one of Texas Air's main subsidiaries, but
later said it had no immediate interest.
   European airlines have been seeking ways of positioning
themselves to exploit the Common Market deregulation set to begin
in 1992.
   Air France and Lufthansa German Airlines signed an accord on
Sept. 15 calling for cooperation in marketing, maintenance,
scheduling and cargo. Lufthansa also has disclosed that it has held
talks with AMR Corp., parent of American Airlines, about a possible
stake in American's Sabre computer reservations system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
