<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   09-28 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybeans Gain On Signs Of Foreign Demand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures were slightly higher,
reflecting signs of stronger foreign demand, while wheat futures
slipped a bit early in today's session on the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   Support for the markets stemmed from talk of possible new export
business with Pakistan, Mexico and the Soviet Union after several
weeks of slow export activity.
   Especially supportive were rumors that the Soviet Union was
looking to buy up to 3 million metric tons of U.S. corn or sorghum,
and signs that the Soviets recently purchased grain from Canada and
soybean meal from South America.
   The Soviets had indicated earlier this month they would import
no more grain this year.
   ``What this is telling the market is that all the rhetoric about
them not buying is just purely rhetoric, that they are in to buy
and it's just a matter of terms,'' said William Biedermann,
director of research with Allendale Inc., a futures brokerage in
Crystal Lake, Ill.
   Early losses in the wheat market may have reflected
position-evening by traders ahead of this afternoon's quarterly
Agriculture Department report on U.S. grain stocks.
   In early trading, wheat futures were } cent to 1} cents lower
with the contract for delivery in December at $3.97\ a bushel; corn
was } cent to 1{ cents higher with December at $2.30\ a bushel;
oats were } cent to 1{ cents higher with December at $1.45\ a
bushel; soybeans were 2\ cents to 3} cents higher with November at
$5.68 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were lower while pork futures were mixed in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .02 cent to .25 cent lower with October at
71.85 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .27 cent lower
with September at 83 cents a pound; live hogs were .15 cent lower
to .05 cent higher with October at 43.25 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were unchanged to .13 cent higher with February at 48.27
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
