<DOCNO> AP890928-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 1207EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-US-Europe'92     09-28 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Europe '92,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Europeans Asked to Drop Any Restrictions Against U.S. Financial Institutions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Community must drop possible
restrictions against nonmember financial institutions as it plans
for economic and monetary union by 1992 or risk provoking
retaliation from the United States, a U.S. official said today.
   ``We still see dangers in the EC concept of reciprocity''
despite European assurances and improvements in the proposed
reciprocity provisions, Treasury Undersecretary David C. Mulford
said in testimony prepared for a House Banking financial
institutions subcommittee.
   The 12-nation European Economic Community hopes by 1992 to
remove internal trade barriers and interlock economic policies and
goals. The United States and other non-European nations are
concerned that the program could create a protectionist ``Fortress
Europe'' against nonmember goods and services.
   ``EC proposals for reciprocity in financial services continue to
concern us,'' Mulford said, `` ... because access to the EC market
will still be conditional on the treatment of EC firms in
third-country markets.''
   ``Despite the softening of reciprocity, the implied threat
remains a potentially powerful instrument, which makes us uneasy,''
he said.
   ``Moreover, once this `club in the closet' is on the books,
there will be a temptation to use it, especially given the EC's
desire to promote changes in the U.S. financial system,'' Mulford
testified.
   ``If actually used _ or rather `misused' _ this would run the
risk of provoking a retaliation action from U.S. authorities ... If
U.S. firms are discriminated against in the EC, there would likely
be consequences for EC national institutions.''
   Mulford expressed confidence that U.S.-European differences can
be worked out.
   But, he said, ``officials come and go, and there are always
risks of misunderstandings. I ask the Europeans: Wouldn't it be
better to lay these reciprocity weapons aside?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
