<FIRST>r f PM-Cigna-Hugo     09-28 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cigna-Hugo,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cigna Takes Charge To Cover Hugo Losses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cigna Corp. said Thursday it will take a $90
million after-tax charge in the third-quarter to cover losses from
Hurricaine Hugo in Puerto Rico, the Virgin Islands and the
southeastern United States.
   Gavin R. Arton, Cigna vice president of financial relations,
said the insurance giang identified 75 percent of the losses as
commercial property _ including hotels, offices, shops and
industrial sites _ devastated by the tropical storm. The remaining
25 percent is damage to personal property, he said.
   The $90 million also includes an estimated $30 million for
reinsurance reinstatement charges, Arton said.
   ``We buy reinsurance in order to protect ourselves against this
happening again,'' he said.
   Cigna plans to report its results for the third quarter on Nov.
2.
   Officials have estimated the hurricane, which killed 28 people
on the U.S. mainland and 33 in the Caribbean, left as much as $3
billion in damage.
   Arton said Cigna agents conducted a week-long investigation at
the sites where the hurricance hit to assess the company's losses.
   ``There are parts of the Virgin Island that we haven't been able
to get to,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
