<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 1419EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-CapitalGains 3rdLd-Writethru   09-28 1005</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Capital Gains, 3rd Ld-Writethru,1033</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Defeats Democratic Tax Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: new thruout with reaction from Bush, congressional leaders;
edits to tighten; also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House today voted to support President
Bush's capital gains tax cut, rejecting Democratic cries that it
was a giveaway to the rich.
   Culminating weeks of political struggle, the House defeated by a
vote of 239 to 190 a Democratic attempt to replace Bush's tax cut
with a plan to raise tax rates for the wealthy and restore
deductions for Individual Retirement Accounts.
   The vote left intact a proposal supported by the president which
would cut by 40 percent the maximum tax rate for earnings from
stocks, bonds, real estate, timber and other assets. A final vote
on the overall bill, which contains many other unrelated budget
provisions and issues, isn't expected until next week.
   The capital gains reduction was supported by 175 Republicans and
64 Democrats and opposed by 189 Democrats and one Republican, Doug
Bereuter of Nebraska.
   Republicans and conservative Democrats who sided with the
president said the tax cut would be a tonic for the economy, and
they called the Democratic alternative a sign of a tax-and-spend
philosophy.
   ``I am very pleased by the bipartisan House vote which
represents a step forward for economic growth, new jobs and
American competitiveness,'' Bush said in a statement after the vote.
   ``A lower capital gains rate will reduce the cost of capital and
create incentives for investment in the long-term productive
capacity of American industry,'' the president said.
   Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., the minority whip, said the vote
showed the ``waning influence of the liberals in the Democratic
Party'' and predicted Bush would continue winning with the help of
Democratic conservatives.
   But House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., said he was ``proud
we took this position'' and said the Democratic schism on capital
gains was not something that extended to other issues.
   ``The Democratic leadership believes in redistributing the
wealth. The bipartisan coalition believes in creating wealth,''
said House Minority Leader Robert H. Michel, R-Ill. He decried the
``rancid rhetoric of class warfare'' being used against a proposal
which he said would mean ``more growth, more jobs, and help us all
be more competitive in an increasingly competitive world.''
   House Majority Leader Richard Gephardt argued that supporting
the Bush plan meant, ``You'll be voting to give $25,000 a year on
the average to ... the wealthiest families in America'' at a time
when the federal deficit was eroding the U.S. position in
international markets.
   The vote wasn't as close as both sides were predicting up until
the end. Although Republicans were confident they took steps to
make sure _ Rep. James Courter, R-N.J., was called by the White
House 8-10 times late Wednesday to make sure he took a break from
his gubernatorial campaign to vote.
   In advance of the vote, each side was accusing the other of
unseemly arm-twisting.
   ``We know there's just been unmerciful kind of pressure brought
to bear on the Democratic side against their members'' who were
inclined to side with Bush, Michel said.
   ``I suspect it (Michel's comment) is a suggestion made to
cover'' Republican tactics of that sort, countered Foley.
``Obviously, the president is using every means at his disposal,
including ... inducements to members of various unstated kinds.''
   With the president's blessing, the House Ways and Means
Committee put into the huge, 2,000-page budget bill a provision
cutting the maximum capital gains tax rate from 33 percent to 19.6
percent for the next 27 months. After that, the rate would go to 28
percent but profits attributed to inflation would not be taxed.
   Foley and the House Democratic leadership took a stand against
the tax break, citing statistics which show the overwhelming
majority of the benefits would go to people earning over $100,000 a
year.
   Their proposal included a tax increase for the wealthy,
increasing their marginal tax rates from 28 percent to 33 percent
so it would be the same as for upper-middle-class taxpayers. The
revenue would be used to cut the deficit and restore universal tax
deductions for Individual Retirement Accounts.
   The Democrats also included a small cut in the top capital gains
rate, from 33 percent to 28 percent.
   Although the tax increase would apply only to the 600,000
wealthiest taxpayers in the nation _ mostly people earning more
than $150,000 a year _ Bush threatened a veto and Republicans
gleefully attacked the Democratic plan.
   ``Tax, tax, tax, tax, tax, tax, tax, tax, tax, tax, tax, tax,
tax, tax, tax, tax... '' said Rep. Paul Henry, R-Mich., repeated
for a minute in a speech before the House on Wednesday.
   Foley said a Democratic loss in the House would not put Bush on
a sure track toward victory.
   ``The Senate leadership feels as strongly as our leadership
does, that this capital gains proposal is a detriment to the budget
process, unfair, and an inequitable proposal. Bad tax policy,''
Foley said.
   ``If we had more time, there's no question in my mind we'd be
winning big,'' said Rep. Vic Fazio, D-Calif., who helped Foley
lobby for the package.
   The capital gains provision is just one of many controversies on
the budget bill, and the House is expected to vote next week on
federally subsidized child care and the catastrophic illness
insurance plan.
   On the catastrophic illness issue, the House will choose between
restructuring the tax program which has drawn ire from the elderly,
sharply scaling back the program in order to repeal the income
surtax, or to kill the program entirely.
   On Wednesday, the House voted pro-business on a pair of issues
generating controversy in that community.
   By a vote of 250-173, it killed a provision in the bill which
would have given workers representation on the boards of
company-financed pension plans.
   Then, by a 390-36 margin, it voted to repeal a 1986 provision
that prohibits employers from claiming tax deductions for health
plans that discriminate against lower-paid workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
