<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 1614EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Braniff-Reax Bjt   09-28 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Braniff-Reax, Bjt,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Braniff Passengers Seek Alternate Flights; Employees Ponder Fate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY JORDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAPEVINE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shocked Braniff passengers scrambled
Thursday for alternate flights while airline employees worried
about their future following the company's second filing for
bankruptcy protection in seven years.
   Only one flight was scheduled Thursday evening between Braniff
Inc.'s major Kansas City, Mo., hub and Dallas after the company
sought protection from creditors to allow it to reorganize under
Chapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code.
   ``I have flown them so often before and my daughter sent me
these tickets,'' said Marcia Mack of New York City. ``I was so
shocked. I have always enjoyed flying Braniff.''
   She was among dozens of worried passengers who waited at
Braniff's ticket counters when its concourse at Dallas-Fort Worth
International Airport opened at 6 a.m. CDT.
   In Kansas City, city convention planners were struggling to
arrange transportation for delegates from two conventions in town,
and for about 1,200 delegates expected next week for a convention
of the Society of Broadcast Engineers.
   The city may have trouble attracting future conventions if
convenient air travel is not available. Officials of other airlines
said it was too early to tell if they would increase their flights
from Kansas City International Airport.
   Meanwhile, some employees were confident that Braniff, which
laid off 2,700 workers, could rebuild as a smaller carrier.
   Braniff filed for bankruptcy protection at 2 a.m. EDT in
Orlando, its home base, only hours after it canceled flights
through Orlando and the Kansas City hub. Rumors of a bankruptcy
filing drove the airline's stock price down earlier on Wednesday.
   ``We knew there was some financial trouble. But we didn't
realize the severity of it,'' said Chuck Skinner, a Braniff agent
who went through the airline's first Chapter 11 proceeding in 1982.
``The (latest filing) really surprised us.''
   However, he predicted Braniff would return, probably as a much
smaller carrier.
   ``I am sure we will end up flying out of this one,'' said
Skinner.
   Braniff will schedule three daily flights out of Dallas
beginning Monday, ``presumably'' to Kansas City, said Al Van Klies,
one of five Braniff agents processing tickets at Dallas-Fort Worth
Airport.
   Employees hadn't yet been told about staffing at the airport.
   ``I think the older people here will still have a job,'' Van
Klies said.
   The agent, who worked at Braniff during its first
reorganization, expected that the second would be similar.
   ``Today, we're just booking people on different flights,'' he
said as he scheduled a passenger on Dallas-based American Airlines.
   Cliff Baker of Plainfield, N.J., whose ticket was honored by
American, said he and his wife Ann were returning from a three-week
vacation when Braniff unexpectedly filed for bankruptcy protection.
   ``We heard about it last night on the news. One guy at our hotel
was trying all night to get Braniff and finally did about 3 a.m.
They told us to come out and get rescheduled and we did,'' he said.
   Baker said he has been a loyal Braniff customer since 1958, when
he rode the carrier out of San Antonio, Texas, during tours at
Lackland and Brooks Air Force bases.
   ``They are a great airline,'' Baker, 49, said. ``I hope they
come back.''
   Lou Antabades of Grand Prairie, Texas, another passenger, said
he had a premonition as he bought a special Braniff ticket to watch
the fall leaves turn colors in the Rocky Mountains.
   ``When they offered the $149 round-trip fair to Denver, my first
images were the TV screens at the airport showing all flights had
been canceled, like they had during the first bankruptcy
reorganization,'' said Antabades. ``But I said, no, that won't
happen again.''
</TEXT>
