<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   09-28 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market chalked up its best gain in
five weeks Thursday in an advance led by environmental,
pharmaceutical and other ``growth'' issues.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 21.85 to
2,694.91, for its best showing since it jumped 56.53 points on Aug.
24.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 5 to 3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
918 up, 536 down and 503 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 164.24 million
shares, against 158.40 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 196.73 million shares.
   In Wednesday's trading the market was confronted with a drop in
the dollar, higher interest rates, and word from International
Business Machines that its third-quarter earnings would fall well
short of analysts' estimates.
   But stocks bounced back from an early decline to finish mixed,
impressing many observers.
   If that combination of events failed to send prices lower,
traders evidently reasoned, the market might be ready for a rally.
   The advance was ``very selective,'' however, said Larry Wachtel,
analyst at Prudential-Bache Securities. ``The theme for the day was
`out of earnings uncertainty and into earnings certainty.'''
   That meant, he said, a flow of money from technology stocks and
other sectors that have lately produced earnings disappointments,
to groups like the drug and pollution-control stocks regarded as
holding out the promise of steady growth.
   IBM shares, down 6 on Wednesday, dropped another 2{ to 109 as
the most active Big Board issue. Digital Equipment lost 1} to 91~
and Hewlett-Packard was down ~ at 50].
   In the pollution-control sector, by contrast, Waste Management,
up 2| at 65}; Wheelabrator Technologies, up 2{ at 41], and
Browning-Ferris, up 1] at 41], all hit new highs.
   Gainers among the pharmaceuticals included Abbott Laboratories,
up 1~ at 64, and Pfizer, up 1 at 68]. Investors also bid up
consumer growth issues such as Philip Morris, up 4{ at 165, and
Procter &amp; Gamble, up 3{ at 120}.
   AVX jumped 8 to 29|. The company agreed to be acquired by
Japan's Kyocera Corp. through an exchange of stock. Kyocera's
American depositary shares rose [ to 80|.
   L.A. Gear dropped 1~ to 43\. The company reported sharply higher
profits for its latest fiscal quarter, but some traders evidently
took profits on that widely anticipated news.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $29.61 billion, or
0.87 percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained 1.73 to 193.55.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose 3.93 to 397.81, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index was up 3.50 at 348.60.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market added
3.37 to 471.14. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 385.75, up 2.71.
