<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 2051EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-GrainInventories     09-28 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grain Inventories,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Corn Stockpile Half of What It Was Last Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. corn stockpile on Sept. 1 was about
1.93 billion bushels, less than half of what it was a year earlier,
according to a quarterly report released Thursday by the
Agriculture Department.
   But the Sept. 1 corn stockpile, which represented ``old crop''
grain harvested in previous years, was about 75 million bushels
more than had been forecast in USDA supply-and-demand figures
issued earlier this month.
   The old-crop soybean supply carried over on Sept. 1 into the new
marketing year and was estimated at 182 million bushels, about 27
million bushels more than forecast earlier. Even so, the Sept. 1
inventory was down 40 percent from a year earlier, the report read.
   Old crop sorghum was estimated at 438 million bushels as of
Sept. 1, about in line with the 425 million bushels forecast on
Sept. 12 but down 34 percent from inventories of a year ago.
   The marketing years for corn, soybeans and sorghum begin Sept. 1
and run through the following Aug. 31. Wheat and barley marketing
years commence on June 1.
   Wheat inventories as of Sept. 1 totaled 1.91 billion bushels,
down 15 percent from a year earlier, and barley stocks at 418
million bushels were down 7 percent.
</TEXT>
