<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     09-28 0688</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0714</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn Futures Surge On Rumored Soviet Interest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn futures prices rose sharply Thursday on the Chicago Board
of Trade, leading other grain and soybean futures higher on
speculation that the Soviet Union was shopping for up to 3 million
metric tons of U.S. corn.
   On other commodity markets, energy futures rose, precious metals
advanced slightly, and livestock and meat futures were mixed.
   Corn settled 1} cents to 5{ cents higher with the contract for
delivery in December at $2.33} a bushel. Wheat futures were \ cent
to 1 cent higher with December at $3.99{ a bushel; oats were 1\
cents to 1{ cents higher with December at $1.45} a bushel; and
soybeans were 3 cents to 6 cents higher with November at $5.70{ a
bushel.
   The rumors of buying interest conflicted with recent Soviet
statements that the Soviets would not import any more grain in
1989. But market analysts said those statements probably were a
ruse to drive prices lower.
   ``They know how to play the game,'' said Walter Spilka, a grain
analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. in New York.
   ``Ask the Soviets if they're going to buy corn, they'll say no,
the price goes down 2 cents and then they'll buy it.''
   Supporting the rumors were indications the Soviets recently
purchased grain from Canada and soybean meal from South America.
   The markets also were boosted by other grain-export news,
including confirmed sales of 106,000 metric tons of U.S. corn to
Mexico and 215,000 metric tons of U.S. corn to Japan, plus a
Chinese bid for 400,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized
prices.
   The sudden wave of foreign demand is a sharp contrast to the
slow export activity of recent weeks.
   ``Compared to last week, this is a mega-increase,'' said William
Biedermann, director of research with Allendale Inc., a futures
brokerage in Crystal Lake, Ill.
   After the close, the Agriculture Department released its
quarterly grain-stocks report, which indicated corn and soybean
supplies were larger and wheat supplies smaller than the market had
expected.
   The USDA estimated soybean stocks as of Sept. 1 at 182 million
bushels, compared to trade estimates averaging 159 million and
year-ago stocks of 302 million.
   Corn stocks as of Sept. 1 were estimated at 1.93 billion bushels
compared to trade estimates averaging 1.89 billion and year-ago
stocks of 4.26 billion.
   The USDA projected wheat stocks for June 1, 1990, at 1.91
billion bushels, essentially unchanged from a year ago, compared to
trade estimates averaging 1.99 billion.
   Energy futures prices rose on the New York Mercantile Exchange,
paced by sharp gains in the October gasoline contract linked to
position-squaring ahead of the contract's expiration on Friday.
   Some of the buying also came in reaction to OPEC's agreement to
raise its fourth-quarter crude oil production ceiling to 20.5
million barrels from 19.5 million.
   ``It seems to me that those writing OPEC off yesterday
recognized today they made a fair amount of progress in recognizing
what their objectives ought to be,'' said Robert Baker, energy
analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 7 cents to 27 cents
higher with November at $19.86 a barrel; heating oil was .38 cent
lower to .40 cent higher with October at 58.86 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .20 cent to 2.19 cents higher with October at
60.93 cents a gallon.
   Gold and silver futures edged higher on New York's Commodity
Exchange in lackluster trading.
   Gold settled 20 cents to 70 cents higher with October at $368.10
a troy ounce; silver was 1 cent to 1.5 cents higher with October at
$5.265 a troy ounce.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, live cattle futures settled
.05 cent lower to .35 cent higher with October at 72.05 cents a
pound; feeder cattle were .30 cent lower to .20 cent higher with
September at 83.05 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent lower to
.25 cent higher with October at 43.42 cents a pound; and frozen
pork bellies were unchanged to .75 cent higher with February at
48.90 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
