<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     09-28 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar moved mostly higher Thursday although
central banks again put pressure on the currency, acting on a
belief that the dollar's advance this year could have unpleasant
economic consequences.
   Gold bullion prices finished with minor changes in the United
States after moving lower overseas. The Republic National Bank of
New York quoted a bid of $366.90 for a troy ounce of gold at 4 p.m.
EDT, up 70 cents from Wednesday's late bid.
   John McCarthy, chief currency dealer at the New York office of
the Amsterdam Rotterdam Bank, said trading volume was moderate and
punctuated by rounds of central bank intervention.
   Activity has slackened in recent days with dealers unwinding
positions as the month ends. Trading maneuvers tied to the close of
Japan's fiscal year on Sept. 30 also has reduced liquidity in the
currency markets, he said.
   ``The central banks intervened three or four times,'' said
McCarthy. ``It did have the desired effect _ the dollar is closing
lower than where it opened in New York'' but above Wednesday's late
levels.
   Finance leaders of the Group of Seven industrial countries have
resolved to keep a tight leash on the dollar.
   They agreed at a weekend meeting in Washington that the dollar's
rise this year threatened to bungle the delicate balance of
economic growth among major trading partners. The G-7 countries are
the United States, Japan, West Germany, Britain, France, Canada and
Italy.
   In earlier European trading, the dollar rose against most major
currencies despite persistent dollar selling by the monetary
authorities.
   Dealers in London said they received buy orders from traders who
expressed confidence in the dollar's underlying strength.
   In earlier Tokyo trading, the dollar closed at 140.85 Japanese
yen, down from 141.35. In London late Thursday, the dollar traded
lower at 140.45 yen. It was quoted at 140.50 yen in late New York
trading, up from 140.32 yen Wednesday.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6085 late Thursday, cheaper
for buyers than Wednesday's late $1.6155. In New York a pound
fetched $1.61065 vs. $1.6167 late Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday's late rates, included: 1.88175 West German marks, up
from 1.8805; 1.6308 Swiss francs, up from 1.6305; 1.17995 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.1771; 6.376 French francs, up from 6.3655; and
1,370.50 Italian lire, up from 1,361.7.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Wednesday's
rates included: 1.8810 West German marks, down from 1.8830; 1.6310
Swiss francs, up from 1.6305; 6.3735 French francs, up from 6.3485;
2.1315 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1215; 1,369.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,359.50, and 1.1803 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1770.
   Gold bullion prices were mixed in the United States after
declining in light trading overseas.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for October
delivery rose to $368.10 a troy ounce, up 20 cents from Wednesday's
settlement. The September contract closed at $367.60 on Wednesday,
its final trading day.
   The late gold bid in London was $366.50 a troy ounce, down from
$368.00. The Zurich late bid price was $366.35, down from $368.00
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $366.45 bid, down from
$369.25.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $5.27 bid a troy ounce,
down from $5.28. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for October
delivery rose to $5.265 a troy ounce from Wednesday's settlement of
$5.252. The September contract finished Wednesday at $5.245.
</TEXT>
