<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     09-28 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices rose in moderate trading
Thursday, reflecting general optimism that OPEC's latest accord
would not mean higher oil production or weaker prices.
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries concluded a
five-day meeting on Wednesday by increasing its stated production
ceiling to 20.5 million barrels a day from 19.5 million.
   Analysts said the higher quota more accurately reflects the
demand for OPEC oil and should help maintain relatively stable
prices through the fourth quarter without raising actual production.
   ``Although there is disappointment in the outcome, people
realize that demand is still running at a high level,'' said Tom
Bentz, director of futures trading at United Energy Inc.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the November contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of crude oil, rose 27
cents to finish at $19.86 a 42-gallon barrel. The contract gained 6
cents in Wednesday's session.
   Among refined products, unleaded gasoline for October delivery
jumped 2.19 cents to close at 60.93 cents a gallon. Analysts said
last-minute buying the day before trading on the contract expires
helped boost prices. The November contract rose 1.05 cents to 57.96
cents a gallon and other contracts posted much smaller gains.
   Heating oil for October delivery rose 0.40 cent to settle at
58.86 cents a gallon, and the contract for November delivery gained
0.30 cent to 59.20 cents.
   ``The feeling in the market right now is that OPEC made strides
in trying to hammer out something. It sets a good groundwork for
the Nov. 21 meeting,'' said Linda Simard, energy broker at Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc.
   ``Crude prices should hold fairly steady between now and the
meeting,'' she said.
   OPEC is scheduled to meet in Vienna in November to map out
strategy for 1990. Observers say the oil group may be in a better
position after the current session to deal with the quota issue.
   Although OPEC raised its official ceiling, it remains under the
cartel's actual production, estimated by various industry sources
at about 22.5 million barrels a day. Analysts said they expect the
cartel to raise the figure to a more realistic level at the
November conference.
</TEXT>
