<FIRST>r f AM-KaiserPermanente     09-28 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kaiser Permanente,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big HMO To Raise Rates 17 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kaiser Permanente of Southern
California, a health maintenance organization with 2 million
members, said Thursday it will raise rates by about 17{ percent
next year.
   The monthly cost of the average individual premium will rise
from $89.90 a month to $104.99 a month, spokeswoman Janice Seib
said. Family plans with two members are twice that amount, or
$209.98; for three or more, $297.33 per month.
   Ms. Seib said tyhe increase was the largest in the last five
years. She blamed rising medical costs, the need to add doctors and
staff, big increases in membership that have strained the company,
and the fact that ``our membership is aging.''
   HMOs offer members medical care for a prepaid, fixed price,
rather than on a pay-per-visit basis.
   On Tuesday, Kaiser Permanente of Northern California said it
would hike rates 19.6 percent next year.
   Kaiser, a non-profit medical institute, is the nation's largest
HMO. It operates nine medical centers and a mental health center in
Southern California.
   James Doherty, president of the Group Health Association of
America, a Washington D.C.-based trade group for HMOs, said many of
the groups have lost money in recent years as premium increases
have failed to keep pace with the rising costs of providing service.
   A recent national survey of 650 HMOs by Group Health showed
individual premiums rose 11.8 percent and family premiums rose 11.6
percent from 1987 to 1988.
   The survey found the monthly national average for a family
contract was $226.89 in 1988 and $90.07 for an individual contract.
</TEXT>
