<FIRST>r f BC-DonnelleyChairman     09-28 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Donnelley Chairman,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walter Elected Chairman of R.R. Donnelley</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John R. Walter, president and chief executive of
R.R. Donnelley &amp; Sons Co., was elected chairman of the printing
company Thursday.
   Walter, 42, becomes one of the youngest chairmen of a Fortune
500 company. He has been with Donnelley, one of the nation's
largest printers, for 20 years.
   Walter succeeds John B. Schwemm, 55, who is retiring Nov. 1
after six years as chairman. Schwemm said in a statement the
succession was planned. He will continue to serve on the boards of
several Chicago-based companies.
   Donnelley is North America's largest printer of catalogs,
newspaper advertising inserts, magazines, books, directories,
computer documentation and financial documents.
   The company prints Business Week magazine and received national
attention earlier this year when eight of its employees resigned or
were fired in the wake of an insider-trading scandal.
   The employees were accused of supplying advance copies of the
magazine to stockbrokers and others, who then traded on companies
reported favorably in the ``Inside Wall Street'' column. Donnelley
was not charged with any wrongdoing.
