<FIRST>u f BC-HertzAds     09-28 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Hertz Ads,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hertz Drops Scali, Picks Wells Rich Greene as Ad Agency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Hertz Corp. said Thursday it has selected
Wells Rich Greene for its estimated $25 million advertising
assignment, severing its decade-long association with the agency
Scali McCabe Sloves.
   The car rental giant and its new agency provided no indication
of Hertz's plans for its long-running campaign that has featured
former pro football star O.J. Simpson and golfing great Arnold
Palmer.
   Hertz, based in Park Ridge, N.J., announced in late June that it
was reviewing its advertising assignment and said Scali would be
among four ad agencies invited to try to win the job.
   At the time, Hertz marketing and sales executive Brian Kennedy
said the Scali partnership with Hertz had produced some the best
advertising of the decade.
   But he noted that Hertz had been adding new services over the
past year and decided ``the time has come ... to re-examine how we
position the company and our services as we move forward.''
   Hertz offered no explanation Thursday for its decision to change
agencies.
   Marvin Sloves, chairman and chief executive of Scali McCabe
Sloves, said it was ``a great disappointment to lose an old
friend,'' but that the agency would look for other ways to put its
experience in the travel business to work.
   The agency's billings total about $300 million a year.
   Sloves said 30 to 40 of the agency's 400 employees worked on the
account, but that he had not yet considered whether there would be
layoffs.
   ``We are pitching two new accounts this week,'' he said, but
declined to identify them. Any wins could offset the potential
impact of the loss of Hertz.
   New York-based Scali is a unit of WPP Group PLC of London.
   Wells Rich Greene, also New York-based, has billings of about
$800 million. Its clients include International Business Machines
Corp.
