<HEAD>West German, U.S. Firms to Buy Tool Producer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emerson Electric Co. and Robert Bosch GmbH of
West Germany have agreed to buy toolmaker Vermont American Corp. of
Louisville for about $440 million, the companies announced Thursday.
   The purchase will be made by a new, as yet unnamed, corporation
that will be formed by the two companies. After the purchase, the
corporation will take the Vermont American name.
   The deal involves a cash tender offer of $40 per share for all
Vermont American shares adjustable upward to $41.
   Vermont American is a manufacturer and marketer of cutting
tools, power tool accessories, hand tools and lawn and garden
products for consumer and industrial use.
   Emerson and Bosch are major producers of power tools in the
United States and Europe. Sears, Roebuck and Co. will be a minority
investor.
   Emerson, based in St. Louis, manufactures a broad range of
electronic, electrical and other products for consumer, commercial,
industrial and government and defense markets.
   Bosch, based in Stuttgart, West Germany, manufactures electronic
automotive equipment, communications technology, consumer goods and
capital goods.
