<FIRST>r f BC-Datapoint     09-28 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Datapoint,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dissident Datapoint Shareholder Files Countersuit Against Edelman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shareholder trying to gain control
of Datapoint Corp.'s board of directors claimed Thursday that
Chairman Asher B. Edelman illegally bought stock in the computer
company to thwart the takeover attempt.
   The lawsuit, filed in Delaware Chancery Court, claims
Datapoint's Edelman-controlled board illegally changed the record
date of a solicitation order in order to give Edelman and
associates time to buy enough stock to block Martin S. Ackerman's
effort to oust the board.
   Edelman, a takeover specialist, increased his holdings in
Datapoint to more than 40 percent through stock purchases during a
two-day period shortly after Ackerman announced his plan to replace
the board.
   Ackerman claims the change in the corporate bylaw resulted in a
``breach of their corporate duties as directors, (and restricted)
stockholders from taking action by written consent for the primary
purpose of entrenching Edelman and other directors in the
management of Datapoint.''
   The suit is a response to a lawsuit filed earlier this month by
Edelman.
   Ackerman began the takeover attempt earlier this month, saying
Edelman was responsible for more than $126 million in stock
declines and losses at San Antonio-based Datapoint, which has about
$330 million in annual sales and employs about 2,600 people.
   Edelman took control of Datapoint in March 1985 and has used
some of the company's liquid capital for his other investments.
   Datapoint officials were not immediately available Thursday to
comment on the latest action.
</TEXT>
