<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 2158EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EmpireofAmerica     09-28 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Empire of America,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Struggling Savings Bank Announces Shareholder's Equity Eliminated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Empire of America Savings Bank, which has
struggled with recent operating losses, announced Thursday it has a
negative net worth and is anticipating a huge third-quarter loss.
   The savings bank said it will continue to operate normally and
that the projected losses will have no effect on the bank's
customers, employees or vendors.
   President and Chief Executive Officer Kent Dixon, while
conceding that the elimination of shareholders' equity through a
negative net worth was of ``great concern,'' said the bank would
``continue to provide the high quality of service which our
customers have come to expect.''
   In July, when the bank announced a second-quarter loss of $54.2
million, Dixon predicted that continuing losses would eat up its
common shareholders' equity by the end of this year. But in a news
release Thursday, Empire said the equity had been depleted as of
Aug. 31.
   Dixon said the bank, one of the nation's 20 largest thrifts, is
anticipating a third-quarter loss of about $150 million.
   Empire operates 142 offices in New York, Texas, California and
Michigan. It has total assets of $11 billion.
   In recent months, Empire has agreed to sell its $650 million
credit card portfolio and also said it plans to sell nearly $1
billion in auto loans it wrote though car dealers.
   In November 1986, when the bank first sold stock publicly, its
shares fetched $5.62. The stock closed Thursday at 36 cents a share.
   ``The basic definition of stockholders' equity would be the
assets of the corporation minus its liabilities,'' said analyst
Bill Ripple. ``If the liabilities exceed the assets, there is
really no stockholders equity. There's no more net worth in the
corporation. Therefore, the value of the stock is zero.''
   The bank is operating under an agreement with federal regulators
to get out of several risky lending businesses and to emphasize its
traditional home mortgage lending.
   An analyst for the First Albany Corp., Donald Kauth, estimated
this summer in a research report that Empire needed to raise $890
million by 1994 to meet federal capital requirements.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
