<FIRST>r f BC-DuPontExtortion     09-28 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Du Pont Extortion,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Pleads Innocent in Du Pont Extortion Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of three suspects set for trial in
an alleged $10 million extortion attempt of the Du Pont Co. pleaded
innocent Thursday.
   Bruno Skerianz, charged with attempted extortion and conspiracy,
entered the plea during his arraignment before U.S. Magistrate Sue
Robinson.
   Skerianz and two other suspects, who have been held at
undisclosed locations since their arrests in February, will be
tried simultaneously in federal court in early December.
   All face the same charges and if convicted, could be sentenced
to 20 years in prison and a $250,000 fine.
   Skerianz's attorney, however, plans to file for a change of
venue because he contends Skerianz cannot receive a fair trial in
Wilmington, headquarters of Du Pont.
   The federal government plans to drop charges against a fourth
suspect, Maria I. Lorenzo de Bianchini, who has agreed to testify
for the government.
   A fifth suspect, Jose Maria Petrosino, is fighting extradition
from Geneva, Switzerland.
   Skerianz and the other suspects, all Argentinian nationals, had
worked at the Du Pont plant in Mercedes, Argentina, one of several
plants that make Lycra, the company's trade name for spandex fiber.
   All of the suspects, except for Petrosino, were arrested in
February in Geneva after an aborted meeting at which Du Pont was to
pay $10 million in exchange for documents that contained trade
secrets about Lycra.
   Spandex is used primarily in clothing such as swimming suits,
leotards and pantyhose.
</TEXT>
