<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 2248EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-HawaiianAir     09-28 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Hawaiian Air,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investment Group Extends Hawaiian Air Buyout Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment group that includes former
Baseball Commissioner Peter Ueberroth has extended its tender offer
for the shares of the parent company of Hawaiian Airlines.
   Numerous unresolved issues remain in negotiations with the
airline's unions, according to a Securities and Exchange Commission
filing Wednesday by HAL Acqusition Inc., which has agreed to buy
HAL Inc.
   The filing was required to extend the offer, due to expire
Tuesday, and the wording did not mean that negotiations with the
unions had hit snags, said J. Thomas Talbot, who with Ueberroth
heads the acquisition group.
   HAL Acquisition and the unions have agreed not to make any
public statements on progress of the negotiations until they are
completed, Talbot said.
   However, the acquisition company is ``delighted'' with the
progress of the buyout bid as a whole, he said.
   HAL Acquisition has extended its $22-a-share tender offer until
after the Oct. 19 meeting of the airline's shareholders, Talbot
said.
   The buyout agreement was announced Aug. 20.
   Hawaiian Air has been plagued by losses in recent years.
</TEXT>
