<FIRST>r f BC-CeramicsMerger     09-28 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ceramics Merger,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Leading Ceramics Companies Agree to Merge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of the leading makers of ceramics used in
high-technology applications, Kyocera Corp. of Japan and AVX Corp.,
announced Thursday they have agreed to merge in a deal worth about
$531 million.
   Under the deal, all outstanding common shares of AVX will be
swapped for American depository shares of Kyocera. Each Kyocera ADS
represents two shares of the company's stock.
   The deal is believed to be the first stock-swap merger between a
U.S. and a Japanese company, The New York Tiees reported.
   Kyocera, based in Kyoto, makes ceramics for semiconductors and
other electronics applications. The company also owns 26.5 percent
of Japan's largest independent communications company, Daini-Denden.
   AVX, based on New York's Long Island, makes ceramic and glass
components used in electronics.
   The deal is subject to approval by Japanese and U.S. regulators.
   Kyocera already has a major market in this country, officials
said.
   ``There isn't a major semiconductor company in the United States
which doesn't buy from Kyocera,'' Marshall D. Butler, chairman of
AVX, told the Times.
   After the merger announcement, AVX shares closed at $29.625, up
$8, on the New York Stock Exchange. Kyocera's ADS's closed at
$80.625, up 12.5 cents.
   Officials of both companies said they hoped to expand their
markets in the United States, Japan and Europe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
