<DOCNO> AP890928-0310 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-89 2337EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-TandyComputers     09-28 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Tandy Computers,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Computer Maker to Pay for Tandy Patents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese maker of portable computers
has agreed to pay Tandy Corp. for several patents, including those
for a 4.5-pound unit that uses handwriting recognition in place of
a traditional keyboard, officials said Thursday.
   Officials at Tandy's Fort Worth headquarters said Toshiba Corp.
reached a licensing agreement with Tandy's Grid System Corp.
subsidiary on its fundamental patents for portable laptop computers.
   The most notable of the patents are those for Tandy's new
GridPad, which is the first PC designed to address applications
such as utility meter reading, census taking and inventory order
taking where data must be gathered or forms filled out while
standing or walking.
   The person using the computer enters information into it by
writing on the computer's clipboard-size screen with an electronic
pen.
   The unit operates for up to eight hours on a set of nicad or
AA-size alkaline batteries. It will carry a base price of $2,370.
   Another patent for which Toshiba will make payments covers a
feature of portable computer design that allows the computer screen
to fold over the keyboard.
   Tandy, which recorded $4.2 billion in sales in its most recent
fiscal year, did not specify the size of the payments or the terms
of the licensing agreement. However, industry analysts said the
Toshiba payments could represent millions of dollars.
   Tandy officials said the company is actively negotiating deals
with other makers of portable computers.
   At a presentation to analysts and members of the media at a
computer manufacturing plant in Fort Worth, Tandy also announced:
   _A $999 laptop computer that weighs 6.5 pounds and can operate
for five hours without recharging its battery. The Tandy 1100 FD
should be available by December. The new laptop was jointly
developed with Matsushita Electric Industrial Co. of Japan, which
began reselling Tandy desktop computers under its Panasonic brand
last year.
   The Tandy 1100 FD will compete with the popular Toshiba T1000
laptop computer. That machine has a list price of $999, but sells
for as low as $649 at discount.
   _A $350 circuit card that turns desktop personal computers into
facsimile machines. The Tandy FaxMate board permits the computers
to create, send and receive facsimile documents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
